<FIRST>r i AM-UNESCO-PLO     10-11 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UNESCO-PLO,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Recommends Delaying PLO Request Until 1991</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive board of UNESCO recommended Wednesday
that the Palestine Liberation Organization's request for admission
to the agency be put off until 1991.
   The recommendation goes to UNESCO's highest decision-making
body, the General Conference, which begins a monthlong meeting
Tuesday.
   If the conference takes the board's advice, as appears likely,
UNESCO will be following the footsteps of the World Health
Organization, which decided in May to put off considering whether
to admit Palestine.
   The PLO's parliament-in-exile from its headquarters in Tunis,
Tunisia, last Nov. 15 declared Palestine as an independent state
without giving specific boundaries.
   The United States, which withdrew from UNESCO nearly five years
ago, had said it would not consider returning if Palestine were
admitted as a member state.
   At the World Health Organization meeting in Geneva, the United
States had threatened to withhold paying its contribution to the
budget, which amounts to 25 percent.
   The resolution approved by the UNESCO board without debate or a
vote called for close involvement of the Palestinians in activities
of the 159-nation United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization.
   The Palestinian observer at UNESCO, Omar Massalha, said the PLO
decided to accept the recommendation for postponement in order to
spare the agency any political confrontation over the issue.
   UNESCO Director-General Federico Mayor has made a determined
effort to get the United States, Britain and Singapore to rejoin
the world body.
   The Americans and British left because they said the
organization had become too political, spent too much money and was
poorly managed. Singapore pulled out saying it could spend its dues
better elsewhere.
   The resolution calls for the ``closest possible participation of
Palestine in the action of UNESCO, in particular through its
programs and full benefits of the scholarship programs.''
   It says the Palestine observer mission now can make requests to
participate in UNESCO programs directly instead of going through
the Arab League as it has in the past.
   Mayor has drawn up an 82-page study for the board outlining ways
the Palestinians can become involved more closely in UNESCO
activities.
</TEXT>
