<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0744 10-11 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Blasts U.S. Government As Assembly Installed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with report that coup failed because
general changed his mind. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `She represents ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega accused
the United States on Wednesday of trying to keep its forces in
Panama to maintain control over Latin America.
   The widow of the Panamanian major who led an unsuccessful coup
against Noriega says it failed because her husband was betrayed by
another major who switched sides at the last minute, according to a
published report.
   Noriega, who blamed last week's coup attempt on the United
States, said Panama must be prepared ``because they cannot catch us
by surprise again, and even if the commander (Noriega) falls, the
people will not fall.''
   Countering what U.S. officials have been saying, Adela Bonilla
de Giroldi was quoted by the New York Times in Thursday's editions
as saying the coup was ``very well organized and coldly
calculated.''
   She said her husband, Maj. Moises Giroldi Vega, worked with Maj.
Francisco Olechea, commander of the elite Battalion 2000, in
planning the coup.
   Instead of being used to oust Noriega, however, Battalion 2000
was airlifted 55 miles from the scene of the fighting and led
Noriega's troops in crushing the coup.
   ``Everything was ready. But Olechea was playing a winner's game
and he failed to come through because of his cowardice,'' she told
the Times in an interview in Miami.
   Mrs. Giroldi was not at military headquarters during the coup
attempt on Oct. 3 and her information came from officers who took
part in the coup and, as she did, fled shortly afterwards to the
United States, the Times said.
   Noriega spoke in Panama City at the People's Power assembly.
Before he addressed the crowd, he introduced Sarah York, 11, a
Negaunee, Mich., girl on her second trip to Panama at Noriega's
invitation.
   ``She represents the truth of the American people, purity and
not hatred,'' he said as he brought his young pen pal to the podium
to wave to the crowd.
   The assembly is comprised of precinct representatives appointed
by the government to act as a legislative body. It replaces the
National Assembly, which was abolished when the provisional
government of President Francisco Rodriguez took office on Sept. 1.
   The government annulled May 7 elections, which foreign observers
say the opposition won by a 3-1 margin.
   Noriega, who commands the Defense Forces and controls the
government, said Washington's intention was not just to eliminate
him, ``but to install in power the enemies of the people.''
   Rodriguez spoke after Noriega. He called for reconciliation and
said his government was open to dialogue.
   On Tuesday, the government announced tough new measures aimed at
suppressing dissent, firing public employees considered to be
disloyal, freezing wages and suspending year-end bonuses.
   Members of the assembly demanded dismissal of ``seditious''
elements still working for the government.
   But Rodriguez, who was frequently rumored to have opposed the
laws during Cabinet meetings, said the measures should not be used
for personal revenge.
   ``The preservation of the country as our home is and must be the
paramount goal of our government,'' Rodriguez said.
   Opposition leaders and members of professional associations
expressed concern over impact of the new laws, which the government
said were meant to ``protect the economy and national security in
the face of U.S. aggression.''
   ``It is the first step in the creation of a police state,''
Christian Democratic Party leader Ricardo Arias Calderon told The
Associated Press.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said in
Washington Wednesday that Panama was decreeing a ``package of war
laws'' as part of an effort to ``eliminate the last vestiges of
democracy and rule of law.''
   Panama blames Washington for its troubles. The U.S. government
imposed economic sanctions on Panama after Noriega was indicted in
February 1988 on U.S. drug charges. He denies the charges.
   Wednesday was the 21st anniversary of the military coup that
brought to power the late Omar Torrijos, the man Noriega considers
his political and ideological mentor.
   The coup deposed President Arnulfo Arias 11 days after Arias
took office. Torrijos banned political parties, exiled scores of
politicians and ruled with the help of a People's Assembly instead
of Congress.
   Torrijos signed treaties with President Carter that committed
the United States to a new relationship with Panama.
   The United States gave up its territory in the Canal Zone in
1979. Under the treaties, the United States must close its Panama
bases at the end of the century, when Panama will take over the
Canal's administration.
</TEXT>
