<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--FakeNewspapers     10-11 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Fake Newspapers,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. Times Replaced With Phony Copies Criticizing El Salvador Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals wrapped thousands of Los Angeles
Times newspapers with fake front pages criticizing the newspaper's
coverage of U.S. involvement in El Salvador.
   The crudely fashioned cover sheets were discovered in Times
newsracks from North Hollywood to South Central Los Angeles.
   The phony front pages with a ``Los Angels Times'' masthead
included front-page stories with such headlines as ``U.S. Wages
Kinder, Gentler War in El Salvador'' and ``We Must Have Been
Asleep, Times Editors Declare.''
   Salvadoran peace activists have used similar bogus newspaper
covers in other cities, including Washington, D.C., and San
Francisco, although no one claimed responsibility for Tuesday's Los
Angeles incident.
   ``We feel the perpetrators' view of our coverage is erroneous,''
said Times Editor Shelby Coffey III. ``They are perfectly free to
have their opinions, but they are wrong in vandalizing our news
racks to express those opinions.''
</TEXT>
