<DOCNO> AP891011-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     10-11 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0902</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ex-CBS anchorman Walter Cronkite says he
misses television journalism, but has kept busy sailing and working
occasionally since retiring eight years ago.
   ``Every time there's a big breaking story, I wish I were sitting
there at the desk making decisions on how we're going to cover it,
who ought to cover it,'' said the man once considered America's
most trusted newsman.
   Cronkite was in Annapolis on Monday for a meeting of the Board
of Visitors of the University of Maryland's College of Journalism.
   Cronkite, an avid sailor, said he is still busy with work as a
special correspondent for CBS News, remains on CBS' board of
directors and has been involved with numerous projects for CBS and
the Public Broadcasting Service.
   But the part-time work fails to take the place of the hectic
day-to-day pace of broadcast journalism.
   ``Right now, the developments in Eastern Europe, gee, I'd like
be on top of that story,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rip Taylor may dress in star-spangled
jackets, wield a mean noisemaker and cover his audiences in
confetti, but he says he's also an actor.
   But Taylor hasn't managed to convince the producers of films,
television shows and commercials that he presents more than his act.
   ``When I go in for a reading they say `Where's the confetti?'''
said Taylor, who is performing at Resorts International Casino
Hotel. ``It's very hard to be taken seriously. I just want to
branch out because, you know, all the best actors are comedians.''
   Taylor was asked to play himself in ``Repossessed,'' his latest
film. The movie is a spoof of ``The Exorcist'' and stars Leslie
Nielsen and original ``Exorcist'' actress Linda Blair.
   ``I said to the director, `What's my motivation?' He said, `I
don't know. Just do what you do.' I can see I won't be getting any
awards for this one. ''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Dennis Weaver, the cowpoke-detective in
the 1970s TV series ``McCloud,'' is riding to the rescue of the
hungry.
   ``It's simple,'' Weaver said Tuesday. ``You see a problem, you
try to help fix it. There were times we were just overwhelmed with
red tape and problems, and I wanted to run and hide.
   ``It is a frightening problem.''
   Weaver, with actress Valerie Harper and others, created
L.I.F.E., or Love Is Feeding Everyone, about six years ago.
According to the county Healh Services Department, L.I.F.E. feeds
about 60,000 people each week.
   The organization collects food from store chains and delivers it
to other groups that dispense it to the needy. The program has been
so successful that Weaver and others want other cities to start
more L.I.F.E. chapters.
   ``We are one people in this country and on this planet, and
there is no use pretending that other people's hunger doesn't touch
those of us who are well fed,'' said Weaver, who won an Emmy for
portraying Chester Good in the television series ``Gunsmoke.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LEE'S SUMMIT, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old girl who once said she
wanted to sing better than Barbra Streisand has been selected to
star on Broadway in a sequel to the hit musical ``Annie.''
   Danielle Findley of Lee's Summit will play the lead role in
``Annie 2,'' a $7 million musical opening in March. She beat out
more than 400 girls who auditioned in New York, Washington, D.C.,
and Los Angeles, it was announced Tuesday in New York.
   ``This has been a lifelong dream for her,'' Danielle's mother,
Brenda Lasater, said Tuesday. ``When she was 4, she went to the
Midland Theater (in Kansas City) and saw `Annie.' She said, `I want
to be Annie someday.'''
   Danielle is described as highly motivated. Told once that she
was a good singer, she replied, ``I want to be better than Barbra
Streisand.''
   The press agent for ``Annie 2,'' David Powers, said Danielle
best met the attributes that Director Martin Charnin was looking
for: a girl with the qualities of the original Annie, Andrea
McArdle, with an ``Ethel Merman-like voice,'' acting talent, spunk,
tap-dancing ability, and no fear of dogs.
   The new production, subtitled ``Miss Hannigan's Revenge,'' goes
into rehearsal next month and begins an out-of-town tryout Dec. 22
at Washington's Kennedy Center. It opens March 1 at the Marquis
Theatre in New York after several weeks of previews.
   This will not be Danielle's first Broadway appearance. When she
was 8 she spent seven months appearing in ``Coastal Disturbances,''
playing one of several children vacationing at a New England beach.
   Danielle, a student at Pleasant Lea Elementary School in Lee's
Summit, starred in a production of ``Annie'' at Kansas City's
Starlight Theater in July.
   She began performing in Kansas City area talent competitions
when she was 5. She has taken voice, acting and flute instruction
and studied jazz, tap and ballet dancing.
   The original ``Annie'' was a Broadway smash, opening in April
1977 and running for 2,377 performances.
   In the sequel, the lead character's dog, Sandy, is being
replaced by a mixed-breed named Beau, who was adopted at a tender
age by trainer Bill Berloni. Berloni trained the original Sandy,
who is now 16 or 17 ``and quite arthritic,'' said Powers.
</TEXT>
