<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WhiteHouseTapes     10-11 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-White House Tapes,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Research Groups Say Government Would Put President Above Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private researchers charge the White House
with wholesale violations of federal record-keeping laws and say
their suit to block destruction of Reagan administration computer
tapes would not hamstring President Bush in performing his duties.
   Lawyers for several research groups filed their response Tuesday
to a Justice Department move in a case that could decide whether
the White House can routinely destroy the kind of computer messages
that were discovered in the Iran-Contra affair.
   After a chance for government lawyers to answer the new
arguments, U.S. District Judge Charles Richey will decide whether
to proceed with the case or allow it to go directly to the Court of
Appeals as the government wants.
   Richey ruled on Sept. 15 that the private organizations may sue
the president to block erasure of the tapes.
   Lawyers for the National Security Archive and other
organizations claim the Bush administration is trying to avoid
responding to inquiries that will reveal ``wholesale violations of
the Presidential Records Act and the other federal records laws
through the routine destruction of information.''
   The case involves 12 days of tapes generated on the Professional
Office System, known as PROFS, used in the Executive Office of the
President.
   On Jan. 18, two days before he left office, President Ronald
Reagan instructed staff members to erase their computer message
systems. The next day, the organizations filed suit to require the
White House to preserve backup tapes that stored these messages in
a computer bank.
   The tapes have since been preserved under a temporary
restraining order issued in January by U.S. District Judge
Barrington Parker.
   The Justice Department asked on Sept. 27 that the case be
shunted directly to the U.S. Court of Appeals, partly because it
involved ``a threat to the president's authority.''
   The organizations that filed suit denied ``such dire
consequences'' are involved. They argued that Richey's Sept. 15
order does not interfere with the president's ability to do his
duties.
   Instead, they said, the Justice Department is apparently trying
to assure the president of ``authority to make unilateral (and
unreviewable) decisions to destroy the PROFS information,
regardless of whether it falls within the definition of
`presidential records' that Congress has mandated must be preserved
for the benefit of future generations.''
   The National Security Archive, a Washington nonprofit group that
researches national security issues, filed the suit along with the
American Library Association, the American Historical Association
and the Center for National Security Studies of the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   The PROFS messages played an important role in the congressional
investigation of the Iran-Contra affair during Reagan's
admninistration.
   Oliver L. North, the White House aide at the center of the
affair, frequently sent PROFS messages to his superiors. In
November 1986, he tried to erase them, but he did not know they
were automatically being stored on magnetic tape in the central
computer bank. By using these tapes, the congressional committees
investigating the affair were able to reconstruct much of the
information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BattleBattle Bjt   10-11 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Battle Battle, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle of Words: Where Did the Revolution Begin?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT PLEASANT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guns, knives and tomahawks were the
tools of war 215 years ago when the Battle of Point Pleasant raged
on a narrow strip of land where the Kanawha and Ohio rivers meet.
   Now, words and history books serve as the weapons.
   Point Pleasant claims that it, not Lexington, Mass., was the
site of the first battle of the American Revolution.
   Historians and geographers acknowledge that the battle _ known
as Lord Dunmore's War _ is important, but for other reasons.
   ``They came out this way to solve an Indian problem _ the
uprising of the Shawnee,'' said Alan Gould, a former history
professor and now Marshall University's provost. ``It can be
extremely difficult to say it's the first battle of the
Revolution.''
   But that's what Point Pleasant residents celebrated Tuesday, the
anniversary of the battle.
   Before the battle, the Virginia armies marched to invade the
Indian country. Four days later a 1,000-man division under Gen.
Andrew Lewis was attacked by about 1,000 Indians led by Chief
Cornstalk. Finally, after a nearly daylong battle, the Indians
retreated, leaving 33 dead. The Virginians had 60 killed and 96
wounded.
   The victory resulted in a treaty on terms dictated by Dunmore,
the Colonial governor.
   ``Congress has declared this a battle of the Revolution and in a
chronological list of the battles, this is the first,'' said
Bradley Reed, superintendent of the Point Pleasant Battle Monument
State Park.
   According to records at the National Society of the Sons of the
American Revolution in Louisville, Ky., Congress on Feb. 17, 1908,
passed a resolution recognizing the Battle of Point Pleasant as a
fight in the American Revolution and appropriated money for a
monument dedicated Oct. 10, 1909 _ the battle's 135th anniversary.
   Consequently, both the Sons and Daughters of the American
Revolution accept descendants from the battle as members.
   ``It's annoying that this should have to be covered up,'' said
Donald J. Pennell of Birmingham, Mich., a past historian general
for the SAR. ``We're fighting New England's hold on history. That
group has been mighty tight with history.''
   Pennell said he grew up believing that the Revolution began in
Lexington on April 19, 1775 _ six months after Point Pleasant. He
changed his mind after meeting a West Virginian who mentioned the
battle, its significance and the congressional resolution.
   ``We need a nationally recognized historian to look at this and
say, `Yea' or `Nay.' And you have to get someone away from the
Boston area,'' Pennell said. ``Nobody has ever refuted publicly the
statement in this congressional record that this is the first
battle of the Revolution.''
   Gould agrees the battle should be recognized by Congress, but
not as a Revolutionary fight.
   ``We can say that the events that precipitated the Battle of
Point Pleasant had little to do with colonial grievances against
the crown,'' Gould said. ``The impact was that it kept the Shawnees
quiet for a while when the first shots were fired in Lexington and
Concord.
   ``I don't think anyone fighting in the battle saw it as a
rebellion against the crown.''
   In 1903, the Ohio Archaeological and Historical Quarterly called
Point Pleasant the first Revolutionary fight because Dunmore put
the Indians up to it to create two battlefronts for the colonists.
   Gould said Dunmore was a loyalist but doubted whether he staged
the fight.
   Although Point Pleasant claims the first battle of the
Revolution, the historian at the Minute Men National Historical
Park in Concord, Mass., says he never heard of the conflict.
   ``I think they're reaching,'' historian Doug Sabin said.
``People often do that with historical firsts.
   Congress' resolution 81 years ago should have recognized Point
Pleasant's significance in the United States' western expansion,
said Sam Clagg, Marshall's professor emeritus in geography and the
author of West Virginia's section in the Encyclopaedia Britannica.
   ``It was significant in breaking the Indian stronghold in the
West,'' Clagg said. ``It established that we were willing to make a
stand on this side of the mountains.''
   Treaties that ended hostilities in the late 1700s gave the new
country rights to lands as far west as the Mississippi largely
because of the victory at Point Pleasant, Gould said.
   Without the victory, he said, the United States would have been
granted lands only as west as the Alleghenies, leaving everything
beyond to France and Spain.
   ``I think they might be celebrating the wrong thing,'' Gould
said. ``They ought to be celebrating the significance of that
victory in American history, and that's that it secured the
frontier.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MCI-AT&amp;TSuit     10-11 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCI-AT&amp;T Suit,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Companies Take Their Ad Battle to the Courtroom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. is asking a federal
court to force American Telephone &amp; Telegraph's ``deceptive'' ads
off the air, even though MCI claims it is taking 100,000 customers
a week away from its rival.
   MCI Chairman William McGowan said Tuesday that MCI filed suit
because AT&amp;T is using false and deceptive ads comparing the two
long-distance phone services in a ``desperate'' attempt to stem the
loss of customers.
   ``They are panicking about it,'' McGowan said.
   AT&amp;T's market share has fallen to 75 percent since MCI broke the
old Bell System's monopoly on U.S. phone service in the 1970s.
MCI's share now is more than 10 percent.
   McGowan said MCI research showed AT&amp;T is losing even more than
100,000 customers a week, but MCI's marketing department, which has
been trumpeting that number in its own ads, ``likes round numbers.''
   But, he said, MCI is suffering substantial financial losses even
as it takes away AT&amp;T customers.
   The MCI lawsuit in U.S. District Court, the latest in a long
string of dustups between the nation's two leading long-distance
companies, charges AT&amp;T made false comparisons between its service
and MCI's Primetime, cut-rate long-distance calling plan.
   MCI complains about AT&amp;T ads that say MCI's rates are cheaper
only when brief calls are made over 900 miles away and after 7 p.m.
and that MCI customers ``might have had better luck calling Mars''
than trying to reach MCI for an explanation of their bills.
   AT&amp;T ``maliciously attacked MCI's honesty and the value of MCI's
competing services by falsely and deceptively representing that
AT&amp;T was superior to its competitors in general, and MCI in
particular, in terms of trustworthiness, quality and price,'' the
suit said.
   MCI itself is known for aggressive advertising, such as showing
people fainting when they see their non-MCI long-distance phone
bills. But McGowan said MCI now is being outspent 8-to-1 by AT&amp;T in
advertising.
   He said he could not estimate the losses MCI had suffered as a
result of AT&amp;T ads, but he said ``it's substantial.''
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said, ``We welcome the opportunity to
discuss who is misleading whom and will do so in a countersuit. ...
We have been concerned about MCI's sometimes misleading print and
broadcast advertising and have complained about it directly to
MCI.''
   He said AT&amp;T attorneys sent a letter to ABC, CBS, NBC and CNN
this month complaining that MCI was stretching facts in ads that
claim ``MCI always saves you money over AT&amp;T, month after month''
and that every week 100,000 AT&amp;T customers switch to MCI.
   AT&amp;T said the ads are false and asked the networks to stop
running them.
   Linnen said ABC and CBS had replied that they would look into
the matter, but NBC and CNN had not yet responded to the letter.
   ``AT&amp;T stands behind its advertising,'' Linnen added.
   MCI complains in its suit about AT&amp;T statements that non-AT&amp;T
companies provide slow telephone connections, that other companies
don't operate worldwide like AT&amp;T and that competing 800, facsimile
and WATS services are inferior.
   The suit asks the court to stop AT&amp;T ``from making false or
deceptive representations that any AT&amp;T service is materially
superior to any competing MCI service in terms of quality or lower
cost, or that MCI has misrepresented its services or rates to
consumers.''
   It also asks a judge to force AT&amp;T to stop advertising for 12
months unless ``such information clearly and conspicuously
discloses a court-approved corrective notice that mitigates the
lingering effects of the misrepresentations described therein.''
   MCI also wants the profits ``wrongfully amassed by AT&amp;T on the
sale of its products or services during the period in question,''
plus interest and legal fees. The suit does not put a price on
those profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
