<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Norville-PhilipMorris     10-11 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Norville-Philip Morris,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC's Deborah Norville Says She Didn't Violate News Guidlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC news anchor Deborah Norville says her taping
of non-broadcast ``interviews'' of business executives during a
paid appearance in February didn't violate the network's news
guidelines.
   ``My understanding was that I would be interviewing some
marketing people, which I did do,'' Norville said Tuesday of the
appearance at a Philip Morris corporate sales presentation in
Hawaii.
   Norville, whose moonlighting at the conference first was
reported in this week's Newsweek magazine, said the interviews
weren't done for NBC and simply were part of the conference.
   ``But the format was more involved than that, as I discovered
when I got there,'' she said. She said she hadn't expected the
format prepared for her might put her in a position of seeming to
endorse some products.
   When she realized there was a problem, she said in a phone
interview, she tried to make the best of ``an awkward situation.''
   ``I rewrote everything they had prepared for me to say,'' she
said. ``I just said, `Look, I can't say these things.' And I made a
point of rewriting everything so that nothing I said could be
construed as an endorsement.''
   In retrospect, the network would not have let her appear at the
sales conference, said NBC News president Michael Gartner.
   ``None of us understood the format (of her engagement) until it
was too late,'' he said.
   ``Had we understood what was involved or expected of Deborah, we
would not have done it. And clearly it's something we wouldn't do
again,'' he said in a prepared response to a query about the paid
appearance she cited.
   Norville, who since Sept. 5 has been news anchor of the
``Today'' show, was anchor of ``NBC News at Sunrise'' when she got
the invitation to appear at the sales meeting. She was given
permission to accept by Gerry Solomon, then executive producer of
``Sunrise.''
   NBC News guidelines say that staff members considering
invitations to speak, lecture or make personal appearances ``should
use their judgment to avoid being placed in a situation in which
they may be used for any purpose.''
   Norville, who declined to say how much she was paid, said she ``
certainly didn't accept the engagement with any thought that I
would be violating any guidelines, and I don't believe that I did.''
   However, she conceded, ``it was a difficult situation. And I was
there, and I had to be as graceful about it as I could, yet try to
be mindful of what my responsibility as a journalist is. It was a
difficult rope to walk and I tried to walk it as best as I could.''
</TEXT>
