<FIRST>r w PM-Shrimpers-Fines     10-11 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shrimpers-Fines,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Starting Monday, Shrimpers Not Using Turtle Devices Face Stiff Fines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf Coast shrimpers are looking to President
Bush for a last-minute reprieve from regulations they claim will
cost them nearly a third of their income.
   Unless Bush intervenes, shrimp fishermen will face stiff fines
next week if they are caught without devices in their nets that
prevent the drowning of endangered sea turtles.
   The Texas Shrimp Association predicts quiet compliance with the
law, but executive director Ralph Rayburn also says shrimpers could
lose up to 30 percent of their catch at a time when earnings are
banked to get them through the non-productive winter months.
   Congressmen from the Gulf Coast say shrimping is an endangered
industry that cannot afford to use the turtle excluder devices, or
TEDs.
   ``You're beginning to see less shrimpers than less turtles,''
says Rep. Solomon Ortiz, D-Texas, who has watched the number of
shrimp-industry employees in Port Isabel, Texas, fall from nearly
3,000 to fewer than 400 in six years.
   Ortiz and Rep. Billy Tauzin, D-La., say fuel and insurance costs
for the shrimpers have been mounting as prices have been driven
down by shrimp imports, which now account for 75 percent of U.S.
consumption.
   Although shrimpers have been required to use TEDs since Sept. 8,
the federal government has forgiven the penalties _ at first in
whole and later in part _ if a shrimper bought and installed a TED.
   Sunday, however, is the last day for such reprieves. On Monday a
shrimper found in violation of the law faces an $8,000 fine. A
second offense could result in a $15,000 fine and a third offense
could cost $15,000 and the confiscation of the shrimper's vessel,
catch, or both.
   That's unless Bush, who agreed to review the matter, intervenes
in the long-fought battle between environmentalists and shrimpers
over the use of TEDs.
   The issue is now before John Sununu, the White House chief of
staff, said Tauzin.
   Tauzin says he's expecting penalties and angry shrimpers if the
law isn't modified, but hopes there won't be a repeat of earlier
blockades of Gulf Coast shipping channels by protesting shrimp
fishermen.
   Tauzin believes shrimpers could lose up to 50 percent of their
catch as crews inexperienced with the devices search for
ever-scarcer shrimp. A 10 percent loss in catch is enough to put
some shrimpers out of business, he said.
   Government scientists have found losses from TEDs can range from
5 percent to 10 percent, or even less, but those demonstrations
were conducted with crews experienced in using TEDs, Rayburn says.
   Conservationists argue shrimping is the single greatest cause of
turtle mortality and that TEDs are the best prevention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
