<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     10-11 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Leaders See Gramm-Rudman Cuts Coming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders believe their dispute
over the capital gains tax cut pushed by President Bush is
virtually certain to trigger the Gramm-Rudman law's automatic
spending cuts next week.
   Their assessment came Tuesday after House and Senate leaders of
both parties failed again to unravel their differences over the
proposed capital gains tax reduction.
   The argument has delayed Senate debate on a related $14 billion
deficit-cutting bill. Unless that legislation is passed by Monday,
automatic cuts in many defense and domestic programs _ expected to
total about $16 billion _ will take effect.
   ``You're not going to avoid'' the cutbacks, Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said after a nearly two-hour private
session. ``I think we're all pretty much in agreement on that.''
   Dole met in the Capitol with Senate Democratic Leader George
Mitchell of Maine, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and
House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill.
   Mitchell said he believed the chances of avoiding the
Gramm-Rudman reductions are ``extremely remote.''
   The air of defeat has arisen because of the complicated dispute
that has tied up congressional leaders for the past week.
   Republican senators are preparing to force the chamber to vote
on a plan to lower the capital gains tax in an effort to honor
Bush's campaign pledge for a cut in the rate. Bush says a rate cut
will stimulate economic activity and boost federal revenues.
   Democratic leaders oppose the idea, arguing it would cost the
government billions of dollars in the long run.
   But the Democratic leadership is on the defensive, realizing
that most senators favor some capital gains reduction, and so they
are trying to reach an agreement with the GOP that would prevent a
capital gains amendment _ and other controversial issues _ from
being added to the deficit-reduction bill.
   Attaching capital gains language to the budget bill _ considered
an urgent, must-pass measure _ would greatly increase prospects for
a cut in the tax rate.
   Each party has been seeking parliamentary arrangements for
voting that would give them procedural advantages in any floor
votes.
   The House also complicated matters last week when it approved an
$11 billion deficit-slashing bill of its own. That measure included
a two-year capital gains cut, a shrinkage of Medicare benefits for
extremely ill elderly patients, an expansion of federal day care
programs and other initiatives.
   Working out a way to pare those items from the legislation _ and
for the House and Senate to agree to a compromise bill _ makes it
all but impossible to finish the task by next Monday, leaders
concede.
   ``The time to have stripped the bill down ... was before we
enacted it,'' Foley told reporters.
   The Gramm-Rudman cuts will be triggered Monday if the projected
deficit for the 1990 fiscal year, which began Oct. 1, is not below
$110 billion.
   The Congressional Budget Office projected Tuesday that the
shortfall will be $141.3 billion. This would call for cuts of $41.3
billion, divided evenly between defense and domestic programs.
   The CBO projections, however, are merely advisory. The White
House's Office of Management and Budget issues its binding
projections Monday. They are expected to require about $16 billion
in cuts, divided equally between defense and domestic programs.
   Congress, as it has done in the past, could undo any cuts with
future legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
