<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Condoms     10-11 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Condoms,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condom Vending Machines Starting to Appear in High Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All dollar figures Canadian.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One Canadian school district is selling condoms
in high school bathrooms and another will start soon in programs
health experts hope will help guard against unwanted pregnancies,
AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases.
   ``They've been installed for two or three weeks,'' says Loretta
Nichols, chairman of the Qualicum School Board of Trustees in
British Columbia. ``There's been absolutely no vandalism ...
There's been much less concern among the students than there is
among the adults.''
   Qualicum, a semi-rural district on Vancouver Island, placed the
condom vending machines in one boys and one girlrs room in each of
its two secondary schools, which some 1,100 students attend.
   ``We've had excellent family-life programs in place prior to
this,'' Mrs. Nichols said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
   The Toronto school board voted 15-3 recently to install condom
vending machines in its 38 secondary schools in a program that
could begin by Christmas.
   Students in Toronto are being taught that the best method for
preventing AIDS is abstention but that condoms can cut the risk
significantly.
   The decision was made after Dr. Perry Kendall, Toronto's medical
health officer, reported 47 known positive tests for the AIDS virus
among local teen-agers between the ages of 15 and 19. He estimated
that there may be as many as nine more positive tests for each one
known.
   Jim Brown, spokesman for the U.S. Public Health Service in
Washington, D.C., said he knew of no high schools in the United
States that provide condom-dispensing machines.
   ``You would have problems in the local communities, etc.,
etc.,'' he said by telephone.
   Mrs. Nichols said the decision in Qualicum was made strictly for
health reasons, without being aware the district would be
considered in the vanguard.
   ``We had no idea whether it was done anywhere else in Canada,
and it really didn't concern us,'' she said. ``The board approached
the situation on the basis of health prevention and left the moral
aspect completely aside.''
   The vote was 6 to 1 in favor.
   A major factor was that area pharmacies close at 6 p.m. so young
people might find it difficult to purchase condoms, Mrs. Nichols
said, while life in a small town also might discourage them.
   ``Because we're a small area, it's difficult for a student to go
in to a drugstore and be anonymous,'' she said.
   The machines that sell condoms for 50 cents each (43 cents U.S.)
were installed by a supplier on a four-month trial basis.
   The Toronto district plans to purchase machines for $200 each,
then sell condoms it buys for 18 cents each at a
yet-to-be-determined price. Educational programs are planned for
students, teachers and parents before the machines are installed.
   ``None of us has ignored or downplayed the distress with which
some parents will receive this plan,'' Kendall said during the
debate. ``Yet in this instance, the harm of not acting far
outweighs potential censure.''
   He said that teen-agers consider themselves immune to the
possibility of getting pregnant or contracting a disease.
   Canada had reported 3,040 AIDS cases as of Tuesday.
   ``Encouraging students to buy condoms will not end the misery of
unwanted teenage pregnancies, of the transmittal of sexual
diseases, of teenage abortions,'' Toronto's Globe and Mail
newspaper said in an editorial. ``It will reduce the numbers,
however.
   ``By addressing the issue openly, schools may give some
teen-agers the strength to make protection an issue when
considering sexual intercourse, and the knowledge that at least one
form of protection is readily available,'' it said.
   The decision on condom machines is up to local school boards.
The Scarborough School Board, which has 24 secondary schools in
Toronto's eastern suburban area, decided against installing the
machines.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   The scientific name for the virus is human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV.
</TEXT>
