<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich     10-11 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Ethics Committee Delaying Decision on Gingrich</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressmen who filed an ethics complaint
against House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich says the House ethics
committee is delaying a decision on whether to investigate
Gingrich's financial dealings.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., complained in a letter to the
committee that a Chicago law firm hired to recommend whether an
investigation should begin has not interviewed many witnesses who
are willing to testify against Gingrich.
   Alexander said Tuesday he had retained his own attorney to
review the committee's progress following his complaint that
Gingrich, a Georgia Republican, may have violated House rules and
campaign finance laws.
   But, he wrote the committee, it was easier to find evidence
supporting his allegations than to find evidence of an
investigative effort by the committee-hired firm.
   The ethics committee _ formally the Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct _ hired Phelan, Pope and John Ltd., the firm that
served as the panel's special counsel in the case against former
Speaker Jim Wright. Wright resigned from Congress in June after the
committee charged him with 69 rules violations.
   Alexander filed an ethics complaint against Gingrich April 11
and amended the document on July 14, but said he has received no
response from the committee.
   The committee denied Alexander's request for information on the
Phelan firm's progress, writing him that House rules prohibit
disclosure of the information.
   The complaint said Gingrich may have violated campaign finance
laws, House limits on outside income and a House rule preventing
acceptance of gifts from those with a direct interest in
legislation.
   Many of the allegations center on Gingrich's formation of a
partnership, including political supporters, to promote the 1984
book he co-authored, ``Window of Opportunity.'' There also were
questions about the use of Gingrich staffers to work on the book.
   Gingrich has denied any violations, although he said last month
that his congressional staff did clerical work on the book. He said
House rules permit such activity as long as the book deals with a
public policy issue, and the staffers work at least 40 hours a week
on congressional duties.
</TEXT>
