<FIRST>r w PM-IowaSkipper     10-11 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Skipper,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battleship Captain Complains of Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of the USS Iowa says the Navy
staffed his ship with ``dopers, marginal performers'' and other
low-quality sailors who had been kicked off other ships, according
to a published report.
   Capt. Fred P. Moosally complained to the officer investigating
the turret explosion that killed 47 sailors in April that he
believed the ship was ``kind of out of it'' when he took over
command in May 1988.
   The Navy, however, said the Iowa's crew was no worse than any
other ship's crew.
   ``I think the battleship has not been properly taken care of as
far as manning goes in the wardroom (the officers on a warship) or
the enlisted area,'' Moosally told Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, the
chief investigator of the Iowa explosion.
   Moosally said some of the sailors sent to the ship were
``dopers, marginal performers, constant UAs (unauthorized
absences).''
   A transcript of the captain's remarks in the May interview was
obtained by the Navy Times, which published them in its Oct. 9
edition.
   The Navy said its investigation concluded the explosion in the
gun turret was probably detonated on purpose by a suicidal sailor
who was upset at the breakup of a friendship with one sailor and at
another shipmate's rejection of his homosexual advances.
   Milligan asked Moosally why he let sailors with criminal records
and disciplinary problems handle ammunition in violation of Navy
regulations.
   Moosally said he would be hard-pressed ``if I was to disqualify
all the guys I've got on (Iowa) that have problems.''
   ``I've got guys that were kicked out of submarines, kicked out
of SPs (shore patrol) that I've got as gunner's mates,'' the
captain said. ``That's what the Navy sends me.''
   The Navy denied that low-quality sailors and officers were
assigned to the ship.
   The four battleships in the Navy ``get their fair share of the
best and worst,'' Lt. Cmdr. Craig Quigley, a Navy spokesman, told
the newspaper.
   Adm. L.A. Edney, vice chief of naval operations, wrote in the
Oct. 16 edition of Navy Times that Moosally's remarks were taken
out of context.
   ``The questioning took place quite soon after the tragedy while
both the captain and the Navy were searching their minds for
possible causes and while the grief he suffered could best be
described as an open wound,'' Edney wrote.
   Earlier this month the Navy gave Moosally a letter of caution
for violations of training and other regulations that were found
during the investigation of the explosion. These violations, the
Navy said, had nothing to do with the explosion.
</TEXT>
