<FIRST>r w PM-StarsandStripes     10-11 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stars and Stripes,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0460 to change cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pentagon Spokesman: Decision Not Made On Editors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pentagon spokesman says a decision on
whether to replace military editors at the armed forces newspaper
Stars and Stripes with civilians won't be made until an ombudsman
submits a report on the question.
   The comment by Pete Williams came a day after he told reporters
Monday, ``When the current military editors retire, it is our
intention to put civilians in there.''
   But Williams said at a Pentagon briefing Tuesday, ``I'm not
denying anything that I said yesterday. I'm just saying that we do
have an ombudsman and it would be well for me to let him make his
recommendations first.''
   The decision to switch from military to civilian editors would
comply with a recommendation in a report last year by the General
Accounting Office.
   The GAO, assisted by the Society of Professional Journalists,
reported that it found evidence of censorship and improper
management at the government-run daily.
   The GAO recommended the editor-in-chief be a civilian with solid
journalism credentials, rather than a military officer.
   Williams' earlier statement had been warmly greeted by those who
have been pressing for such a change, but it apparently caught the
ombudsman _ former Washington Post editor Philip M. Foisie _ off
guard.
   Foisie, reached in Tokyo, said Williams had ``misspoke.''
   ``I think he got confused,'' Foisie said. ``I'm doing a study. I
haven't made any report yet. A decision of the kind mentioned by
Mr. Williams would not be made until my report.''
   Foisie, who was appointed last summer to help deal with the
allegations of censorship, has been in the Far East for more than
two weeks, visiting bureaus of the overseas paper and investigating
its problems.
   Williams said that even if the changes occur, ``I anticipate
that there will always be a military commander of the newspaper.
Now, how you divide up editorial responsibilities is something that
we're asking Mr. Foisie to advise us on.''
   Although frequently referred to as one newspaper, the Stars and
Stripes is published in two separate editions by largely autonomous
bureaus in West Germany and Japan.
</TEXT>
