<FIRST>r a PM-ChainsawCuts     10-11 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chainsaw Cuts,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Chainsaw Massacre III' Edited After X-Rating</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producers of the blood and gore sequel
``Leatherface: The Texas Chainsaw Massacre III'' hope to chop off
its X rating in the editing room and turn it into an R-rated
massacre.
   New Line Cinema will resubmit the film Oct. 17 in an effort to
win the less restrictive rating from the Motion Picture Association
of America's Classification &amp; Rating Administration.
   ``Some adjustments have been made. They aren't major, but you
just sort of have to play around with the material,'' a studio
executive said Tuesday on condition of anonymity.
   ``Chainsaw III'' follows a young teen-age couple driving through
Texas and their encounter with a cannibalistic clan and an eventual
path to hell.
   New Line planned to release the slaughterfest starring Kate
Hodge and William Butler on Nov. 3.
   The New York-based motion picture association, which issues
movie ratings as a guideline to parents, doesn't discuss reasons
for its ratings decisions or comment on what scene or scenes are
deemed objectionable.
   An R rating lets those under age 17 to see the film if
accompanied by an adult. Only adults are allowed in for movies
rated X, the most restrictive audience category and deemed a
financial death sentence for mainstream movies.
   ``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre'' was released in 1974 by
Bryanston Pictures and was rated R. ``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre
2'' wasn't submitted to the association for a rating when it was
released in 1986 by Cannon.
</TEXT>
