<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-11 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground against the Japanese yen
Wednesday despite the Bank of Japan's raising of its discount rate,
while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged.
   The Nikkei Stock Exchange lost 136.28 points, or 0.39 percent,
ending at 35,240.07 points. It had gained 167.00 points Monday.
Stock and foreign currency markets were closed Tuesday for a
national holiday.
   Stock dealers attributed the index's fall to the yen's sharp
decline in earlier trading, as well as the central bank's discount
rate hike.
   The dollar, which opened higher at 144.90 yen, ended at 143.90
yen, up 1.67 yen from Monday's close of 142.23 yen. It moved
between 142.55 yen and 144.95 yen.
   The U.S. currency started to fall in earlier trading after
rumors the Bank of Japan might raise its discount rate, traders
said.
   The Bank of Japan raised its official discount rate by 0.5
percent to 3.75 percent shortly after the morning markets closed
Wednesday, central bank officials confirmed.
   The new rate became effective as soon as it was announced at
12:45 p.m., a bank official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   This was the second increase in the key lending rate this year.
The previous hike went into effect May 30, bringing the rate to
3.25 percent, to stem inflation and strengthen the yen, which has
fallen against the dollar in recent months.
   ``The decision came in consideration of recent currency market
fluctuations, movements in foreign interest rates, domestic
economic trends, consumer prices and the money supply,'' the
central bank said in a statement released after its announcement
Wednesday.
   ``The Bank of Japan hopes the rate hike will stabilize consumer
prices and encourage the continued growth of domestic demand,'' the
statement said.
   Expected increases in interest rates on savings accounts at
banks had not yet been determined, the official added. The rate is
currently at 0.26 percent.
</TEXT>
