<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-11 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds AID's Abortion Restriction Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has upheld the
constitutionality of an Agency for International Development policy
that denies financial aid to private groups supporting abortions in
foreign countries.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled Tuesday against constitutional
challenges filed by three family planning organizations, two
foreign and one based in the United States, that had sued AID in
1985 challenging the policy.
   The Reagan administration decided in 1984 that it would no
longer contribute to non-government organizations which perform or
promote abortion as a method of family planning in other nations.
   In 1988, U.S. District Court Judge June Green ruled that the
policy violated the constitutional right of the U.S.-based group,
DKT Memorial Fund Ltd., to associate with the foreign
organizations, based in New Delhi, India, and London.
   The appeals panel reversed Green in a 2-1 decision, while
upholding other portions of her decision favorable to AID.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>US Says It Seems Likely Soviet Advisers Still Involved in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House says the Soviet Union is still
providing ``vast amounts'' of weapons to the Afghanistan
government, and it seems likely that Soviet advisers are still
involved in the fighting.
   The New York Times reported Tuesday that a confidential Bush
administration intelligence report said Soviet advisers wearing
Afghan uniforms were launching Scud missiles at rebels.
   ``It seems a likely conclusion, but I cannot be more specific,''
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said about Soviet
involvement.
   ``Our position is still the same, that the Soviets are supplying
vast amounts of weapons and money and support to the Afghanistan
government and we similarly are staying involved on that basis. But
I can't get into people and so forth.''
   Moscow has said its last troops were withdrawn from Afghanistan
in February.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Safety Regulations for Microwave Packaging Considered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heat-sensitive food packaging materials
designed for microwave cooking will be evaluated by the Food and
Drug Administration for potential new safety regulations.
   The FDA said Tuesday it is asking for information about heat
susceptors, metalized surfaces in the packages of food intended for
microwave cooking. These heat susceptors absorb microwave energy
and become very hot, allowing the food to become brown and crisp.
   Because the susceptors become so hot, the FDA said it is
concerned that other parts of the package, including adhesives,
polymers, paper and components of plastic films, may migrate into
the food at high levels.
</TEXT>
