<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens 1stLd-Writethru a0422 10-11 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0422,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Lands Seven in Top 10, But NBC Holds Lead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `Also during ...' to CORRECT Chung to tied for
68th sted 70th.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC had seven of network television's top 10
programs last week but NBC narrowly rode ``The Cosby Show'' and the
baseball playoffs into first place in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings.
   ABC finished within 0.8 point of NBC, and its ``Roseanne'' was
the highest rated program of the week.
   ABC has the contract to carry the World Series between the
Oakland Athletics and San Francisco Giants.
   The last such regional contest in 1985, between the Kansas City
Royals and St. Louis Cardinals, went seven games and was a ratings
winner for ABC. But the A's-Giants contest has the disadvantage of
being on the West Coast.
   That means all the games will have to start two hours before
prime time, at 5 p.m. in their respective cities, so East Coast
viewers can catch the first pitch at 8 p.m.
   ``This World Series is not a regional matchup,'' insisted Jack
O'Hara, ABC's director of sports programming. ``The two teams are
national attractions with very recognizable superstars.''
   ``If ABC called us up and said, `Hey, we don't like this
Oakland-Giants matchup,' we'd take it,'' said Preston Beckman,
NBC's vice president of sports audience research.
   NBC led the three networks for the 68th consecutive week, with
an average rating of 15.2 to ABC's 14.4 and CBS' 12.5.
   The ratings are the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million
homes with television sets in the United States.
   Here are last week's top 10 shows: ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``The
Cosby Show,'' NBC; ``The Wonder Years,'' ABC; ``NBC Monday Night at
the Movies: ``A Cry for Help: The Tracy Thurman Story''; ``Who's
the Boss?'' ABC; ``NFL Monday Night Football, Philadelphia vs.
Chicago,'' ABC; ``Chicken Soup,'' ABC; ``Growing Pains,'' ABC;
``Head of the Class,'' ABC; and ``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS.
   National League games did better than American League contests
during the playoffs, with the Giants-Cubs matches on Sunday and
Thursday nights tying for 12th place in the ratings. The first game
for the National League series, on Wednesday night, was in 17th
place while the third game on Saturday night was No. 19.
   Two American League games were played in prime time, with the
Tuesday night game between the Athletics and the Toronto Blue Jays
in 36th place and the Friday game at No. 38.
   ``One of the two teams in the American League was a Canadian
team, so you don't have the benefit of two markets in the United
States,'' said Beckman of the lower American League ratings. He
said the American League also tends to draw lower ratings.
   Also during the week, a rare interview with Marlon Brando failed
to lift the sagging ``Saturday Night With Connie Chung.'' The CBS
show tied for 68th place.
   The bottom 10 network shows, from the lowest: ``Championship
Baseball Preview _ American League,'' (Friday night) NBC;
``Saturday Night With Connie Chung,'' CBS; ``Championship Baseball
Preview _ National League,'' (Saturday night) NBC; ``Mr.
Belvedere,'' ABC; ``NFL Live Extra,'' NBC; ``Tour of Duty,'' CBS;
``Championship Baseball Preview _ American League,'' (Tuesday
night) NBC; ``Living Dolls,'' ABC; ``Snoops,'' CBS; ``Primetime
Live,'' ABC.
   In news shows, ABC ``World News Tonight'' tied for first place
with the ``CBS Evening News,'' each with a 9.8 rating. ``NBC
Nightly News'' had an 8.0 rating.
</TEXT>
