<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Editorial     10-11 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Editorial,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Government Newspaper Tells Readers To Brace For Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an editorial marking a
major Afrikaner holiday, one of the country's staunchest
pro-government newspapers told its readers to leave apartheid
behind and prepare for ``a new world _ a mainly black one.''
   ``Whether some whites like it or not, a new South Africa is
dawning _ a South Africa in which people of color walk tall,'' said
the editorial in Tuesday's editions of The Citizen, a Johannesburg
daily.
   The editorial was intended as an assessment of the country's
political situation on Kruger Day, a holiday marking the birthday
of Paul Kruger. He led the mainly Dutch-descended Afrikaners into
the Anglo-Boer War against the British in 1899 after becoming
president of an Afrikaner republic in what is now Transvaal
Province.
   ``President Kruger might be bewildered, like may of us are, by
the suddenness of changes that have come or are coming, but he
would know, as we do, that this beloved country has the inner
strength to survive and fulfill its great destiny,'' The Citizen
said.
   ``Apartheid is dying and the right will never be able to
resurrect it,'' the editorial said. ``The black man is coming into
his own and will never be subjected again to pass laws, influx
control or any of the other monstrosities of apartheid.
   ``It is a new world _ a mainly black one _ and there will never
be a way of returning to white domination or white sovereignty.''
</TEXT>
