<FIRST>r a PM-Veterans'Journey     10-11 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Veterans' Journey,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mountain Trek Links U.S. and Soviet Veterans Who Share Hopes for
Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along the 10,000-foot ridges of central
Asia's Tien Shan mountains, where few Westerners have set foot,
veterans of the Vietnam and Afghanistan wars shared battlefield
memories and a desire for peace.
   The Americans, most of them former Marines, Special Forces
troops or paratroopers, recalled how fellow soldiers in Vietnam
were killed or wounded by gunfire from AK-47 assault rifles,
supplied by the Soviet Union.
   Soviet veterans, also from elite combat units, offered similar
accounts of how their comrades fell victim to hand-held Stinger
missiles that the United States had shipped to the Afghan rebels.
   ``We talked about that quite openly,'' said Bob Rheault, the
leader of the U.S. group, ``and then we'd think about what would
happen if we started shooting at each other with our own weapons.
   ``We'd end the planet,'' said the retired Army colonel.
   For eight days last month, about 35 U.S. and Soviet veterans
trekked across some of the world's most spectacular and forbidding
terrain in an expedition that reflected the spirit of glasnost, the
Soviet's policy of openness that is responsible for a growing
number of exchange programs.
   Earthstewards Network of Bainbridge Island, Wash., a non-profit,
educational group that seeks to promote citizen diplomacy, had
invited Rheault to lead the expedition and recruit participants.
   A Soviet veterans' group organized the itinerary; the Americans
had no idea of their destination until they arrived.
   ``It was a great adventure,'' said retired Lt. Gen. Hal Moore,
who commanded a 1st Cavalry Division battalion in the Ia Drang
Valley, the landmark 1965 battle between U.S. and North Vietnamese
forces.
   Moore, 67, of Crested Butte, Colo., was surprised at the ease
with which he and the other Americans were accepted by the younger
Soviet veterans. Many of the Americans were a generation older.
   ``They called me their brother, and they wanted me to call them
my little brothers,'' Moore said. ``I thought they might call me
`grandfather'.''
   The route traversed a range of remote and barren mountains that
cuts across western China into the Soviet Union east of Tashkent.
   Despite language barriers _ each group had two interpreters _
and the age differences, the former soldiers forged a common bond,
according to members of the U.S. contingent.
   Attitudes toward the respective wars were strikingly similar,
Rheault said, citing the example of one of the Soviets, who
displayed knife wounds from hand-to-hand combat in Afghanistan. The
Soviets completed their troop withdrawal from Afghanistan earlier
this year.
   ``He was proud of having been a good soldier, but he was not
happy at having been sent to fight that stupid war,'' Rheault said.
   Rheault, a former commander of U.S. Special Forces troops, is no
stranger to controversy. He and five Green Beret subordinates were
arrested by the Army in 1969 on charges of killing a South
Vietnamese civilian who was an alleged double agent. Rheault was
jailed 70 days before the Army abruptly dropped the charges.
   Rheault went on to develop innovative outdoor adventure programs
at the Hurricane Island Outward Bound School in Maine. He said the
Tien Shan expedition reinforced the belief that communication
improves hopes for peace between the superpowers.
   At the end of a day's climb, the Vietnam veterans sang ``Where
Have All the Flowers Gone'' and other songs of the era. The Soviets
shared their protest songs, including the mournful ``Black Tulip,''
which took its name from the helicopter that lifted out bodies of
dead Soviet soldiers.
   ``We had so much in common that it transcended our
differences,'' said the 63-year-old Rheault. ``We certainly felt a
lot closer to each other than any of us felt to our own
politicians.''
</TEXT>
