<FIRST>r a PM-People-Copeland     10-11 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Copeland,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock, Opera Fans Rave About Rock Drummer's Opera</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock fans and opera lovers were enthusiastic
about the world premiere of an opera written by Stewart Copeland,
the former drummer with the rock group Police. A newspaper review,
though, wasn't so kind.
   The idea of a rock star moving into the opera world is ``very
exciting,'' said 22-year-old Brent Brown, of Painesville, a
longtime fan.
   ``He's bringing new ideas to high opera,'' said Brown, dressed
for Tuesday night's premiere in a tuxedo and red bow tie.
   A companion, David Dunham, 28, also of Painesville, said the
opera ``Holy Blood and Crescent Moon,'' was ``a good mix for new
people. You need that.''
   Dunham, a fan of opera, said that the ``orchestrated score needs
a little work. The actual singing is good.''
   But a reviewer for The Plain Dealer newspaper found problems.
   ``Copeland's score rises only at a few isolated moments to
anything that makes us care about his characters. It is full of
nervous orchestral busy-work,'' the review said.
   Dunham said the capacity audience at the ornate State Theater
included many more young people than the typical opera audience.
``I wouldn't expect to see them here for `Carmen,''' he said.
   Copeland, who spent six years with Police and later wrote scores
for movies and television shows, took four years to write ``Holy
Blood and Crescent Moon,'' a tale of the Crusades in the Middle
East.
   The 37-year-old decided to write an opera on a lark in 1984,
while he was composing music for a ballet for Shakespeare's King
Lear for the San Francisco Ballet.
   His opera will be performed Thursday through Sunday at the State
Theater and in March 1991 in Fort Worth, Texas.
</TEXT>
