<DOCNO> AP891011-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0532EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MajorCon     10-11 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Major Con,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Falsehood' Master Sentenced to Federal Medical Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You'd have to wonder about a guy who
claimed he was a CIA spy, a mobster, a doctor, the Army's youngest
major general, Elvis Presley's pal and a hero who rescued scores of
POWs from Vietnam.
   His girlfriend did, and after she checked Robert S. Lyons' story
with the Secret Service, they arrested him.
   Lyons, a 35-year-old Mission, Kan., salesman of water
purification systems pleaded guilty in July to impersonating a CIA
agent and a major general and was sentenced Tuesday to 15 months of
psychiatric treatment.
   U.S. District Judge Earl E. O'Connor said Lyons has ``a history
of falsehoods that can't be substantiated other than through his
words.''
   Lyons' ex-girlfriend, Beth Hannah of Overland Park, said Lyons
was charming, quick-witted, and full of stories.
   ``He was a gentleman,'' she said. ``He always held the door
open.''
   Ms. Hannah, 45, nearly married him, and Cindy Cohen, 35, also of
Overland Park, did. Both suffered financially for believing his
stories and both attended his sentencing.
   ``He was a master of manipulation,'' Ms. Cohen said, ``an
absolute master.''
   ``He would make a tremendous writer,'' Ms. Hannah said. ``It's a
waste.''
   Ms. Cohen recalled, ``Robert was constantly lying. He would go
from day to day, minute to minute, building one story on another.''
   Lyons left the Army as a private, but he wrote an article about
himself in a bogus newsletter.
   The story recounts how General Lyons led a commando team in 1983
to Southeast Asia, rescued 285 prisoners of war and returned with
the remains of 300 servicemen. It said he received two Medals of
Honor and was awaiting a third.
   Ms. Hannah, who knew little of government and the military, said
Lyons laced his lies with enough detail to make them sound true. By
late January, less than a month after they met, she gave Lyons
$1,000 to pay his debts.
   Ms. Cohen met Lyons at a restaurant in 1981. She had arrived
there and saw a former boyfriend with a nicely groomed man who
identified himself as Dr. Pat Lyons.
   In the weeks to come, Ms. Cohen said, Lyons kept making excuses
to see or call her. At such meetings, he would mention that he flew
helicopters, designed vacuum cleaners and sold insurance.
   One day, she said, Lyons came to her house saying he wanted to
come clean: His first name was Robert, not Pat, and his stories
about being a doctor were false.
   He said he had no choice but to lie because he was trying to
protect his real identity as a member of the Kansas City mob.
   Another day, Ms. Cohen said, they drove to a carwash, where
Lyons jumped a track and smashed her Pontiac into a post. He
promised that his insurance policy would pay for the damage and
said the mob had arranged the wreck.
   Ms. Cohen agreed to marry Lyons in 1981 because he said the mob
would leave them alone once he married.
   ``I had to get married because I wanted my family left alone,''
she said. ``I wanted my cake decorating shop left alone.''
   But during 18 months of marriage, Ms. Cohen said, she was forced
to sell her furniture and close her business to appease creditors.
``I was watching my life being destroyed,'' she said.
   Ultimately, Lyons confessed that he had lied about his life as a
mobster. Ms. Cohen threw Lyons out of their house, divorced him and
later had the marriage annulled.
   Hannah said she became suspicious when a neighbor saw Lyons'
resume and doubted his claims. The neighbor called the CIA, where
authorities said they had never heard of Lyons. She then called the
Secret Service.
   During the hearing, Lyons' attorney, John Gerstle, described his
client as ``an individual who has severe problems and enormous
emotional problems.''
   ``This has been a long, trying five months for ... my family, my
friends,'' Lyons said. ``I'm sorry for this episode and the entire
train of events.''
  
</TEXT>
