<FIRST>r a PM-AlaskaQuake     10-11 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Quake,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Hits Alaska; No Injuries or Damage Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook buildings in
Alaska's capital and woke up residents from Juneau to Sitka early
today. No injuries or damage were immediately reported.
   The quake measured 5.1 on the Richter scale in a preliminary
measurement, said Alec Medbery, spokesman for the Alaska Tsunami
Warning Center in Palmer.
   It struck at about 12:50 a.m. (4:50 a.m. EDT) and was centered
50 miles west of Sitka, about 110 miles southwest of Juneau,
Medbery said.
   ``It was felt widely, all the way from Sitka to Juneau and all
points in between,'' Medbury said. ``There were no reports of
damage but it woke quite a few people up. Buildings shook and it
was enough to wake them up.''
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 5 can cause considerable damage.
</TEXT>
