<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0553EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UkrainiansThreatened     10-11 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ukrainians Threatened,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Asked to Investigate Threats Against Ukrainians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE BEAR LAKE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI has joined the
investigation into the vandalism, cross-burning and threats against
a family of Ukrainian Christians.
   The bureau is looking into possible civil rights violations
against Vladimir and Ekaterina Doroshkevich and their eight
children, who resettled in the area two months ago.
   A cross was found burning on the family's lawn Sunday morning
and anti-Russian slogans were spray-painted on the Calvary Assembly
of God Church that is sponsoring their resettlement.
   The pastor, the Rev. Mike Smith, received a telephoned death
threat directed against his family and the Doroshkeviches.
   Lt. James Moeller of the White Bear Lake Police Department said
police are analyzing evidence and, so far, the incidents appear to
be the work of a single person.
   ``It's far too early to theorize, but there's nothing at all to
suggest this is anything more than an isolated incident from an
individual, a misguided individual,'' he said. ``There's nothing to
suggest a group or an organized activity.''
   The harassment that Doroshkeviches have suffered is the first
aimed at any of the more than 10,000 Soviet Christians who have
immigrated to the United States since 1988, said Judi Jankowski of
the Minnesota chapter of World Relief, an arm of the National
Association of Evangelicals.
   On Tuesday, the church received scores of phone calls after news
reports of the harassment and vandalism. Almost all of the callers
voiced support for the church and the emigres, said church
secretary Donna Boyum.
   She said three callers criticized the resettlement of the
Doroshkeviches, who say they suffered religious persecution in
their Soviet homeland and spent 12 years trying to emigrate. More
than 60 callers had a positive message, she said.
   ``We've had offers of donations, food and clothing, people who
want to write notes of support to the family, other churches
putting them on their prayer chain,'' Boyum said. ``People
generally are shocked that anyone would do something like this.''
   The Twin Cities Area Human Rights Coalition planned to hold a
session today allowing representatives of various religious
organizations to speak out against the incidents.
   ``We fear this is an example of the xenophobia that seems to be
occurring in our country, in which some people are threatened by
any kind of difference whatsoever,'' said Carol Wirtschafter,
assistant director of the Jewish Community Relations Council
Anti-Defamation League of Minnesota and the Dakotas.
</TEXT>
