<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Refugees     10-11 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Refugees,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homesickness Drives Some East Germans Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homesickness has prompted the
return of more than 50 East Germans who fled their strict Communist
homeland for the West in the past month, a border official says.
   Nearly 50,000 East Germans have arrived in West Germany since
Sept. 11, when Hungary removed restrictions on crossing its western
border.
   Many refugees cried tears of joy when they arrived, but West
German officials have cautioned that many would face personal
problems as they tried to fit into a new society.
   Wolfgang Schlee, spokesman for Bavarian border police, said
Tuesday that 54 refugees who arrived since Sept. 11 already had
returned and he expected more to do so.
   ``Homesickness is the key,'' he said by telephone from Munich.
``Many of them miss their friends. It's for personal reasons.
   ``In some cases, it's a question of wives, children and parents
left behind, alone or in need of care.''
   He noted that many brought ``only the most necessary things with
them. Most of what they owned was left behind.''
   Speculation has arisen about how the refugees would be treated
if they returned home, but Schlee said he doubted they would face
the harshness of the past.
   East Germany severely punishes what it calls ``flight from the
republic.'' Armed guards, fences and the Berlin Wall are designed
to block escape. Over the years, thousands of East Germans have
been sent to prison after being caught fleeing.
   Official news media in East Germany have given prominence to
statements from those who left and returned after becoming
disillusioned in West Germany. They regulary carry bleak
descriptions of life in West Germany, insisting that unemployment
and housing shortages are rampant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0633EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-ChicagoSchoolReform     10-11 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago School Reform,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago on Brink of New School System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters cast ballots today to choose local
councils that could reform the city's much-maligned school system
by giving parents a direct say in their children's education.
   ``The bad education system is really crippling the city,'' said
Donald Moore, executive director of Designs for Change, an
education research and advisory group that helped shape the reform
package. ``Whether you have kids in school or not, it's important.''
   Chicago's school system, the nation's third largest with 410,000
students, has had low test scores and high dropout rates. In 1987,
then-Education Secretary William Bennett called the system the
nation's worst.
   Under a reform package passed last year by the Illinois General
Assembly, elections are being held today at the city's 469
elementary schools and Thursday at the 71 public high schools to
take much power out of administrators's hands and turn it over
largely to parents.
   Among other things, the councils will have the authority to hire
and fire principals, develop school-improvement plans and spend
money.
   ``I think people understand the significance,'' Moore said.
``The best indicator of that is that we have 17,000 candidates, and
therefore we will have contested selections for almost all
positions on the councils.''
   Each council will include six parents, two teachers and two
community residents without schoolchildren. School staffs will
elect the teacher members. The 11th member of each council will be
the principal of the school or schools the council oversees.
   A 50 percent turnout among parents with children in schools was
predicted by community activists and others who spent weeks trying
to mobilize residents to participate.
   ``I'm just asking people to take a look at this very seriously
because to go into it for anything other than helping the kids, it
will not work,'' said Mary Guyton-Smith, an AT&amp;T clerk seeking a
community representative spot on the council at Farragut High
School on the city's southwest side.
   Despite fears that politicians and others would manipulate the
elections to favor certain candidates, Moore said election judges
were hired by the school board to make sure the elections are
impartial.
   Project LEAP (Legal Elections in All Precincts), a watchdog
group that monitors regular municipal elections, also agreed to
monitor the voting to watch for improprieties.
</TEXT>
