<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BayBridge-Mayors     10-11 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bay Bridge-Mayors,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oakland Mayor Plays Down Hostilities After San Francisco Mayor's
Comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even though San Francisco's mayor won't
be getting all A's from his Oakland counterpart, hostilities were
played down as the San Francisco Giants and Oakland Athletics
prepare to meet in the World Series.
   Still, Oakland Mayor Lionel Wilson wanted to capitalize at a
press conference Tuesday on San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos' recent
remark that there wasn't anything in Oakland he wanted.
   ``He kind of took a potshot at us recently, but I'm willing to
let bygones be bygones,'' said Wilson, beaming in a bright green
A's jacket and cap.
   ``I read this morning that he said he was joking,'' Wilson said,
referring to Agnos' comments. ``Well, it wasn't a good joke, but so
what?''
   He pointed out the Athletics have won the American League
pennant two years in a row and won three championships in the time
it's taken the Giants to just make it into the Series two times.
   ``I appreciate the Giants being in the World Series. I'm happy
for them,'' said Wilson, who reportedly was furious when he first
heard Agnos' disparaging statements about his neighbor on the east
side of the Bay Bridge.
   Wilson's peace-making statements were spoken in the spirit of
the first inhabitants of Oakland _ the Ohlone Indians, a hunting
and gathering people said to have maintained such a peaceful
attitude that they had no word for war.
   But the reality is that the World Series war is on, and so is
the rivalry between San Francisco and Oakland.
   Wilson disclosed that he wrote a letter to Agnos about the
anti-Oakland comments he made last week. Wilson said Agnos called
him about the letter, but he didn't return the calls.
   ``I was too upset, and I think I had a legitimate reason. I've
never said anything to try and diminish San Francisco,'' said
74-year-old Wilson, an Oakland resident since age 3.
   Sensing his ``joke'' about not wanting anything in Oakland had
gone too far, Agnos on Monday called Oakland a ``great city with a
great team and a great mayor.''
   Agnos even said there were a few things he ``wouldn't mind
winning'' from Oakland if Wilson wanted to bet on the World Series.
   ``Sure. I'll go high stakes or low stakes,'' Agnos said. ``If
(Wilson) wants to go high stakes, I'll bet him Candlestick Park
against the Oakland Coliseum. If he wants to go low stakes, I'll
bet him dinner at Flint's Ribs.''
   Wilson said he hoped for a ``friendly wager'' with Agnos on the
Series, which he predicted the A's will win in six games thanks to
their superior pitching.
   He knows a little bit about the sport, having played pro ball
for the California Eagles, a black team in the days of segregated
baseball.
   Before the news conference, Wilson quipped: ``I know what I'll
bet him; maybe I'll have a plastic foot made he can put in his
mouth.''
   At his own news conference in San Francisco, Agnos told
reporters Tuesday that he's won every bet he's made since becoming
mayor, including one on the Super Bowl: ``I want to keep the string
going.''
</TEXT>
