<FIRST>r a PM-PanamanianRebels     10-11 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panamanian Rebels,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel: Coup Participants Never Intended to Kill Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of the coup attempt against Panama's
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega had no intention of killing him during
the several hours they held him hostage, a participant told the
Miami Herald.
   The rebel, one of 42 Panamanians flown into Miami this week
after seeking refuge at U.S. military bases in their homeland,
spoke on condition that neither his name nor the location where he
was interviewed be disclosed, the newspaper said today. He said his
troops knew him as Commander Thunder.
   He suggested junior officers who took part in the coup attempt
turned Noriega over to their superiors. He said the rebels had held
Noriega hostage for several hours last week and could have killed
him at any time.
   ``There was no intention at any time to kill the man,'' the coup
participant said.
   Asked why, he said it may have been because a soldier would find
it hard to execute his top commander.
   ``It may have been their military discipline,'' he said.
   In their public proclamations, the rebels said they had staged
the coup to ``retire'' Noriega and five senior colonels of the
Panamanian Defense Forces.
   Among 42 exiles who arrived in Miami is Capt. Francisco Alvarez,
who was arrested last year for taking part in a March 1988 coup
attempt against Noriega. Alvarez reportedly was released from jail
three months ago.
   The Washington Post reported another of those given refuge was
Capt. Javier Licona, believed to be the highest-ranking participant
in the coup to escape capture.
   One of the rebels in Florida said the soldiers feared for their
relatives at home.
   ``Noriega is a beast,'' the man said. ``He won't stop at
anything. He's going to take reprisals against our wives, our
children and our parents back in Panama.''
</TEXT>
