<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MissingBoat     10-11 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Boat,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Gets SOS From Charter Boat; Hoax Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast Guard and Navy crews searched the dark
waters of the Gulf of Mexico early today after getting a distress
call about a charter boat sinking with 18 aboard, but officials
said the SOS may have been a hoax.
   ``I'm sinking, and I'm going into the water,'' a man claiming to
be a charter boat captain told the Coast Guard late Tuesday, said
Petty Officer Fred Kephart.
   Seventeen life vests and a five-person raft were available on
the 64-foot fishing boat, the man said, reportedly adding, ``We are
going to abandon ship in 45 seconds.''
   Boat and airplane crews found no sign of the vessel by daylight,
and the Coast Guard received no reports of missing boaters, leading
to speculation the call was a hoax _ especially considering the
number of people supposedly on board, said Petty Officer 2nd Class
Bob Morehead.
   ``In a normal search and rescue operation like this, we get
several calls from family members and friends and other cocnerned
people. We haven't gotten that in this case,'' he said.
   ``There is the possibility that this is a hoax. But we are
operating on the assumption that this is a legitimate call, until
we are confident we have searched the whole area with no sign of a
boat and no report of anyone overdue.''
   The search was centered about 30 miles south of Pensacola Pass,
the entrace to Florida's Pensacola Bay.
   Seas were 3 to 4 feet, winds were 8 mph and the water was around
70 degrees, making overnight survival in the water possible, said
Lt. David McBride of Mobile, Ala.
</TEXT>
