<HEAD>Tropical Storm Claims At Least 18 Lives, Fishermen Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th, `About 95 ...' to UPDATE with power
out at Clark air base; picks up 5th pvs: Dan was ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Dan battered Manila
and southern Luzon Island today with 62 mph winds, killing at least
18 people, injuring 55 and shutting down transport, schools and
government offices.
   Up to 20 fishermen were reported missing after two fishing boats
broke from their moorings and collided early today at a port in
Batangas province south of the capital.
   Nearly 60,000 people fled their homes and sought shelter in
government relief centers, officials said. Damage was extensive in
Manila.
   About 95 percent of the city of more than 7 million people was
without electricity as winds ripped down power lines. Schools in
Manila were closed for the day, as were government offices and
stock markets.
   U.S. Air Force officials at Clark Air Base north of Manila said
Dan knocked out 80 percent of the electricity in the camp's housing
area.
   Dan was the second killer storm to strike the Philippines in the
last week. On Friday, Typhoon Angela roared across the northern
coast of Luzon, killing at least 118 people.
   At Manila's airport, Dan's gusty winds pushed an empty Omani
Boeing 707 into the DC-10 that brought President Hussain Muhammad
Ershad of Bangladesh to the Philippines Monday for a four-day visit.
   A wing of the 707 struck one of the engines of Ershad's plane.
   Dan slammed into Luzon on Tuesday night 210 miles southeast of
Manila, passing just south of the capital before entering the South
China Sea.
   Five of the deaths occurred in the Manila area, four in Laguna
province, four on Marinduque island, two in Cavite province, two in
Bataan province and one in Quezon province.
   In Batangas province, the coast guard said 10 people were
rescued when the two fishing boats collided off Bauan, 50 miles
south of Manila.
   The Office of Civil Defense said up to 30 people may have been
aboard the two vessels, but the coast guard said the figure was
uncertain.
   Utility officials said that by mid-afternoon power had been
restored in about 16 percent of the city. A generator at a suburban
power station caught fire and burned for three hours after the
storm ripped off the roof.
   Philippine Airlines canceled 30 domestic flights from the
capital and international service was disrupted.
   An average of 20 typhoons or tropical storms strike the
Philippines annually.
</TEXT>
