<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-Protest     10-11 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Protest,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March Near Site Of Mass Killings By Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UITENHAGE, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 30,000 people
marched through this industrial city today to protest apartheid and
honor 20 blacks killed by police during a 1985 funeral procession.
   The march, which stretched for more than three miles, was one of
the largest in a series of protests nationwide since President F.W.
de Klerk announced last month that the government would allow
peaceful mass demonstrations.
   Many of the marchers in Uitenhage wore black arm bands in
commemoration of those who died in 1985, when police fired on
several thousand mourners heading toward this city from the black
township of Langa in a funeral procession for men killed earlier by
police.
   Police were deployed in large numbers along the parade route and
blocked off side streets with barbed wire, but no disturbances were
reported. Nearly all the marchers were black, but some were white
or mixed-race.
   Three clergymen heading the parade presented a petition to a
police commander containing demands of the marchers, including
improved services and schools in Langa, lifting of the state of
emergency and release of political prisoners.
   Marchers help aloft banners of the outlawed African National
Congress guerrilla movement and placards with slogans, including
one which said: ``Don't Shoot Us. We March For Peace.''
   Uitenhage, a stronghold of the pro-apartheid Conservative Party,
is in eastern Cape Province near the coastal city of Port Elizabeth.
   Police said today that 40 people were arrested for violence
during a mass protest Tuesday in Mpumalanga, a black township in
Natal Province. An estimated 10,000 to 15,000 people attended a
rally there demanding that national police units be withdrawn and
be replaced by police from the tribal homeland of KwaZulu.
   Mpumalanga has been one of townships hardest hit by violence
arising from a three-year power struggle between supporters of
militant anti-apartheid groups and members of Inkatha, a more
conservative Zulu political organization.
</TEXT>
