<HEAD>Japanese Officials Invited to Discuss Drug-Money Laundering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady has
invited Japanese officials to the United States to discuss ways to
eliminate drug-money laundering, the Treasury Department announced
today.
   Deputy Secretary John E. Robson, who is in Tokyo this week,
delivered Brady's letter to Japanese Finance Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto inviting Finance Ministry and other Japanese government
officials to the meeting.
   ``The United States government has made drug-money laundering
one of its highest priorities,'' Robson said, according to a
Treasury statement. ``We are eager to work with the Japanese
government to mount a unified effort to stop the illicit use of the
global financial system by drug cartel leaders.''
   ``International cooperation is the key to taking the profit out
of drugs,'' he said.
   In addition to Treasury facilities here, the Japanese will visit
the Internal Revenue Service Computing Center in Detroit and the
Federal Law Enforcement Training Center in Glynco, Ga.
   Robson is in Japan for meetings with Japanese government and
business leaders focusing on long-term U.S. competitiveness as well
as money laundering. He recently headed a U.S. delegation at a
meeting of the Financial Action Task Force in Paris.
