<HEAD>Nursing Home Aide Sentenced in Patients' Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nursing home aide was
sentenced to 20 to 40 years in prison today for helping smother
elderly patients in a pact with her lesbian lover.
   ``Without you, I'm sure this matter never would have been
cleared up,'' Circuit Judge Robert Benson said in sentencing
Catherine Wood, who had pleaded guilty and testified against her
lover.
   In a statement read by her lawyer, Wood said: ``Saying `I'm
sorry' is not enough. Mere words cannot express my feelings of
remorse.''
   Wood, 27, admitted serving as lookout while some of five
patients at Alpine Manor Nursing home in Walker were suffocated by
another former aide, Gwendolyn Graham.
   Wood said the murders were part of a pact the two hoped would
bind their love. She said Graham told her the killings helped her
``relieve tension.''
   Wood pleaded guilty to a reduced charge of murder and conspiracy.
   Graham was convicted last month of five counts of murder. The
defense charged that Wood fabricated the story because Graham had
left her for another woman.
   Graham, of Tyler, Texas, faces a mandatory sentence of life
without parole.
   Wood testified she stood guard outside the room of a 60-year-old
Alzheimer's patient while Graham suffocated her with a washcloth.
She also said she diverted the attention of a supervisor while
Graham suffocated another patient.
   Graham and Wood lived together as lovers at the time of the
murders in 1987. The two broke up later that year. Police began
investigating the deaths after Wood's ex-husband said she confessed
to him.
