<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-NuclearWaste     10-11 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Waste,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Asking States' Help in Storing Nuclear Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's chief of staff was urging the
governors of seven states today to accept radioactive waste from
the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant in order to avert a possible
shutdown of the plant next year, officials said.
   The facility near Denver is the nation's only source of
plutonium triggers used in nuclear warheads. Colorado Gov. Roy
Romer has said he will not allow the plant to continue operating if
alternative sites are not found to store the waste by next March.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins has said closure of Rocky
Flats would amount to unilateral nuclear disarmament, since the
triggers cannot be made elsewhere.
   John Sununu, the White House chief of staff, was telephoning the
governors of Colorado, Idaho, Nevada, New Mexico, South Carolina,
Tennessee and Washington today to ask for their help and to
underscore the importance of keeping Rocky Flats open, said Phil
Keif, an Energy Department spokesman.
   ``He'll tell them this is a critical thing, we hope you'll
help,'' Keif said.
   The seven states chosen as possible alternative sites for the
Rocky Flats waste were selected because they already host Energy
Department nuclear facilities, Keif said.
   Some of these states, including Washington, Nevada, New Mexico
and Idaho, already have said publicly they would not agree to take
any Rocky Flats waste, even temporarily.
   The waste is contaminated with plutonium, which remains
radioactive for 240,000 years.
   Also today, Watkins's top aide on nuclear waste issues, Leo
Duffy, was meeting with Nevada Gov. Bob Miller in Carson City to
ask him to drop his already-announced opposition to holding some of
the Rocky Flats waste, Keif said.
   Duffy later was flying to Idaho Falls, Idaho, to make a similar
plea to Gov. Cecil Andrus. Idaho had been storing excess waste from
Rocky Flats, but on Sept. 1, Andrus sealed his state's borders to
further shipments, citing the Energy Department's failure to open a
planned permanent waste dump in New Mexico on time.
   Watkins told Congress last week that the Waste Isolation Pilot
Project, or WIPP, near Carlsbad, N.M., would not be ready to open
before next July 1 at the earliest.
   Watkins said about 250 cubic yards a month of Rocky Flats waste
would have to be stored elsewhere after March in order to meet
Romer's demands while WIPP was unavailable. He suggested then that
he would ask seven states to share the burden of temporarily
holding the waste, while acknowledging that it would be difficult
to persuade the governors.
   Duffy also planned to meet with Romer today in Denver to discuss
the problem, Keif said.
   In addition, Energy Department officials were briefing the
states' congressional delegations on the WIPP repository problems
and the need for alternative storage sites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0084 </DOCNO>
