<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia     10-11 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Threaten Strikes Over U.N. Food Aid Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARANYAPRATHET, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodians in Thailand's largest
refugee camp threatened strikes and refused to unload U.N. food
supplies today after the international organization cut aid to the
camp, a relief official said.
   Aid workers said Tuesday that the U.N. cut some of its food
rations to the sprawling Site 2 camp because food and other
supplies were being diverted to guerrillas fighting inside Cambodia.
   Site 2 is controlled by Khmer People's National Liberation
Front, one of the three guerrilla groups fighting the
Vietnam-backed government in Phnom Penh.
   The cuts meant a decrease of about 20 percent of the total food
aid to the camp, which houses about 140,000 Cambodians, they said.
   But the Cambodian administration of the camp had told refugees
that the U.N. had cut off all aid to the camp, the relief official
said today, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Workers in the refugee administration had refused to unload U.N.
food trucks and hospital staff had threatened to strike on
Thursday, he said.
   ``The (guerrilla group's) tactic appears to be to create
anti-United Nation's sentimemnt among the population,'' he said.
   Some refugees had become hostile to relief workers, and some aid
staff had been verbally abused, he said.
   Although there are more than 100 outside relief workers in Site
2, much of the essential day-to-day work is done by refugees.
   The aid official said the United Nations had insisted the
refugees ensure that international food supplies are not sent to
the guerrillas, or sold on the open market. It had also demanded an
end to military operations carried out from Site 2, he said.
   Relief officials have reported diversions of food, medicine and
other humanitarian aid since the international assistance program
began a decade ago.
   Some officials privately have been especially critical of the
aid being supplied to the communist Khmer Rouge guerrillas, who
exercise rigid control over the civilians under their control.
   Human rights organizations have cited numerous human rights
abuses at the Khmer Rouge camps, where monitoring of international
aid is far more difficult than in camps of the other two guerrilla
groups.
