<SECOND>PM-School Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0515,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Teen in High School Bombings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with no motive given, no arrest
record, school reopening today; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The teen-ager ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STANLEY D. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested a 16-year-old on
charges of planting two bombs that exploded at his high school on
consecutive days.
   Anonymous tips led officers Tuesday night to the home of the
boy, whose name was withheld, Detective Kevin Smith said. Police
searched his home but would not say what they found and gave no
motive for the bombings.
   Detective John Gunter said the youth had no arrest record and
had not been in trouble at school.
   Bombs exploded Monday and Tuesday at 1,200-student Anderson High
School, causing no injuries. Classes were canceled and students
sent home both days. Damage was estimated at less than $800.
   As word of each blast spread, telephoned bomb threats were
phoned to several other high schools in the area of central
Indiana, authorities said.
   Classes resumed without incident today. Principal Horace
Chadbourne said attendance was normal.
   ``Everything's going well,'' said Shelley Drake, assistant vice
principal. ``Students are happy and feel secure, and we're about
the business of education.''
   ``I'm sure it's over. This is a new day,'' she added.
   Ms. Drake said teachers came to school early and patrolled the
halls before class. ``We did that just to let the students know
that everything's fine,'' she said.
   Not all of the students felt safe, however.
   ``It's kind of scary,'' said Jackie Mohler, a sophomore. ``I
feel safer, but one of my teachers told me this usually starts a
chain, so we'll probably have some (bomb threats) today.''
   The teen-ager was arrested at his home at 8:30 p.m. and charged
with two counts of arson and two of manufacturing an explosive
device, all felonies. He was held at a juvenile detention center.
The student made no statement, Smith said.
   At least one other youth was either involved or was aware of
what was happening, investigators said. They are looking into the
possibility of filing charges against him, they added.
   On Tuesday a small pipe bomb exploded about 7:35 a.m. in a
hallway outside the school auditorium, said Charles Petersen, agent
in charge of the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in
Indianapolis.
   Only a few students and teachers were in the building at the
time.
   Earlier Tuesday, Chief Ron Rheam said police would step up
security at the school today. ``I do not fear for any teacher or
student coming to the school tomorrow,'' he said.
   Monday's explosion occurred in a wrestling room below the west
end of the the school's 9,000-seat gymnasium.
   The crudely made device was a small fire extinguisher filled
with gasoline and a smokeless powder, police said. It was placed
atop a heater 15 feet above the floor, Petersen said.
   ``The bombs were placed in areas where there is not heavy
traffic flow, so that the person that's placing the bombs has some
feeling that he does not want anyone hurt,'' Rheam said.
   Prosecutor William F. Lawler Jr. said he will ask the juvenile
court to waive jurisdiction on the bombing suspect. This would move
the state's case into adult courts and mean the suspect could face
stiffer penalties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
