<FIRST>r w PM-US-Italy     10-11 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Italy,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Confers With Italian President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush welcomed Italy's President
Francesco Cossiga to the White House today to discuss issues
including changes in Eastern Europe, the Soviet Union and ``the
need for unity ... when tensions are easing but the threat to peace
and freedom still exists.''
   Cossiga, in remarks at a ceremony on the South Lawn of the White
House, called for more Western aid to the reform government of
Poland and touched on other areas of sensitivity between Italy and
the Unied States, including Italian aid to leftist Nicaragua.
   At the arrival ceremony, Bush recalled that his first stop in
Europe as president last spring was in Italy.
   ``The road to alliance unity began in Rome,'' he said, referring
to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization conference that he
attended on that trip.
   The president said he and Cossiga planned to discuss the reform
movements sweeping Eastern European nations as well as developments
in the Soviet Union and the Western alliance.
   ``We'll discuss alliance issues and the need for unity that is
critical today when tensions are easing but the threat to peace and
freedom still exists,'' Bush said.
   In a lengthy statement, Cossiga noted ``changes in the direction
of democracy which are taking place in Poland, Hungary and the
Soviet Union.''
   Calling for more financial assistance to help the process, he
said, ``I'm thinking in particular of the great Polish nation that
is currently in the throes of serious difficulty in its courageous
attempt to work its renewal and which needs more substantial aid
from us.''
   Cossiga said Italy wants to create ``a new relationship with
Eastern Europe, particularly the countries of the opposite shores
of the Adriatic (Sea) and over the Alps.''
   He also said that Italy will continue its assistance in Latin
America, where the country's aid to the Sandinista government of
Nicaragua is a bone of contention with Washington.
   The three-day official visit is Cossiga's first since assuming
office in 1985.
   Italian Foreign Minister Gianni De Michelis, accompanying
Cossiga, is also expected to seek the U.S. views on Eastern Europe,
especially on events in Italy's neighbor, Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
