<FIRST>r w PM-StolenCheese     10-11 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stolen Cheese,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentuckians Admit Diverting Government Cheese to Supermarket Pizzas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Kentucky businessmen today pleaded guilty
to diverting $1.2 million worth of government-surplus cheese to
make frozen pizzas for commercial sale in supermarkets, the Justice
Department said.
   Ricky Kazuo Oshiro and his brother, Cliff Oshiro, pleaded guilty
in federal court in Lexington, Ky., to a 1985-86 conspiracy to
defraud an Agriculture Department program that donates surplus
cheese to feed low-income people.
   A department statement said the Oshiro brothers were supervisors
of a Florence, Ky., plant operated by Sabatasso Foods, Inc., that
had a contract to make pizzas with USDA cheese for school lunches.
The company also made frozen pizzas for sale to supermarkets.
   The brothers admitted to claiming more cheese than the company
needed to perform the contract and using it to make frozen pizzas
for sale in supermarkets, U.S. Attorney Louis DeFalaise said.
   Each defendant could receive a five-year prison term a $250,000
fine. The case was investigated by the USDA's inspector general.
   Sabatasso Foods, which was formerly based in Santa Ana, Calif.,
was purchased by Schwann Enterprises, Inc., of Minnesota in 1986.
</TEXT>
