<DOCNO> AP891011-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     10-11 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferre Sticks to His Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International fame has not changed Monsieur
Ferre, as the Milanese creator is called since he became designated
designer for the famed French house of Dior.
   He still cuts a modest, bashful figure with his rotund body and
bearded, chubby face as he comes out on the runway for the standing
ovation that greets his collection.
   He seems embarrassed by the lipstick marks left by his models
who vie to kiss him on the runway, and inevitably takes out a
handkerchief to wipe away his tears of emotion at another
successful show.
   Yet this shy man always produces a dynamite collection. His
style is sexy, self-confident and unmistakable.
   The Ferre silhouette puts the accent on the upper body with
broad shoulders and ornate neckline, tapering into a small waist
and narrow hips. He favors see-through fabrics, tight contours and
bold hemlines.
   Ferre's spring-summer 1990 collection, presented Tuesday night
midway through the weeklong Italian ready-to-wear showings, was no
exception.
   It was his first own label show since shocking the fashion world
by accepting Dior's offer, and the crowd was curious to see if he
could successfully divide his loyalties between traditional rivals
Milan and Paris.
   What they found was a Ferre better than ever, light and airy on
the one hand, seductively masculine on the other.
   Thus, bare midriff chiffon see-through blouses are worn under
slick man-tailored suits with large rhinestone and gold buttons. Or
a huge silk corsage of flowers and feathers and bejeweled cufflinks
turns a man-tailored shirt into a feminine item.
   Pants are cut straight for day and night, and they are a dandy's
delight, coupled with an oversized white blouse with a spill of
panels down the front resembling a huge bouquet of napkins and a
straw fedora.
   As the day goes on, Ferre's style becomes more elaborate,
culminating in a series of chiffon floral and paisley printed gowns
richly decorated with gold and crystal sequins.
   Ferre is into heavy gold jewelry, as are many of the designers
in Milan. He adorns his models with enormous charm bracelets with
sea-motif charms, large beaded necklaces and chain belts.
   Among Ferre innovations were the short-skirted summer wicker
work suits woven out of burlap to look like raffia, and a body suit
in bands of gray jersey and skin colored chiffon that looked like
mummy wrappings.
   Another big name to show Tuesday night was Mariuccia Mandelli,
the master mind behind the Krizia label.
   The Krizia collection was young and carefree with an accent on
the 1940s. To the tune of ``In the Mood,'' Krizia showed that by
day she was in the mood for bright colors, short easy shapes and
lots of prim navy blue and white.
   Neat daytime navy blue suits and dresses with crisp white
lapels, alternated with T-shirts adorned with the new Krizia
animal, the giraffe. These were worn over cheerleader shorts in
tropical shades. Two new daytime ideas were jodhpur sweat pants,
and patchwork camouflage leather.
   At night, Krizia indulges in her favorite fabric _ accordian
pleated silk _ for beautiful shawled blouses and wafty
pastel-colored short party dresses.
   Like many of her colleagues this week, Krizia has no trouble
baring the flesh, leaving wide open spaces in the midriff or down
the back. Bras as lingerie seem to be out of fashion, whereas they
take on new life as outer wear, appearing in leather and jersey by
day, and sequin and gold by night. See-through fabrics abound.
   For more than an hour, Krizia's models kept coming out down the
long runway. While reporters simply put down their notebooks,
rowdier photographers shouted ``Basta!'' _ ``Enough!''
</TEXT>
