<DOCNO> AP891011-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-UtilityTaxes     10-11 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Utility Taxes,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Rejects Bill Calling for Quick Refunds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee today
rejected a bill that could have resulted in quick refunds averaging
$223 apiece for customers of the nation's utility companies.
   The bill by Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., lost on a 22-13 vote,
with 12 Democrats and one Republican supporting it.
   At issue in the bill, co-written by Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.,
was about $19 billion that the power, gas and telephone companies
collected in advance from customers to pay corporate taxes to the
federal government. The money was collected in anticipation that
the utilities would owe taxes at a 46 percent corporate rate.
   However, when Congress enacted the 1986 tax overhaul, it cut the
top corporate rate to 34 percent. Matsui was able to win passage at
that time of an amendment giving utilities as long as 30 years to
refund the excess to consumers.
   Matsui says now that he made a mistake, that he was misled by
the utilities into believing that the excess would be used to buy
new equipment. Many utilities, he says, are so rich with cash that
they are buying such businesses as golf courses, recording studios
and a drug store chain.
   ``Never before in my 11 years in Congress has an issue been as
crystal clear as this one,'' Matsui said earlier this year when he
introduced the heavily lobbied bill. ``It's a matter of right vs.
wrong, good public policy vs. bad special interests, ethics vs.
greed.''
   His bill would have have given state utility commissions
authority to order utilities to refund the excess over some period
longer than three years.
   There was little debate in the committee before the bill was
rejected. Reps. Ronnie Flippo, D-Ala., and Ed Jenkins, D-Ga.,
argued that forcing quick refunds would cost consumers two or three
times the size of the refund several years down the road.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
