<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MinorityAffairs     10-11 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Minority Affairs,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>University of Mississippi Establishes Minority Affairs Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Mississippi freshmen must
take an academic course that covers social issues and tries to
engender an appreciation of cultural and ethnic diversity.
   The university on Tuesday also announced the creation of a
Minority Affairs Council to establish programs and policies to
increase minority participation in campus life.
   A school spokesman said the freshman course should begin in the
fall.
   Earlier this year, members of the school's Beta Theta Pi
fraternity stripped and bound two members, wrote racial slurs on
their bodies and dumped them on the campus of predominantly black
Rust College. The students contended they did not know their prank
had racial overtones.
   The school closed the fraternity for three years, expelled one
student and suspended four others for two years.
   The panel was established following a six-month study by the
Chancellor's Task Force on Minority Participation in Campus Life
and includes administrators, faculty and staff.
</TEXT>
