<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AppalachianHomecoming     10-11 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Appalachian Homecoming,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Expected for 10th Appalachian Museum Homecoming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORRIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Music by such groups as the Smoky Mountain
Boys along with demonstrations of such frontier arts as and lye
soap-making are expected to draw thousands to the 10th Appalachian
Museum Homecoming.
   Thursday through Sunday, the museum 16 miles north of Knoxville
will play host to 480 crafts people, musicians, singers, authors
and celebrities for the celebration of Appalachian pioneer life.
   ``So many of the older people look forward to this for literally
months and weeks before the homecoming. They will talk about who
they met for a long time afterwards,'' said museum founder and
homecoming organizer John Rice Irwin.
   For $6 a head, visitors can learn how to make lye soap, corn
shuck dolls and flowers, hickory bark baskets, braided rugs, gourd
items, knives, saws, skillets, glass, brooms and more.
   The demonstrations will be given by people who learned those
skills as part of everyday life, Irwin said.
   ``It is just amazing how rapidly the culture has changed so that
younger folks don't have any idea what their grandparents did,''
Irwin said Tuesday.
   ``So many of the revivalists in the craft business are great
people, but as you would surmise, it's just not the same as doing
it like you have since childhood.''
   The expected 35,000 visitors also can sample freshly made apple
butter, sassafras tea, parched corn, molasses, bread, cream and
butter.
   Music is a large part of the homecoming, including performers
such as Grandpa Jones; Grammy-winning songwriter Jimmy Driftwood,
known for the hit ``Battle of New Orleans''; songwriter, musician
and river boat pilot John Hartford, known for the hit ``Gentle on
My Mind''; Roy Acuff's Smoky Mountain Boys; the Bottom of the
Barrel Bunch and a band called Dismembered Tennesseans.
   The celebration also will feature appearances by regional and
nationally recognized writers such as ``Roots'' author Alex Haley,
who lives nearby.
   The pioneer museum in the hills of eastern Tennessee is a
60-acre collection of original pioneer buildings and paraphernalia.
   Its first homecoming consisted mostly of a few crafts people and
some authors trying to sell books. But word of the annual festivity
spread by mouth and the event grew in attendance.
   ``I don't have a right to stop it,'' Irwin said. ``It would be
like a preacher deciding to disband the church.''
</TEXT>
