<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--India-Jobs     10-11 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--India-Jobs,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Announces $390 Million Jobs Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday unveiled a $390
million plan to provide 1 million jobs a year for the poor in
India's urban centers.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi announced the plan in Parliament,
saying it would create new jobs, finance entrepreneurs and build
new housing.
   According to government figures, about 10 million people are
unemployed and 34 percent of its 880 million people live below the
poverty line, defined as being able to afford a daily diet of 2,000
calories.
   The job program, named for former Prime Minister Jawaharlal
Nehru, will cost $390 million annually and be implemented
immediately, Gandhi said.
   Several development programs this year have been named for Nehru
because Nov. 14 is the centennial of his birth. Nehru was
independent India's first prime minister and Gandhi's grandfather.
   When Gandhi announced the plan in the upper house, opposition
members booed and shouted, ``Corrupt Rajiv Gandhi, resign!
Resign!'' The opposition demands Gandhi's resignation following
newspaper allegations of corruption in a $1.4 billion artillery
deal with a Swedish company.
</TEXT>
