<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1456EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--AffordableTickets     10-11 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Affordable Tickets,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theater Tickets Went for As Low As a Penny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tickets that normally cost $24 went for
as little as 1 cent, but Trinity Repertory Theater's experiment
with letting patrons pay what they wanted was a success, a
spokeswoman said Wednesday.
   ``We got about 240 people, which is a lot more than we
expected'' on Tuesday for a preview performance in the 550-seat
theater, Suzanne Fortier said.
   The audience for the performance of Maxim Gorky's ``Summerfolk''
ranged ``from students to elderly from the apartment up the
street,'' she said.
   Based on similar experiments in Baltimore and San Diego,
Trinity's managing director, E. Timothy Langan, said he expected
people would pay $3 to $4.
   Fortier said most people paid $5 to $10. ``We got everything
from a penny a ticket to $20 a ticket,'' she said. The only rule
was that no one got in free.
   The theater had yet to compile figures on revenue for the
evening.
   Langan said the theater had set aside $5,000 from a grant to
cover the costs of the experiment.
   Fortier said the experiment likely would be repeated.
</TEXT>
