<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-11 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROARING SPRING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglers antsy to hit the lake
whenever the mood strikes need not worry about buzzing up Gerlane
Berkheimer's bait shop any time of the day or night.
   Mrs. Berkheimer and her family have run an around-the-clock bait
business for a decade in this community 12 miles from Raystown Lake.
   The demand at odd hours for minnows, worms and fishing supplies
was reinforced about seven years ago when Mrs. Berkheimer's
husband, Daryl, was hospitalized one night, leaving the business
unattended.
   A fisherman got the shop's door off the hinges, took some bait,
left $11 and a note and put the door back, said Mrs. Berkheimer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newfangled push-button device for
guarding against germs on toilet seats has Alan Brill flushed with
excitement.
   Brill, a former advertising agent, is distributing the
Swiss-made devices that include a special toilet seat attached to a
spool of plastic wrap, which rolls out in place of conventional
paper seat covers.
   ``People are paranoid about what you can contract from a toilet
seat,'' said Brill, whose company has installed hundreds of the
devices in Florida and Georgia. ``If you have a toilet seat covered
with paper, the paper could absorb moisture that could go right to
your skin.''
   Brill's customers include hotels, country clubs and restaurants.
   The device sells for $250 to $280 and can be leased for $15 to
$19 a month. A case of 12 rolls of replacement plastic costs
$48.95, with each spool providing 90 sittings worth.
   Brill said he picked up an interest in bathroom hygiene from his
father, who considered toilet seats unsanitary. Brill first saw the
Hygolet seat demonstrated in 1985.
   ``I thought it was the greatest thing since electricity,'' he
said. ``You could freely sit on a toilet seat without worrying
about who sat on it before you.''
</TEXT>
