<FIRST>r a AM-Sullivan-HallofFame     10-11 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-Hall of Fame,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Criticize Group for Honoring Police Commissioner During 60s
Strife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black officials criticized an
association for honoring the late L.B. Sullivan, the city's police
commissioner during the civil rights turmoil in the 60s and a
participant in a historic libel lawsuit.
   ``L.B. Sullivan was a famous racist and hater of black people
and anything they stood for,'' said Montgomery County Commissioner
Frank Bray after the Alabama Peace Officers Association announced
that Sullivan would be installed Wednesday in its Hall of Fame.
   ``I think it was very inappropriate,'' said state Rep. Alvin
Holmes. ``He promoted segregation and racism in the city.''
   However, a third black official, Montgomery City Councilman
Joseph Dickerson, said he has no harsh feelings about the induction
of Sullivan, who was Montgomery's police commissioner from
1959-1967.
   ``The police commissioner's actions during the 1960s were a sign
of the times,'' he said. ``He was playing a role. If he was the
police commissioner today, he would be playing a completely
different role.''
   Murfee Gewin, executive director of the Peace Officers
Association, said the induction was based on Sullivan's overall
contribution to law enforcement.
   ``He was prominent in the field of advanced training of law
enforcement officers and in increasing their abilities through
continuing education,'' Gewin said. ``This is a career award.''
   Sullivan sued The New York Times in 1960 after it ran an
advertisement soliciting funds for the legal defense of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. The ad said Montgomery police, armed with
guns and tear gas, surrounded a black college after a student
demonstration.
   Sullivan won the libel suit and a $500,000 judgment when the
case was tried in Montgomery, Alabama's capital. But the U.S.
Supreme Court eventually overturned the verdict on appeal,
establishing libel precedent in the process.
   The court, ruling in what became known in libel case history as
Sullivan vs. The New York Times, asserted that public officials who
sue for libel must show that the story, even if false, was
published with malice, with knowledge the story was false or with
``reckless disregard'' for whether it was true or false. The
court's decision also established a higher standard of evidence to
prove malice.
   Sullivan, who was state public safety director from 1951-1955,
also served as state prison commissioner in the early 1970s when
Alabama's overcrowded prisons came under federal court scrutiny. He
was on then-Attorney General Bill Baxley's staff as executive
assistant when he died in 1977 at age 56.
</TEXT>
