<FIRST>r i AM-Thatcher-Heirs     10-11 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher-Heirs,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Race to Succeed Thatcher Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the fringes of this week's annual
convention of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
Party, the race to succeed her has begun.
   In a party she has dominated for 14 years, and which prides
itself on loyalty to the leader in good times and bad, the language
is coded and the jockeying discreet.
   After 10 years as prime minister, Mrs. Thatcher remains firmly
in control of her party and intent on several more years in office.
She is greeted with undimmed enthusiasm as she arrives daily in the
convention center to sit attentively through hours of debates and
speeches by her Cabinet ministers.
   By tradition, a prolonged standing ovation is guaranteed when
she winds up the convention on Friday, her 64th birthday, with her
keynote address.
   But Mrs. Thatcher's public opinion poll ratings are at an
eight-year low, the pound is sliding, interest rates are soaring
and headlines warn of economic crisis.
   Thus speculation about the succession is inevitable, and outside
the Winter Gardens conference hall in this north England seaside
resort, two of the top hopefuls, ex-Defense Secretary Michael
Heseltine and Deputy Prime Minister Sir Geoffrey Howe, are playing
to packed houses.
   Howe said Wednesday that Conservatives ``must show that we are
good, not just at winning battles, but at winning arguments and
winning friends.
   ``We must choose the style to match the mood of Britain ...
making sure that people recognize us as a listening party, just as
much as a crusading one,'' Howe added at a crowded fringe meeting.
   Decoded, Howe's statement was a clear criticism of Mrs.
Thatcher's combative style, and the image she projects of lacking
compassion toward the have-nots in the entrepreneurial Britain she
has tried to create.
   Howe, 62, whose mild-mannered style is the antithesis of Mrs.
Thatcher's, was removed as foreign secretary last summer in what
was widely seen as a demotion.
   Heseltine, 56, a temperamental politician who stalked out of the
Thatcher Cabinet in 1986 during a dispute over the takeover of an
ailing helicopter-maker, Westland, topped two public opinion polls
last week as the favorite to succeed Mrs. Thatcher.
   Howe was also among the top six potential successors, along with
former party chief Norman Tebbit, Transport Secretary Cecil
Parkinson, and ex-Education Secretary Kenneth Baker, now party
chairman.
   At a standing-room only fringe meeting in a Victorian theater,
Heseltine hinted that the Thatcher government _ presiding over a
record trade deficit _ was letting Britain slip back into the old
ills of high-wage, low-productivity industry.
   ``Truth does not change simply because it is 10 years old,''
thundered the tall, self-made millionaire. ``Britain is not paying
its way.''
   Heseltine, a rank-and-file lawmaker, has been doing what all
ambitious politicians do while waiting in the wings: going for the
grass roots by campaigning tirelessly up and down the country.
   He never criticizes Mrs. Thatcher herself, and when asked about
his leadership aspirations, his stock response is that he'll do
whatever the party asks.
   The leader of the Conservative Party is chosen by its members of
Parliament, and if the party has a parliamentary majority, the
leader automatically becomes prime minister.
   Mrs. Thatcher has won three successive elections, and it is
generally assumed she will lead the party into the next election,
which must be held by mid-1992.
   But the Tories are trailing the opposition Labor Party by an
average of seven points in a string of recent opinion polls. Labor
has been consistently ahead for the past four months.
   Now, to take the shine of the Tory convention, interest rates
are at 15 percent, double the rate of June 1988. Inflation, which
Mrs. Thatcher vowed to eradicate, is at 7.3 percent, and the pound
has suddenly weakened.
   The downturn could be just a phase, as Mrs. Thatcher's
supporters insist. But if it is worse than that, and she looks like
losing the next election, she might have to make way for a
candidate with better prospects.
   Commented London's liberal Guardian newspaper, ``If and when ...
there actually is a vote for the leadership of the Conservative
party to succeed Mrs. Thatcher, it may be judged that the race
began ... in Blackpool.''

</TEXT>
