<DOCNO> AP891011-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1457EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Lutherans-Divestment     10-11 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutherans-Divestment,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lutheran Body Facing Challenge Over South African Divestment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute over church pension funds invested
in companies operating in South Africa is dividing members of the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America as its pension board
prepares to meet this week.
   A resolution ordering the board to divest all South African
holdings by Sept. 1, 1991, was approved in August at the
denomination's first churchwide meeting since the 1987 merger of
the Lutheran Church in America, the American Lutheran Church and
the Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
   At least one congregation, Advent Lutheran Church in the St.
Paul suburb of Roseville, has authorized a lawsuit to prevent the
pension board from divesting, says its pastor, Thomas Basich.
   ``Nobody is for apartheid; I think it's awful,'' said Basich.
``The issue here is whether or not political considerations should
enter into investment decisions without approval of the 26,000
people who are members of the pension fund and beneficiaries of the
pension fund.''
   The Rev. Joseph W. Ellwanger, of Cross Lutheran Church in
Milwaukee, counters: ``The bottom line must not be financial return
but what is morally right.''
   ``The other point is that investments in non-South African
companies have indeed yielded as much as, and, in many cases, more
than companies involved in South Africa,'' said Ellwanger, acting
treasurer of Pension Members for Justice, a grassroots Lutheran
organization advocating divestiture to pressure South Africa to end
its policy of racial segregation known as apartheid.
   At stake is the denomination's $1.6 billion pension fund, of
which $84.9 million is invested in companies that do business in
South Africa.
   Some members of the independently incorporated pension board
based in Minneapolis also oppose the resolution. Board President
John Kapanke has said the board, at its monthly meeting here
Thursday through Saturday, will consider seeking a court judgment
on whether the board can totally divest within the bounds of its
fiduciary responsibility.
   ``It is our opinion that the timeline as proposed puts the board
in an almost impossible situation if it is to divest within a
prudent policy,'' Kapanke said during the August convention.
   It is unclear how many of the 21-member pension board oppose
divestment, or whether they have the authority to defy the
assembly, Kapanke said.
   ``They are going to try to weigh the directive of the churchwide
assembly with the fiduciary responsibility of the members,'' he
said.
   If the board fails to meet the 1991 deadline, Kapanke said
church members could institute a procedure to remove members.
   Several Protestant denominations, notably the Episcopal Church,
the United Church of Christ, the Church of the Brethren and the
Quakers already have strong divestment policies at varying stages
of implementation, said Donna Katzin. She is director of South
Africa programs for the Interfaith Center on Corporate
Responsibility in New York, an ecumenical coalition of the Lutheran
body.
   However, the Lutheran pension board believes it's the first U.S.
religious denomination to set a specific date for divestment, she
said.
   Ellwanger said the pension board knew the resolution was
imminent because the new denomination's constituting convention in
1987 passed a similar resolution.
   ``I'm not sure that any deadline would be satisfactory to John
Kapanke and people against divestment,'' Ellwanger said.
   Basich said he doesn't believe divestiture is an ethical way to
end apartheid. ``I don't think it's right for people who live
10,000 miles away to wreck another country's economy. Who's going
to gain by that?''
   He said members already have the option of putting their pension
money in ``South Africa free'' funds but that only 13 percent of
pension fund contributions have been so earmarked.
   Kapanke said investments in non-South African companies have
performed well. ``Through August 31, the social purposes equity
fund (non-South African investments) was up about 28 percent,'' he
said.
   An estimated 85 percent of the convention's 1,041 delegates
voted for the divestment deadline, but Kapanke said delegates
didn't fully understand the issue and called for a vote on the
matter by pension plan members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
