<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1500EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-FloridaAbortion 3rdLd-Writethru a0624 10-11 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Abortion, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0624,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TIGHTENS lead, SUBS 8th graf pvs, `Gustafson and ...' to ADD
that session was to last through Friday.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature today killed 10 more
anti-abortion bills favored by Gov. Bob Martinez and sped toward
early adjournment without disturbing Florida's abortion law.
   ``A right, having been established, is not easily removed,''
said House Speaker Tom Gustafson, a Democrat.
   Four bills in the Republican governor's package were killed on
Tuesday, the first day of a special session he convened to take
advantage of a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in July opening the door
to more restrictive abortion laws.
   Today, the Senate Health Care Committee voted 5-2 to kill a
proposed constitutional amendment restricting abortions to cases of
rape or incest or when the mother's health is in danger or the
fetus deformed.
   Later, the panel defeated three proposals to tighten clinic
regulations, and a House subcommittee rejected six bills that
mirrored the Senate measures.
   ``I don't think it's a moment for rejoicing,'' Martinez said
after the first defeat of the day. ``If anything, it's a moment of
sadness.''
   The proceedings were the nation's first special session on
abortion since the U.S. Supreme Court upheld a restrictive Missouri
abortion law.
   Gustafson and Senate President Bob Crawford, also a Democrat,
said they expected both houses to adjourn by late afternoon. The
special session was to have lasted through Friday.
   ``I think the Legislature was reflecting the will of the
people,'' said Crawford.
   Only a handful of spectators attended today's proceedings, and
virtually none of the estimated 10,000 demonstraters in town Monday
and Tuesday were visible today at the Capitol.
   In recent weeks, the first-term governor has focused on the
issue of regulating clinics more closely. Three South Florida
clinics have been closed by the state in the last two weeks after
inspectors found unhealthy conditions.
   On Tuesday, about 1,000 abortion-rights activists celebrated
outside the Capitol.
   ``The real news story is that nothing is going to happen here,''
Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion Rights
Action League, told a cheering crowd. ``Martinez is suffering a
very embarrassing defeat.''
   Florida lawmakers convened in the afternoon amid tight security
after more than 10,000 pro-choice and anti-abortion demonstrators
held rallies. Police guarded the doors to the Democratic-controlled
Senate and House chambers.
   The abortion-rights side sang ``America the Beautiful'' and
hired an airplane to trail a banner reading, ``Keep Abortion
Legal.'' Anti-abortionist activists wore T-shirts with the words:
``Spoken As a Former Fetus ... I'm Glad I'm Here.''
   Police made two arrests. A 14-year-old was charged with a
misdemeanor for wearing a derogatory message on his jacket that
referred to the governor, and a 49-year-old abortion-rights
supporter was jailed on charges of striking a man in the face with
a video camera.
   Martinez's proposals that were defeated by the Senate Health and
Rehabilitative Services Committee included a ban on use of public
financing and public hospitals for abortions and a requirement for
viability tests on the fetuses of women who are at least 20 weeks
pregnant.
   Those bills were defeated 9-3, as was a proposal that would have
required women to wait a week and undergo counseling before having
an abortion.
   The committee said a bill to establish a state adoption center
to promote adoption as an alternative to abortion was a good idea,
but defeated it 8-4. Lawmakers said it should be taken up again
when the Legislature considers child abuse reform next month.
   The committee action Tuesday ``was a blow to the unborn,'' said
Ken Conner, president of the Florida Right to Life.
   Elsewhere, a legislative committee Tuesday in Springfield, Ill.,
heard pro-choice advocates decry proposed curbs on late-term
abortions, but the panel chairman said the bill probably would go
to the House without major changes.
   In Harrisburg, Pa., a lawmaker introduced a bill to eliminate a
law requiring rape and incest victims to report the crimes before
they can get publicly funded abortions. A House committee set a
hearing on a series of abortion-related bills for Friday.
</TEXT>
