<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Temple     10-11 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Temple,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militant Jewish Group Plans to Lay Cornerstone for New Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN SCHECHET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of militant Israelis is preparing to
lay a three-ton cornerstone next week in hopes of eventually
rebuilding the ancient Jewish Temple, angering Arabs and some
fellow Jews.
   ``This is the answer to the intefadeh (Palestinian uprising) and
the answer to those who are trying to destroy us,'' Gershon
Salomon, chairman of the Temple Mount Faithful movement, said
Wednesday.
   The group wants to rebuild the temple that was destroyed by the
Romans in 70 A.D. An earlier temple, built by King Solomon, was
destroyed by the Babylonians in 587 B.C.
   Such a plan is provocative because the 35-acre site where the
ancient temples stood includes the spot where Moslems believe the
prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven.
   The platform's two mosques, the Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa,
are the holiest Islamic places of worship after Mecca and Medina in
Saudi Arabia.
   The Temple Mount Faithful initially planned to lay the
cornerstone on the platform, but police denied them permission,
Salomon said. Instead, the cornerstone will be placed ``in the
meantime'' near the ramp leading to the Moghrabi Gate of the mount,
he said.
   The ceremony is scheduled for Monday.
   Jerusalem police spokesman Uzi Sandori confirmed the Temple
Mount Faithful has permission for a ceremony near the gate.
   ``If it causes a disturbance or damage, we will of course stop
them,'' Sandori said.
   Adnan Husseini, director general of the Moslem trust that
administers the mosques, said he did not know what Moslem reaction
would be.
   ``They know well that the Moslems know how to take care of their
mosques,'' Husseini said. ``The police and God will save the
mosques because they are for people praying.''
   Rabbi Richard G. Hirsch, executive director of the World Union
for Progressive Judaism, the international office for Reform
Judaism, criticized Salomon and his movement.
   ``I consider their version of Judaism to be a perversion of
Judaism and their acts to be a retrogressive negative force,'' he
told The Associated Press.
   He added: ``We consider any attempt at this time to inject an
issue such as a reconstruction of a Temple in Jerusalem to be a
negative, divisive, deleterious force.''
   A spokesman for Conservative Jews said Salomon and his group
were motivated by politics, not religion.
   ``He is attempting to make a political provocation, and we are
very opposed to this,'' said Rabbi Ehud Bandel, director of the
Conservative Movement's education and outreach department.
   Salomon said he did not care what the Arab reaction would be.
   ``I don't want to hear an answer from the Arabs,'' he said. ``We
think that the Arab period in Israel and on the Temple Mount has
come to an end.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
