<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1554EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-ArmsTalks     10-11 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Arms Talks,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pact Won't be Ready by Summit, Congressman Predicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Soviet pact reducing strategic nuclear
arms is unlikely before President Bush's summit next year with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, a leading House Republican
said Wednesday.
   Rep. William S. Broomfield of Michigan, ranking GOP member on
the House Foreign Affairs Committee, said unresolved issues will
delay a superpower agreement.
   Broomfield recently met with arms control negotiators during a
congressional delegation's trip to Geneva. He based his comments on
statements made by the Soviets negotiators, including the chief
negotiator, Yuriy Nazarkin.
   ``The Soviet negotiators view the likelihood (of a START treaty)
as very doubtful'' prior to the summit scheduled for late spring or
early summer next year, Broomfield said in an interview.
   The lawmaker said a number of ``troubling'' problems still have
to be worked out. He declined to provide specifics.
   However, Broomfield said he is optimistic that a U.S.-Soviet
agreement will be reached to slash the superpowers' store of
long-range nuclear missiles by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   ``Eventually,'' he said. ``It won't be a rushed job ... for
signing at the summit.''
   Shortly after meetings last month in Wyoming between Secretary
of State James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, Bush indicated that a strategic arms control treaty
was possible.
   ``Yes, I do,'' the president said in response to questions on
the chance of a treaty. ``I think the setting of a summit will
perhaps serve as a catalyst for moving forward.
   ``But it's not a given, it's not absolutely certain that that's
going to happen. But I would agree that we have a good likelihood
that might happen,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
