<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1556EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Blast     10-11 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Blast,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Killed in Bomb Blast Under Police Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected tribal militants detonated a
bomb under a police bus in northeastern India on Wednesday, killing
11 people, news reports said. Seven of the dead were policemen.
   Press Trust of India said the blast occurred on a remote, hilly
road in Assam state's Nalbari district, 850 miles east of New Delhi.
   Besides the police, the dead were the driver of the bus and
three civilians who had hitched a ride, the news agency said.
   The bomb, detonated by remote control, was believed to have been
planted by extremists of the Bodo tribe who are fighting to set up
an independent homeland in Assam, a hilly state bordering
Bangladesh and Bhutan, the news agency said.
   The area is a militant stronghold. The tribes took to arms two
years ago, and at least 290 people have been killed in violence
this year.
   The government has refused to break up Assam into two states but
says it is willing to hold talks with the militants who allege
discrimination in jobs and education by the state's majority
non-tribal population.
   The Bodos, mostly farmers, were animists before they converted
earlier this century to Christianity and Hinduism, India's dominant
religion.
   The Bodos make up about 30 percent of Assam's 20 million people.
</TEXT>
