<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-EasternEurope 360   10-11 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Eastern Europe, 360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cracks Appearing in Eastern European Anti-Reform Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cracks are appearing in the once solid
anti-reform communist governments of East Germany and
Czechoslovakia although there's been no real progress toward
democracy, senior State Department officials said Wednesday.
   The officials pointed to recent moves by the mayors and other
authorities in Leipzig and Dresden, East Germany, to open a
dialogue with pro-democracy demonstrators as an indication
resistance may be growing to the communist government's anti-reform
stance.
   ``There seems to be some indication of a split,'' Richard
Schifter, assistant secretary of state for human rights told the
House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   ``It could be that some people see the handwriting is on the
wall and prefer to go with change rather than sticking with the old
men'' who rule East Germany, Schifter said.
   Curtis Kamman, deputy assistant secretary of state for European
affairs, agreed that the mayors' action could be significant.
   ``I hope that that continues and that it represents movement,''
he said.
   Kamman said that while the role of the Communist party remains
paramount in East Germany, Czechoslovakia, Romania and Bulgaria,
the ferment of the Democratic reform movement in Poland and Hungary
``cannot fail to have an impact.''
   ``Already splits are occuring in the formerly solid anti-reform
regime front in (East Germany) and Czechoslovakia, although both
still have a long way to go,'' Kamman said.
   Kamman said he believes change is so far advanced in Poland and
Hungary, where a ``genuine rebirth of politics is under way,'' that
it is difficult to see how it could be reversed.
   ``It is very hard to go in another direction unless you bring
repressive force to bear, and I don't think anyone in those
countries wants to do that,'' Kamman said.
   Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., co-chairman of the watchdog Commission
on Security and Cooperation in Europe, told the panel that despite
official resistance and oppression, ``the thousands of East Germans
marching to the American civil rights song `We Shall Overcome' ...
bring hope that independent activity will broaden and become a
powerful force for reform.''
</TEXT>
