<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Dissidents 1stLd-Writethru a0594 10-11 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Dissidents, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0594,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Fails to Appeal in Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to ADD report from sources on
Devaty.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights activist who has
gone underground failed to appear in the Brno regional court
Wednesday to appeal his sentence, witnesses said.
   Stanislav Devaty was sentenced to 20 months in prison on Aug. 29
on charges of ``inciting hostile moods in the population'' after he
was involved in ``production of printed material and organized
petitions in its support,'' the state news agency CTK said.
   Devaty, 37, was released from custody after the sentencing
pending an appeal of his conviction, and he apparently went
underground after that.
   Activist Jana Petrova brought a letter from Devaty to the Brno
court in which he said he would remain underground until the
charges were annulled, emigre sources in Vienna said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   After the sentence was pronounced, Devaty said, ``None of us
doubts that this trial should be considered a political trial.''
   Vaclav Havel, the banned playwright and unofficial leader of
Czechoslovak opposition, called Devaty's decision to go underground
``an experiment and a very respectable decision ... in continuity
with his attitude,'' speaking to reporters outside the courtroom
Wednesday.
   Devaty was initially detained March 16, as part of a mass
crackdown on dissent that included the jailing of Havel and other
leading activists.
   Devaty was tried in connection with a petition signed by more
than 400 people calling for more religious an cultural freedom and
the release of all political prisoners.
   Havel, meanwhile, said he had not known in advance about the
publication of his picture and a birthday greeting in the Communist
Party daily newspaper Rude Pravo.
   A picture of Havel appeared in the paper Saturday with an
accompanying birthday greeting to Ferdinand Vanek, a name Havel
used in some of his plays.
   The message said Havel's ``friends and colleagues thank him for
the hard work he has done and is still doing in his life, send many
greetings and wish him a lot of success in his work.'' Havel turned
53 on Oct. 5.
   Havel's picture has not appeared in the official Czechoslovak
press since the 1968 Soviet-led invasion that quashed the ``Prague
Spring'' liberalization reforms of Alexander Dubcek. It was printed
in the personal columns apparently unwittingly by the paper's
editors.
   ``I consider it a good prank, but I certainly did not do it,''
Havel said about the publication of the picture under the
pseudonym. ``It is not my habit to congratulate myself.''
   ``It was done by a group of admirers unknown to me, but I thank
them, it made me very happy,'' Havel told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview.
</TEXT>
