<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OceanService     10-11 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ocean Service,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tippie Takes Over Ocean Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Kay Tippie took office Wednesday as
director of the National Ocean Service.
   Tippie, sworn in a day earlier, became the first woman to head a
division of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   The service prepares the nation's nautical and aeronautical
charts, predicts tides, monitors coastal pollution, manages the
National Marine Sanctuaries and collects a wide range of coastal
and ocean data.
   Tippie had directed the agency's estuarine programs since 1986.
Before that, she directed the Environmental Protection Agency's
Chesapeake Bay Program and served as executive director of the
University of Rhode Island's Center for Ocean Management Studies.
   The ocean service is one of five NOAA divisions. The others are
the National Weather Service, National Environmental Satellite,
Data and Information Service, National Marine Fisheries Service and
the Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research.
</TEXT>
