<DOCNO> AP891011-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Pauley-Today     10-11 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pauley-Today,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jane Pauley's ``Today'' Past Noted, Her ``Today'' Future Uncertain.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Jane Pauley's 39th birthday looming and her
13th year on ``Today'' noted, the only question Wednesday was
whether she'd stay on the top-rated, troubled morning show. Neither
she nor NBC would say.
   All NBC News would say in response to a published report that
Pauley probably would leave the show at year's end was that Pauley,
who has two years left on her contract, would stay at the network.
   ``As Jane Pauley has stated, she will be staying on with NBC
News,'' NBC said in a statement. ``Conversations about specifics
are concluding now and we expect to announce our mutual plans
shortly.''
   Pauley, who didn't return phone calls on the 13th anniversary of
her joining the show, reportedly has been upset over changes at
``Today,'' including a switch of news anchors in which ``NBC News
at Sunrise'' anchor Deborah Norville last month was made the
``Today'' news anchor.
   That job had been held by John Palmer, a former White House
correspondent, since 1982. He now anchors the earlier ``Sunrise.''
   There has been speculation, about which NBC won't comment, that
Norville is being considered as the next ``Today'' co-anchor. She
was given a five-year contract in August.
   Peggy Hubble, an NBC News spokeswoman, declined to say Wednesday
when or if Pauley will be leaving ``Today,'' which she co-anchors
with Bryant Gumbel.
   ``We're discussing her role with NBC News,'' Hubble said. As for
``Today'' and Pauley, she said, ``I think it's premature to make
any specific announcement.'' She said she didn't know when one
would be made.
   NBC News president Michael Gartner, NBC Sports president Dick
Ebersol, who oversees ``Today,'' and Pauley's agent, Ralph Mann,
did not return calls. Secretaries said the three executives were
out.
   Pauley, who turns 39 on Oct. 31, succeeded Barbara Walters, the
first female co-anchor of ``Today,'' in 1976.
   At that time, Walters left to join ABC after 15 years on
``Today,'' on which she started as a writer. She now co-anchors
``20-20'' for ABC News and celebrity-interview specials for ABC
Entertainment.
   Both Pauley and Norville, 31, came to NBC News after anchor work
at NBC-owned WMAQ-TV in Chicago. Norville joined NBC in January
1987.
   Gumbel started Wednesday's ``Today'' broadcast by noting that
Pauley began on the show 13 years ago that day. ``That's a long
time. Is that a lifetime?'' he asked her.
   ``It's a long time. It's my whole adult life, virtually,''
Pauley responded. ``Thank you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
