<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1652EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PrisonEscape     10-11 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Escape,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Lay Trail of False Clues of `Escape,' Hide in Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY DAUBENMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two inmates planted false clues hinting
that they had escaped from the world's largest walled prison and
then hid inside the facility for a week while authorities conducted
a three-state, $100,000 manhunt.
   The two men concealed themselves in a four-foot hollowed-out
stack of boxes and apparently planned to scale the walls of the
State Prison of Southern Michigan at Jackson when the search died
down, said Department of Corrections spokeswoman Gail Light.
   However, Detective Sgt. Jerry Boyer said Wednesday no one is
red-faced about falling for the ploy by David Bellah, 42, and
Steven Mikko, 27, who were found Tuesday after officials were
tipped to their hiding place.
   ``I'm not embarrassed in the least bit. We had information to
believe these guys were outside and we followed up on it,'' he
said. `` ... If you have a crow pie that you want me to eat, I'd be
glad to.''
   Boyer estimated state police spent more than $100,000 searching
for the inmates within Michigan. The search extended to Indiana and
Nevada, where Bellah and Mikko had friends and relatives.
   The two, discovered missing on Oct. 4 during a routine count,
were thought to have walked out disguised as guards, Boyer said,
because negatives left in their cells indicated they had made false
badges and a note said they had bought guard uniforms for $250.
   Mikko also arranged for a cousin who lived in the area to call a
probation officer to say she had been asked to pick up the two on
the day of the reported escape in Rives Junction, about 10 miles
north of Jackson, Boyer said.
   ``It certainly leads a reasonable person to believe they had
escaped from prison,'' said Boyer, adding that the size of the
57-acre institution made it difficult to search it thoroughly.
   Light said prison officials were suspicious and received several
tips that the two were still inside the prison.
   ``The evidence left in the cell was so obvious we had some
doubts whether it was legitimate evidence or whether they were
trying to distract us,'' she said. Light declined to reveal the
source of Tuesday's tip that paid off.
   ``We searched the prison every single day and continuously since
they left. We never stopped looking for these guys,'' said Marcia
Bailey, administrative assistant to the warden at Jackson.
   Bellah was convicted of killing a Lansing police officer during
a 1977 bank robbery. Mikko is serving 25-40 years on an armed
robbery conviction in Montcalm County.
   The two went undetected in a hollowed out, four-foot stack of
boxes in a furniture factory on the prison grounds even though the
area had been searched with tracking dogs, Bailey said.
   Light said a spring mechanism allowed the men to tighten the
metal strap on the outside of the stack to make it appear the stack
of boxes was solid.
   The pair had a homemade grappling hook and 84 feet of rope made
from nylon laundry bags. They apparently intended to scale the
28-foot prison wall, she said.
   The two had a supply of apples, candy bars and water, and
officials speculated that other inmates brought them food, Light
said.
   Bailey said the men were armed with crude knives but offered no
resistance when found.
   They are being held in administrative segregation and Bailey
said they will face misconduct hearings. They could be placed in a
higher custody level and have time outside their cells restricted.
   Before the escape, the men were listed as ``close custody''
prisoners, a level below maximum security, and could leave their
cells during the day for work and recreation.
   Jackson County Prosecuting Attorney Joseph Filip said no
criminal charges will be filed. The potential two- to five-year
sentences would have less impact than prison disciplinary steps, he
said, noting Bellah already is serving a mandatory life sentence.
   Authorities said Mikko had attempted escapes at least twice
before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
