<FIRST>u w AM-Thornburgh'sTravels 690   10-11 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh's Travels, 690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Travels Cost Twice As Much as Predecessor: Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's trips cost
the government more than twice as much as those taken by his
predecessor during a nearly comparable period, the Justice
Department said Wednesday.
   Thornburgh's 47 trips aboard government aircraft between Oct. 7,
1988, and Sept. 4 cost $154,618, compared with $74,247 Attorney
General Edwin Meese spent during his last 10 months in office,
according to records furnished by spokesman David Runkel.
   Runkel attributed much of the increased expense to three flights
aboard U.S. Marshals Service airplanes that cost $80,171.
   ``The only difference is when you include the incredible charges
of the Marshals Service,'' he said.
   Travel records show that a Marshals Service twin-engine jet flew
from Oklahoma City to Pittsburgh on May 16 to pick up Thornburgh at
9:40 a.m. and fly him back to Washington at a cost of $5,260.
   The night before, Thornburgh had flown from Washington to
Pittsburgh aboard an FBI turboprop plane. That trip cost $730,
according to FBI records.
   While in Pittsburgh, Thornburgh voted in the Pennsylvania
primary, spoke to FBI agents at the local field office and was
interviewed by radio station KDKA.
   A letter the Marshals Service's public affairs chief, Stephen T.
Boyle, wrote last week to two news organizations detailing the
expenses said the plane for the Pittsburgh-to-Washington flight was
requested May 12.
   Boyle said he didn't know why Thornburgh requested the plane.
   Thornburgh's tab at the Marshals Service also includes $46,792
for an Aug. 6-9 trip to Mexico City for a meeting with Mexican
officials and to Honolulu where the attorney general addressed the
American Bar Association convention, according to Boyle's letter,
written in response to queries by The New York Times and Los
Angeles Times.
   Runkel made Boyle's letter and a similar response by FBI
spokesman Milt Ahlerich available to reporters.
   Thornburgh and five aides flew aboard a Marshals Service Boeing
727 airliner from San Francisco to Honolulu because the plane used
during the earlier legs of the trip was unable to fly non-stop from
the West Coast to Hawaii, Runkel said.
   The Boeing 727, normally used to transport prisoners, was
pressed into service because another plane that Thornburgh
originally planned to use for the entire trip had broken down
before he left Washington, Runkel said.
   A June 12-14 trip to Texas aboard a twin-engine Marshals Service
jet that flew from Oklahoma City to Washington to pick up
Thornburgh and several aides cost $28,118. The airplane was
requested two weeks in advance, according to Boyle's letter.
   The expense of the attorney general's travels also included what
it cost for aides to accompany him on the trips, Runkel said.
   Runkel said he didn't understand why the Marshals Service
billing system makes flights on its planes significantly more
expensive than those aboard FBI aircraft.
   Boyle said the Justice Department's management division ``went
over the bills in some detail before they reimbursed us to
determine if they were indeed valid and justifiable and apparently
felt they were because they paid the bill'' for all three flights.
   The Marshals Service includes the cost of fuel, Boyle said.
   The figures for Meese's travels covered the period from Oct. 1,
1987, until he left office Aug. 8, 1988. Runkel said $62,000 of the
$74,247 was for trips aboard FBI aircraft. Meese flew on commercial
airlines for the other trips.
   Runkel did not have figures for the number of trips Meese took.
   The total figures provided by Runkel include an additional three
weeks for Thornburgh, during which he spent $5,256 on travel.
   Thornburgh has been flying aboard government aircraft on the
advice of the FBI, which determined that his security
communications could not be guaranteed aboard commercial flights,
Runkel said.
   Thornburgh has traveled frequently because he wants to speak to
groups of federal prosecutors and law enforcement officials around
the country, Runkel said.
   ``That's part of his job to speak about what the Department of
Justice is doing,'' Runkel said.
</TEXT>
