<FIRST>u i AM-Pope     10-11 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Takes Pilgrimage to Catholic Enclave in Indonesia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One name only for Suharto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAUMERE, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II crossed the
Indonesian archipelago on Wednesday to take his pilgrimage to
Flores, the ``island of flowers,'' a Catholic stronghold in a sea
of Islam.
   The pope flew in a C-130 military transport after changing
planes in Dili, giving him a preview of his stop Thursday in East
Timor. Indonesian authorities had erected a billboard at the
airport with a picture of the pontiff and President Suharto that
says ``Welcome Pope John Paul II to Timor, Indonesia's 27th
Province.''
   Indonesian forces invaded the former Portuguese territory in
late 1975 and annexed it the following year.
   The dusty island of Flores prepared for days for the papal
visit, being overwhelmingly Catholic in the world's most populous
Moslem country. The Vatican estimates nearly 85 percent of Flores'
663,000 residents are Catholics.
   Roman Catholics number about 5 million in Indonesia, compared to
the 157 million Moslems.
   Lying offshore was an Indonesian warship, part of security
precautions for the pope's overnight stop. Church officials
expected about 250,000 people at a papal Mass in a soccer stadium.
   The pope told them Catholics can play an important role in
Indonesia.
   ``You understand the enormity of the task facing your country in
providing better education and training, more jobs and just wages,
and a more equitable distribution of the advantages of economic and
cultural development,'' he said.
   ``Your Christian faith urges you to be involved in this great
undertaking.''
   The pope flew 940 miles eastward from Jakarta to reach this
island that was first settled by Portuguese and Dutch explorers.
   Meanwhile, news reports in Lisbon, Portugal, said Wednesday that
nationalist rebels fighting Indonesian rule in East Timor called a
5-hour cease-fire in their 14-year-old guerrilla struggle while
John Paul visits the Southeast Asian territory.
   Abilio Araujo, a Lisbon-based official of the Revolutionary
Front for an Independent East Timor, or FRETILIN, said the
movement's central committee called the truce at a clandestine
meeting Tuesday in central Timor, the Portuguese news agency Lusa
reported.
   Araujo said the rebels called on their Catholic supporters to
attend the papal Mass and pray for withdrawal of Indonesian troops
from the territory.
   The Vatican does not recognize the annexation of East Timor and
has continued to keep the bishop of Timor under its direct control.
He is not a member of Indonesia's conference of bishops.
   John Paul's decision to visit the territory touched off
controversy. FRETILIN officials said the trip implies a tacit
recognition of the occupation.
   However, the pope told reporters accompanying his Asian tour
that to skip the territory would be an ``offense'' to East Timor's
Catholics.
   Human rights groups estimate about 100,000 Timorese have died
from fighting, famine or disease since the Indonesian invasion.
   Under international law, Portugal is still the administrative
power in East Timor.
</TEXT>
