<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-NATO     10-11 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-NATO,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, NATO Chief Reaffirm Goal of Reducing Forces in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and NATO Secretary General
Manfred Woerner reaffirmed Wednesday a commitment to reaching an
agreement with the Warsaw Pact within a year on reducing
conventional forces in Europe.
   Woerner, speaking with reporters after conferring at the White
House with Bush, said, ``I think there is reason for optimism.''
   ``Even if it takes more than one year _ if it takes 14 months or
15 months _ I think you can realistically expect an agreement
soon,'' said the NATO chief.
   Bush and Woerner also discussed the dramatic changes in Eastern
Europe and the future role of NATO.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said that in
addition to reaffirming their commitment to reaching a conventional
forces agreement within six to 12 months, the two leaders
``discussed a variety of alliance issues and developments in
Eastern Europe.''
   Bush praised Woerner's leadership at a time when the alliance is
charting a new course for NATO and for giving it ``the mission of
working to overcome the division of Europe,'' Fitzwater said.
   It was at the NATO summit in Brussels last May that Bush
unveiled his proposal for a steep pullback of U.S. and Soviet
troops from Europe.
   Woerner, who also met with Vice President Dan Quayle, said, ``We
are interested in a peaceful evolution, not in unrest, not in
upheaval, not in revolution'' in Eastern Europe.
   Woerner said NATO must ``be seen as an instrument of the
political management of change in East-West relationships'' as well
as ``the major source of stability in a time of transition.''
   Woerner said he saw no danger of waning public support for NATO
in the West as expectations rise for political and economic reforms
in the Eastern Bloc.
   ``We have to explain to our publics that you can only guarantee
peace and stability as long as you have this NATO,'' he said.
   If there were ``unfortunate developments in the East,'' he said,
it is ``only as long as NATO exists, only as long as we keep up our
guard, (that) Soviet politicians know that there is only one way to
solve their problems, the peaceful one; that there is no way to go
militarily, that there is no chance for military adventures.''
   ``We try to support the forces of reform and to support (Soviet
President Mikhail) Gorbachev insofar as he opens up the society,
improves the human rights situation and allows
self-determination,'' he said.
   On the demonstrations in East Germany, Woerner said, ``we can
and will not interfere with their affairs. But as you can see,
there is strong pressure from inside towards reform and it must be
clear to the leaders of East Germany that only if they allow reform
to take place this regime will be able to develop peacefully.''
   ``If they continue like they do with their tough repression,
they will not be able to manage the change,'' he said.
</TEXT>
