<SECOND>AM-Marcos Suit,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motion Filed to Keep Marcos Family from `Squandering' Philippines
Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the Philippine government say
ousted president Ferdinand Marcos and others violated an injunction
prohibiting them from disposing of any of their assets, in part to
buy arms for an invasion.
   The charges are contained in a motion filed in U.S. District
Court Friday in connection with the civil case in which the
Philippine government is seeking $5 billion it says Marcos, his
family and associates looted from their country.
   The motion accused Imelda Marcos and her deceased husband's
worldwide network of bankers, agents and associates of
``liquidating, squandering and concealing assets belonging to the
Philippines'' in violation of a 1986 injunction.
   Court papers also alleged the Marcoses spent $2.8 million and
encumbered an additional $200 million in their Swiss bank accounts
to purchase arms for a planned invasion of the Philippines.
   Lawyers for the Philippines requested that a June court order be
modified to ``more closely monitor, control and account for the
Marcoses' expenditures, transactions, and assets, in order to
prevent further violations.''
   The motion alleges the Marcoses ``fraudulently transferred'' to
Saudi arms merchant Adnan Khashoggi ownership and control over two
New York buildings, four related corporations and at least one
Swiss bank account allegedly worth more than $100 million.
   The allegations against the Marcoses and Khashoggi closely
parallel some of the charges in a federal criminal indictment
brought against the trio in New York City in October 1988.
