<FIRST>r a AM-ArsonArrest     10-11 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arson Arrest,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policeman Arrested in Series of Arsons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAZLEHURST, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city policeman who reported most of a
rash of fires in public buildings, including schools, in this small
town has been arrested on seven counts of arson.
   Jerry Chase, 25, of Hazlehurst, surrendered Tuesday to Copiah
County Sheriff Tommy Jackson. He was being held under $70,000 bond.
   ``He had told me they were trying to pin it on him, but I didn't
know this was going to happen,'' said Chase's brother, Andre.
   Chase was accused of setting two fires each at Hazlehurst
Elementary School and Hazlehurst High School on Sept. 21, said
Copiah County District Attorney Dunn Lampton. He also was charged
in Sept. 22 fires that damaged the courthouse and destroyed the
county welfare building.
   The seventh charge involves the Sept. 25 blaze set at a building
that houses temporary welfare offices. Someone slipped past guards
and shoved a flaming wad of newspaper behind a ceiling tile.
   Lampton said Chase became a suspect through a process of
elimination.
   ``He discovered a good many of (the fires),'' Lampton said. ``It
was just a process of the Sheriff's Department, chief of police and
the state fire marshal's office looking closely at each fire. Of
course, he was a police officer and we had the reports he wrote.''
   Public School Superintendent George C. French said guards will
remain on duty at the schools. In addition to the guards, private
security personnel were hired by the welfare office and the
county's Housing and Urban Development offices.
