<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1747EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-House-Poland     10-11 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-Poland,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Votes to Sharply Increase Aid to Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Without dissent, the House Foreign Affairs
Committee on Wednesday endorsed legislation authorizing $837.5
million in aid to pro-democracy movements in Poland and Hungary.
   The 35-0 vote, nearly doubling the amount proposed by President
Bush, sends the legislation to the House floor for action next week.
   Some Republican members said they were concerned about the
spending levels authorized by the bill.
   But most members of the panel said the legislation is an
appropriate and urgently needed response to democratic and
free-market trends in both Eastern European nations.
   ``Success with our help is uncertain, but failure without our
assistance is guaranteed,'' said Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., moments
before the bill was approved.
   The House bill includes the $200 million in aid to help Poland
stabilize its currency that Bush proposed last week.
   The Bush administration took no position on the bill, which
would authorize spending $837.5 million to aid Poland and Hungary
over the next three years _ $284 million of that in the fiscal year
that began Oct. 1.
   The lion's share of the aid would go to the more populous and
economically troubled Poland.
   A Democratic proposal under consideration in the Senate calls
for making $1.25 billion available to help Poland and Hungary shift
to a free-market economy and build Democratic institutions. The
administration has proposed spending $455.5 million over the
three-year period.
   Hamilton said the House bill addresses an ``extraordinarily
unique'' opportunity to wean Eastern Europe away from communism
with the United States playing a leading role.
   ``This is an opportunity that may not come again for a long,
long time and I think we should grab it and run,'' said Rep. Robert
J. Lagomarsino, R-Calif.
   The chairman, Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., said the aid would
``lessen the impact of the instability which must take place when
you think of the enormity of the changes'' Poland and Hungary will
have to make to transform their state-run economies.
   ``I can only say that after four decades in which we spent
literally trillions of dollars to prevent the communization of
Western Europe, this is a relatively modest amount to promote the
unravelling of comminism in Eastern Europe; it is a very small
price to pay,'' said Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y.
   Although several Republicans said they had problems with the
levels of spending, only Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis., said he was
opposed to the entire concept of the bill.
   Roth contended the legislation does not adequately spell out how
the money would be spent and represents ``an attempt to solve the
problem by throwing money at it.''
   Roth was not present for the roll call vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0156 </DOCNO>
