<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Syria 1stLd-Writethru a0664 10-11 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Syria, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Pilot Lands in Israel, Army Says He Defected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with new material and editing. CORRECTS year
Syrian pilots landed in Israel. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEGIDDO, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Syrian major flying a Soviet-made
MiG-23 on a training mission defected to Israel Wednesday by flying
over the Golan Heights and landing at a civilian air field in
northern Israel, the Israeli army said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin identified it as a MiG-23 MLD _
``one of the most advanced versions of the MiG-23 supplied to the
Syrians after 1982.'' Asked if information obtained from the
aircraft would be shared with the United States, he said: ``We can
assume so.''
   Syria and Israel are archenemies and have been in a state of war
since the Jewish state was created in 1948.
   A Syrian official in Damascus said the pilot did not defect, but
ran into mechanical problems and made an emergency landing. Syria
asked the Red Cross to assist in his return.
   It was the first time a Syrian flyer was reported to have
defected to Israel, although Israeli forces have seized other
Syrian planes and received defectors from other Arab countries.
   ``This morning a Syrian pilot escaped from Syria with his plane,
a MiG-23, and he landed safely in Israel,'' said Col. Raanan
Gissin, an army spokesman.
   ``He defected to Israel and that's a fact,'' Gissin said, adding
it appeared to be ``for personal reasons.''
   Israel radio said the pilot asked for asylum. An army spokesman
said no decision on that had been announced, adding: ``At this
point we have nothing official to say. We're talking with him to
see what he wants.''
   The aircraft was ``detected by the Israeli air force and landed
here,'' Gissin said.
   He refused to say if Israeli aircraft escorted the Syrian plane
or if it penetrated sophisticated air defenses as it crossed the
Golan Heights, captured by Israel from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war.
   The pilot, identified as Maj. Adel Basem, a 34-year-old
bachelor, landed about 11:15 a.m. at an airfield used by
crop-dusting planes at Megiddo, 57 miles north of Jerusalem, an
army communique said.
   There was a companion jet but an army spokesman said as far as
Israel can tell, the second jet returned to Syria.
   A witness named David Mizrahi told Israel radio he did not
realize the plane was Syrian because he saw no Israeli escort
planes.
   ``If there were accompanying planes I would have known it was
being brought down,'' he said. ``I thought it was a disguised plane
or something.''
   Mizrahi said an armed civilian drove a white Peugeot into the
airfield and confronted the Syrian flyer.
   The radio quoted other witnesses as saying the pilot raised his
hands and said, ``I have no intentions of war.''
   Rabin and armed forces chief of staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron flew
in by helicopter to meet the pilot.
   Rabin was asked three times in an interview on Israel TV how the
jet eluded Israeli border defenses, but would say only, ``All this
is being checked now.'' The Syrian official in Damascus, who spoke
on condition of anonymnity, said the pilot had to land after the
plane ``faced a technical failure.'' Other Syrian sources said
smoke poured from the aircraft's engine.
   Gissin, addressing reporters in front of the needle-nosed Syrian
aircraft, declared, ``I can categorically say there were no
technical malfunctions. It was in perfect condition when it
landed.''
   The aircraft, painted in a camouflage pattern of brown, beige
and green, was illuminated by a spotlight. Its cockpit bubble was
up. There was no outward sign the plane had caught fire.
   Gissin said the aircraft carried no ammunition or armaments
except two 23mm machine guns mounted near the cockpit.
   He said the advanced MiG-23 would be useful to both Israel and
its allies. The craft, originally developed in 1967, was believed
last updated in 1985.
   The MiG-23 is a single-seat, swing-wing fighter bomber. It has a
range of 530 miles and can carry up to 17,000 pounds in bombs and
missiles. It is a mainstay of Syria's air force, though Damascus
also has the Soviet's most advanced craft, the MiG-29.
   Nick Cook, aviation editor of the Jane's Defense Weekly in
London, said the United States is believed to have at least four
MiG-23s, obtained through Egypt, and uses them to train airmen for
dogfights.
   Brig. Gen. Oded Erez, a former head of air force intelligence,
told Israel Television much could be learned from having Israel's
pilots fly the craft and much also could be learned from the pilot.
   On Aug. 12, 1968, two Syrian pilots landed MiG-17s in Israel
because of navigational error. They were exchanged for Israeli war
prisoners in 1973, but their planes were not returned.
   Two Arab pilots defected to Israel in the past. Iraqi pilot
Munir Redfa landed in Israel in a MiG-21 on Aug. 16, 1966, and
Egyptian Hilme Mahmoud Abbas flew a Soviet-built Yak-11 training
plane into the country Jan. 19, 1964.
</TEXT>
