<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     10-11 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Release of Anti-Apartheid Prisoners, Urges More</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Wednesday applauded
South African government plans to release eight anti-apartheid
prisoners and urged ``the release of all political prisoners,
including Nelson Mandela.''
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the United
States had long regarded the freeing of political prisoners as an
important step to promote talks between the South African
government and the non-white majority in the country.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the U.S. government also welcomed President
F.W. de Klerk's meeting Wedneday with Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the
Rev. Alan Boesak, and the Rev. Frank Chikane.
   De Klerk did not say when the prisoners would be released.
   ``We are encouraged by these positive moves, and hope that they
are merely the first steps in a process which will see the release
of all political prisoners, including Nelson Mandela, and the
return of political exiles, lifting of the state of emergency and
associated restrictions on political activity, and negotiations on
a peaceful transition to a nonracial and democratic South Africa,''
Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Ms. Tutwiler said South African Foreign Minister P.W. Botha
called Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Tuesday to tell him
of the government's decision. She was asked whether Botha had given
Baker any idea of when Nelson Mandela might be released.
   ``If he did, Secretary Baker did not impart that to me,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said, adding that she didn't know whether Baker planned
any further meetings with South African officials.
   Mandela is the best-known imprisoned leader of the outlawed
African National Congress.
   Ms. Tutwiler said she was unable to say whether the U.S.
government would drop some sanctions against South Africa as a
result of the freeing of the prisoners.
