<FIRST>r w AM-Dickinson-Collier     10-11 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>^AM-Dickinson-Collier,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dickinson Says Investment Venture Didn't Violate House Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama Rep. Bill Dickinson said Wednesday he
did not violate House ethics rules when he accepted a one-third
interest in a $300,000 investment venture from a businessman whose
companies have done $50 million in government defense work in the
past two years.
   Dickinson, the ranking Republican on the House Armed Services
Committee, said there was ``nothing illegal, immoral or unethical
about'' his joining with industrialist Ben Collier to form the
Montgomery Investment Club in 1986.
   Dickinson said he approached Collier with ``what I thought was a
good business opportunity'' and Collier agreed to put $300,000 into
the joint venture. The agreement provided that any profits or
losses would be shared one-third by Dickinson and two-thirds by
Collier.
   Asked what he put into the venture, Dickinson replied, ``I had
the contacts.''
   House rules prohibit members from accepting gifts of more than
$100 from any individual who has a direct interest in legislation
before Congress. The House ethics committee has said the rule
applies to any individual who has a special interest ``in
influencing or affecting the federal legislative process which
sets'' him apart from the general public.
   ``If he's got a direct interest in legislation I don't know what
it is,'' Dickinson said of Collier. ``He's never asked me to vote
any way, I don't know of any legislation he's interested in and
that's as far as it goes.''
   Collier owns 45 percent of American Apparel Co., which was
formed in 1987 after Collier and several associates purchased the
assets of the bankrupt Selma Apparel Co.
   The firm now has three plants in Alabama, and according to Rick
Cippele, a part owner of the company, has received $48.6 million in
uniform contracts awarded by the Defense Logistics Agency after
competitive bidding.
   Collier also owns half interest in National Microsystems, a
Montgomery company that manufactures electronics components and
test equipment for the aerospace, automobile and appliance
industries.
   Mark Chesnutt, director of public affairs for National
Microsystems, said $3 million of the company's $9 million in total
revenue this year came from subcontracts with two major defense
contractors, United Technologies Corp. and GTE Government Systems.
   Dickinson said he has promoted National Microsystems among
defense contractors, just as he has promoted other businesses in
his district that are interested in defense subcontracting work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
