<SECOND>AM-Britain-Ship, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merchant Ship Capsizes Off Oman, British Destroyer Rescues 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 10 rescued, two missing, CORRECTS
that ship capsized but hasn't sunk. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A merchant ship carrying a crew of 12 capsized in
the Arabian Sea off Oman late Wednesday, and a British destroyer
rescued 10 in the dark but two men remain missing, the Defense
Ministry said.
   The 500-ton Al Mawarid was bound from Dubai to Aden with a load
of timber when it overturned, a ministry spokesman said. The
ministry initially said it sank when the cargo shifted suddenly,
but the spokesman later said the circumstances were unclear.
   The Royal Navy destroyer HMS Manchester continued searching
through the night for the two missing crew, who are believed
trapped in the upturned hull, said the spokesman, who by custom was
not identified.
   The rescued included the vessel's captain and first officer, who
were not identified. The survivors were believed to include four
Iranians and crew from India, Oman and Dubai, the spokesman said.
   The officer of the watch on the Manchester, which was en route
to the Persian Gulf, spotted wreckage and survivors in the water
about 17 miles east of Ras al Hadd off Oman, the spokesman said.
   Six crew scrambled up nets thrown over the side of the
Manchester and two spotted clinging to chunks of wood were
recovered shortly afterwards, the spokesman said.
   A boat was launched to search the immediate vicinity and the
captain scrambled Manchester's Lynx helicopter to search further
afield while the medical officer provided first aid to the
survivors, the spokesman said.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Service said it had no reports of
the capsizing and no information on a vessel named Al Mawarid.
</TEXT>
