<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SEC-Breeden     10-11 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Breeden,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breeden Sworn in as Newest SEC Member, Named Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House staffer Richard C. Breeden
was designated chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission
Wednesday after being sworn in as the newest member of the
regulatory agency.
   Breeden, 39, took the oath of office in a White House ceremony
attended by President Bush.
   ``Maintaining strong and competitive U.S. financial markets in
an era of global capital flows will be among my key priorities,
along with continued resolute action to prevent fraud and to
protect investors,'' Breeden said in written remarks released by
the SEC.
   Technically, Breeden is taking the seat of former SEC member
Charles C. Cox, who left office Sept. 30 to join Lexecon, a
Chicago-based consulting firm.
   But Bush designated Breeden as the 24th SEC commissioner,
replacing David S. Ruder, who also left the commission last month
to return to teaching law at Northwestern University.
   There is still a vacancy on the five-member commission, which
oversees securities markets, regulates the sale of stocks, bonds
and stock options and enforces securities laws.
   Breeden, a graduate of Stanford University and Harvard Law
School, has served Bush in a variety of capacities _ most recently
as an architect of the landmark legislation to restructure the
nation's ailing savings and loan industry.
   Nominated by Bush Sept. 7, Breeden sailed through confirmation
hearings before the Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs
Committee a week later and was confirmed by the full Senate last
Wednesday.
   A native of Manhattan Beach, Calif., Breeden lives in the
Virginia suburbs outside Washington, D.C. with his wife, Holly, and
their three sons.
</TEXT>
