<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Jurors     10-11 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Jurors,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Hears Illinois Case Involving Black Jurors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The constitutional rights of white defendants
are violated if prosecutors keep blacks off juries, the lawyer for
a white man convicted of rape argued Wednesday before the Supreme
Court.
   Cook County, Ill., public defender Donald S. Honchell wants the
court to order a new trial for Daniel Holland and to give him the
authority to object to the removal of prospective black jurors.
   Honchell faced tough questions from Justices Antonin Scalia and
Byron White, who said only the pool of jurors should be
representive of the community _ not the jury itself.
   ``You're driving up hill in this case,'' White said.
   Prosecutors, without explanation, may reject 12 prospective
jurors by using peremptory challenges. The defense also has 12
peremptory challenges.
   In Holland's case, two challenges were used to remove two
blacks, though prosecutors said the disqualifications weren't
racially motivated.
   ``It's a level playing field,'' Scalia said of the jury
selection process. ``Each side gets their peremptories. Why isn't
that a perfectly rational system?''
   ``This court,'' Honchell said, ``can utilize the Sixth Amendment
to say white defendants have a right to complain.''
   The Sixth Amendment guarantees the right to a fair trial.
   An all-white Cook County jury convicted Holland in 1981 of rape,
sexual assault, armed robbery and kidnapping.
   Five years later, in a case involving a black defendant and
black jurors, the Supreme Court barred prosecutors from
disqualifying potential jurors based on race.
   Holland took his case to the U.S. Supreme Court after the
Illinois Supreme Court said a white man lacks the legal standing to
challenge the exclusion of blacks from a jury.
   Cook County Assistant State's Attorney Inge Fryklund argued that
decision by the state court should stand.
   ``Petitioner Holland got exactly what the Sixth Amendment
provides,'' she said.
   The Supreme Court will issue an opinion next year.
   The American Civil Liberties Union and the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People Legal Defense and Education
Fund support Holland.
   In a brief filed with the court, the groups cited a 1975 Supreme
Court ruling that upheld a male defendant's right to challenge the
exclusion of female jurors.
   On May 4, 1980, Holland offered a ride to a 17-year-old girl and
her boyfriend _ both white _ after the couple's car had two flat
tires. Holland then pulled a knife and told the boy to get out.
   He raped the girl, forced her to perform oral sex and stole $60
before leaving her in an alley. He was sentenced to 85 years in
prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
