<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Very Little Rain, Record Heat On Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered over small sections of the nation Wednesday
and temperatures hit record highs near 90 degrees in Nebraska,
which had record lows earlier this month.
   Light showers were scattered over northwestern Minnesota, behind
a cold front that extended from west-central Nebraska across
southeastern South Dakota into northeastern Minnesota.
   Showers also were scattered from northern New Hampshire across
Maine, and over the eastern side of the Florida Peninsula.
   The heaviest rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was
0.68 of an inch at Augusta, Maine.
   In the West, wind gusted to 80 mph at Ames Monument, Wyo.,
between Cheyenne and Laramie.
   The temperature soared to a record 89 degrees at Grand Island,
Neb., and North Platte, Neb., hit a record reading of 87.
   Temperatures elsewhere around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged
from 43 at Augusta, Maine, to 98 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Wednesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 14 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
