<FIRST>r w AM-Stoltenberg-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru   10-11 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stoltenberg-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Believes Gorbachev Urged Reforms on East Germans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with later comment from Stoltenberg and quotes
from second West German official. Edits throughout to tighten. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders in East Germany have little
choice but to make reforms such as those occurring the Soviet
Union, two top West German officials said Wednesday.
   ``It's inconceivable that ... (East Germany) will stay as it
is'' in view of changes in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary,
West German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg told reporters.
   Stoltenberg, who met Tuesday with President Bush, and NATO
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner, a former West German defense
minister who visited Bush on Wednesday, spoke at separate news
conferences.
   ``The major disagreeable thing for them is that if they continue
like they do, their tough repression, they will not be able to
manage the change, they will not be able to peacefully develop
their countries,'' Woerner said about East Germany.
   ``They get more and more isolated, and I think that is reason
enough to change.''
   Stoltenberg said the repression used by China to crush its
student democracy movement wasn't ``a real alternative'' for East
Germany.
   ``But if they don't take the Chinese example, they have to move
in the other direction,'' he said. ``Otherwise, the economic and
political situation will deteriorate because people have no
motivation for work and have no motivation to participate under the
existing patterns.''
   Stoltenberg said earlier that Mikhail Gorbachev's attempts to
urge reforms on East Germany have been weakened because of his own
problems at home.
   ``Gorbachev's influence in the Warsaw Pact countries is not as
great as ... (the Soviet leader's) was five years ago because he
has more and more domestic difficulties,'' he said. ``He has
influence, but not, I think, to the same extent as ... his
predecessors had.''
   Gorbachev leader visited East Germany last week, expressing
confidence in Erich Honecker's ruling Communist Party. However,
Gorbachev urged Honecker's government to work with ``all forces in
society'' to tackle problems facing East Germany.
   Honecker indicated he would continue his hard-line approach and
not follow the reforms adopted in the Soviet Union, Poland and
Hungary.
   There have been mixed signals from the East German government
since Gorbachev's visit, with some calls for reform, as the country
grapples with how to staunch the flow of refugees to the West.
   More than 100,000 people have left East Germany this year, many
in recent weeks.
   ``We do not know what Gorbachev said to Honecker when he was
there, because they had a closed session, of course,'' Stoltenberg
said. ``But from some remarks some of his close officials made to
West German counterparts in private conversations, we think that he
advised them to do some reform steps.''
   Stoltenberg, who arrived here Monday, has met with Vice
President Dan Quayle, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Secretary
of State James A. Baker III.
   He will visit U.S. and German forces at military bases in
Norfolk, Va., and Texas before returning to West Germany on Friday.
</TEXT>
