<FIRST>u i AM-UN-CentralAmerica     10-11 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Central America,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN to Send 625-Member Peacekeeping Force to Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations will send a highly
mobile border patrol force to Central America as part of the
regional peace agreement signed in August, says a report by
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   A copy of the report to the Security Council, obtained by The
Associated Press on Wednesday, shows the peacekeeping force will be
equipped with jeeps, helicopters and speedboats. The mission is to
involve 625 people, including civilian support personnel.
   Its job is to prevent any nation from mounting an attack on a
neighbor, to verify that no rebel forces cross borders to launch
raids and to halt radio or television TV broadcasts by
insurrectionists.
   The presidents of El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras, Guatemala
and Costa Rica requested the force in a letter to Perez de Cuellar
in March.
   Personnel from Canada, West Germany, Spain and a group of Latin
American nations are to join the operation.
   It must be approved by the Security Council, but council members
have indicated support for such a force, to be called ONUCA to
reflect the Spanish name for the United Nations.
   ONUCA will be the first major U.N. peacekeeping effort in the
Western Hemisphere. A two-man observer group was stationed in the
Dominican Republic in 1965-66 to monitor a truce between two
military factions vying for control of the government.
   The mission will include 260 military observers, 115 crew for 12
helicopters and an airplane, 50 men to operate speedboats and
patrol boats, a 14-member medical staff, 104 U.N. administrators
and 82 locally hired civilians.
   West Germany's contribution is not yet clear. Its constitution
prohibits sending soldiers abroad, except to support NATO, but it
could contribute members of the border police, pilots and support
personnel.
   Headquarters will be in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, with liaison
offices in the other four Central American capitals and 31
``verification centers'' staffed by observers.
   The naval unit, to be based at La Union, El Salvador, will
patrol the Gulf of Fonseca, coastal areas and rivers.
   No estimate of the operation's cost was given in the report.
   In a separate report released Wednesday, Perez de Cuellar said
another U.N. force would be needed to collect weapons from the
Contras, Nicaraguan rebels based in Honduras who are being
disbanded, and assist in their repatriation or relocation to
another country.
   U.N. election monitors also have gone to Nicaragua to verify
that national elections scheduled for Feb. 25 are conducted fairly
by the leftist Sandinista government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
