<FIRST>u a AM-Bishops-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0706 10-11 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bishops-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0887</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Attack Israeli Rights Abuses, Call for Palestinian Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to add comments from chairman of bishops'
committee and Arab leader; expands 2nd graf, `The draft ..., to include
ground rules of peace envisioned by bishops. Picks up 8th graf pvs: `The
intefadeh ...; ADDS 1 graf with Mahony's response to criticism of bishops
for not addressing Vatican recognition of Israel.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ A committee of U.S. Roman Catholic bishops Wednesday
criticized alleged Israeli human rights abuses in the West Bank and
Gaza, and called for Palestinians to be included as equal partners
in negotiations for a sovereign Palestinian homeland.
   The draft statement by the Ad Hoc Committee on the Middle East
praised the United States for opening discussions with the
Palestine Liberation Organization, and asked the administration to
take a more active role in negotiating a peace in the Middle East
that meets the security needs of Israel and the ``long-denied
rights'' of Palestinians.
   ``It is our conviction that a truly open moment for peace exists
in the Middle East, and that the United States has an indispensable
role to play in the peace process which has moved us to write this
statement,'' said the committee, made up of Archbishop Roger Mahony
of Los Angeles, Cardinal John O'Connor of New York and Bishop
William Keeler of Baltimore.
   The statement, ``Toward Peace in the Middle East: Problems and
Principles,'' will be presented to the nation's 300 bishops at the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops' fall meeting Nov. 6-9 in
Baltimore.
   Some U.S. Jewish leaders welcomed the bishops' support for
Israel, but said they were troubled by parts of the statement,
including what they said was the bishops' premature support for a
sovereign Palestinian homeland.
   The bishops also failed to give equal weight ``to Israel's very
real problems and legitimate rights in maintaining order in the
territories,'' and a 40-year history of terrorist attacks by
Palestinians, said Rabbi A. James Rudin, national interreligious
affairs director of the American Jewish Committee, and Judith H.
Banki, his associate.
   An Arab leader applauded the bishops' draft document.
   ``The addition of such a respected moral voice on the side of
Palestinian independence is an historic development at a critial
juncture in the Palestinian-Israeli conflict,'' said Abdeen Jabara,
president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee.
``History will record that the moral authority of the American
Catholic Church was indisputably on the side of peace in the Middle
East.''
   The bishops said the statement was devised after consultations
with the Vatican, religious leaders in the Middle East, U.S.
policymakers on the region and major Jewish, Arab and Christian
organizations.
   All the groups the bishops met with were ``very, very grateful
for the role of the Catholic bishops,'' said Mahony, the committee
chairman who described the prelates' role as one of being
instruments of peace.
   ``We see this as a moral challenge. There is a better way to
live,'' he said.
   The intefadeh, the rebellion by Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied territories of the West Bank and Gaza since 1987,
has recast the policy agenda in the Middle East by bringing
Palestinian claims to the forefront, the bishops said.
   The uprising is a ``cry for justice'' and ``personal and
political identity'' that demands ``on both moral and political
grounds, a response by the United States government,'' the bishops
wrote.
   The bishops cited several alleged Israeli human rights abuses in
the occupied territories, including beating deaths of Palestinians
and people not involved in demonstrations, the demolition of homes
and arrest and detention without trial.
   American support for Israel is basically a sound policy, the
bishops' committee said, but it does not conflict with concern for
human rights.
   The United States also must go beyond the approach taken in the
Camp David accords of the 1970s, which gave Palestinians a
secondary role in the peace process, and grant ``their right to
participate as equals, through representatives selected by
Palestinians, in all negotiations affecting their destiny,'' the
bishops said.
   Having opened political discussions with the PLO in December
1988, ``the United States now has the opportunity to use its
influence and relationships to foster a more extensive dialogue
among Israel, Palestinians and the Arab states,'' the bishops wrote.
   The bishops also called upon the Arab states and Palestinians to
recognize Israel's right to exist.
   ``The time is long since past when this basic element of
international life should be affirmed for Israel,'' the committee
said.
   The bishops specifically asked the Arab nations to establish
full diplomatic relations with Israel, and for all nations involved
in the peace process to pressure Syria to withdraw from Lebanon.
   One U.S. Jewish leader said the statement is worthy of
discussion, but its credibility is undermined by a failure to call
upon the Vatican to establish full diplomatic relations with Israel.
   ``It is incongruous of them to ask the Arab states to establish
such diplomatic relations while not asking the Vatican, the seat of
the Roman Catholic Church, to do so,'' said Elan Steinberg,
executive director of the World Jewish Congress.
   Mahony said the issue of Vatican relations with Israel was not
``in our jurisdiction or our competence.''
</TEXT>
