<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CopelandOpera     10-11 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Copeland Opera,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fans, Music Critic at Odds Over Rock Drummer's Opera</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans generally were enthusiastic about the
world premiere of ``Holy Blood and Crescent Moon,'' an opera by
Stewart Copeland, former drummer of the rock group Police. But a
newspaper music critic panned it.
   ``Music is the heart and soul of opera, and Copeland's score
rises only at a few isolated moments to anything that makes us care
about his characters,'' Robert Finn of The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer
said in a review published Wednesday. ``It is full of nervous
orchestral busy-work.
   ``We are left here with a well-intentioned but essentially
amateurish work.''
   Finn added: ``Give the young pop composer credit for not making
some sort of pop-oriented opera out of his subject. He has tried
for something serious and genuine.''
   The curtain had to be held for 15 minutes Tuesday night while
hundreds of last-minute ticket buyers found their seats.
   David Bamberger, general manager of the Cleveland Opera, said
more tickets were sold for Copeland's opera than any other grand
opera the company has produced.
   For spectator Brent Brown, 22, of Painesville, the idea of a
rock star moving into the tradition-laden world of grand opera is
exciting. ``He's bringing new ideas to high opera,'' said Brown, in
dinner jacket and red bow tie.
   Copeland, who spent six years with the rock group Police and has
scored movies and television shows, took four years to write the
opera, a tale of the Crusades in the Middle East.
   Cleveland Opera officials said it is the first time a major
figure from popular music has written an opera since George
Gershwin wrote ``Porgy and Bess.''
   Copeland, 37, decided to write an opera on a lark in 1984, when
he wrote music for a ballet for Shakespeare's ``King Lear'' for the
San Francisco Ballet. He said he would write another ballet ``after
I finish my opera.''
   Bamberger's son, Stephen, heard the remark and urged his father
to contact Copeland.
   ``Holy Blood and Crescent Moon'' will be performed again
Thursday through Sunday at the State Theater and in March 1991 in
Fort Worth, Texas.
   Producers from several opera companies across the country were
invited to the Cleveland performances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1850EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-France-Nobel     10-11 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Nobel,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Minister Says Nobel Committee Neglected Frenchman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The committee that awarded the Nobel Prize for
medicine to two American scientists should have recognized the
contributions made by a French researcher, France's minister for
research and technology said Wednesday.
   ``I share the deep regret of not having seen the name of
Professor (Dominique) Stehelin attached to the Nobel Prize for
medicine,'' Henri Curien told the National Assembly in response to
a lawmaker's question.
   Stehelin was the principal signer of the first article in the
scientific magazine Nature in 1976 on the discovery of the cellular
gene which is at the origin of cancer.
   The article was also signed by San Francisco scientists J.
Michael Bishop and Harold E. Varmus, who won this year's prize for
cancer research, and researcher Peter Vogt.
   ``The Nobel jury judged it fine to keep only the names of the
two California scientists,'' Curien said. ``I can assure you there
are some others, like Professor Peter Vogt, who are also very
disappointed.''
   Stehelin, a research director for the National Center for
Scientific Research at the Pasteur Institute in Lille, said Monday
that the decision to award the prize only to Bishop and Varmus was
``unfair and rotten.''
   Bishop and Varmus, who work together at the University of
California School of Medicine in San Francisco, have called
Stehelin's work crucial to the discovery of oncogenes, which
control normal growth cells and their division.
   The discovery showed cancer develops when the function of
oncogenes is disturbed and cells grow without control.
</TEXT>
