<FIRST>r w AM-US-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0702 10-11 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Colombians Awaiting Extradition to U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with U.S. official saying one of two suspects
arrested in Colombia was a major drug shipper. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian described by U.S. officials as a
major drug shipper was one of two suspects arrested Wednesday in
Colombia, the Justice Department said.
   Colombian police arrested Jose Rafael Abello Silva, 35, a member
of the Medellin cartel wanted on U.S. charges of conspiring to ship
500 kilograms of cocaine into this country, said Justice Department
spokeswoman Harri J. Kramer.
   A federal grand jury in Tulsa, Okla., indicted Abello in 1987 on
charges of conspiracy to import and distribute cocaine.
   ``He was considered a major transporter for the Medellin
cartel,'' said Cornelius Dougherty, a spokesman for the Drug
Enforcement Administration.
   Abello was responsible for ``major shipments of cocaine and
marijuana into the states,'' Dougherty said.
   The State Department was serving Colombian authorities with a
request that Abello and another suspect, Manuel Palma, to be held
under the provisional-detention section of President Virgilio
Barcos' extradition regulations, Kramer said.
   Palma is wanted by federal authorities in Miami on charges of
interstate travel in aid of racketeering in connection with an
operation to launder drug money, Kramer said.
