<FIRST>u a AM-TrainDeaths     10-11 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Deaths,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Questioning Aliens About Dead Traveling Companions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Border Patrol is trying to
determine if a smuggler of illegal aliens locked four men in a
trailer on a railroad car where they were killed by a pesticide
used to fumigate the trailer, agents said Wednesday.
   Autopsies showed the four men found in the trailer and a fifth
found along the railroad tracks 60 miles away were killed by the
pesticide, officials said Wednesday.
   Border Patrol agents suspect the men were locked in the trailer
by smugglers in Harlingen, where the train left Monday night for
Houston.
   ``At this point, that appears to be the case, although we're not
ready to issue a complete report on that,'' said Border Patrol
Chief Silvestre Reyes of McAllen.
   ``We do believe that there was smuggler involved. We believe we
have a lead on a smuggler,'' he said.
   A smuggler may have arranged with someone to open the trailer
doors once the train stopped in Victoria, where at least one of the
men was destined, Reyes said.
   Four victims were found Tuesday in the truck trailer, being
hauled ``piggyback'' on a flatcar, on a rail siding in Victoria.
The fifth was spotted later near Sinton, a small town about 60
miles away where the train had stopped for nearly two hours
overnight.
   Preliminary autopsy reports from Travis County Medical Examiner
Robert Bayardo and Nueces County Medical Examiner Joseph Rupp
showed all five died of asphyxiation by hydrogen phosphate gas.
   The gas was emitted by Phostoxin pesticide packets tossed into
the trailer to kill boll weevils and other vermin in its cargo of
corn flour, or masa, during the rail trip.
   ``One of the guys had some coins in his pocket and those coins
were black, indicating there was poison in there,'' Victoria
Justice of the Peace Sylvia White said of one autopsy report.
   Complete toxicology reports could be issued later in the week,
she said.
   The trailer had two warning stickers the size of license plates
on its doors. They showed skulls and read in English and Spanish:
``Danger. This trailer is being fumigated'' and ``Do not enter.''
   One of the victims was from the state of Guerrero, Mexico, one
had documents from Honduras, and a third had papers that had been
stamped in El Salvador but indicated he was from Venezuela,
officials said. Authorities have found no identification for the
two others.
   Four other illegal aliens noticed the five were sluggish during
the stop in Sinton, police said.
   Victoria Police Lt. Jack Williams said the four, who rode the
same train, found one man on the ground at Sinton.
   ``But they thought he was intoxicated,'' Williams said. ``They
tried to wake him, but were unable to. So, they moved him off the
tracks. Then they went back to the truck where the man had been and
found the others passed out.''
   ``We don't know if he got off by himself or he had help,'' san
San Patricio County Sheriff's investigator Johnny Segovia.
   One of the four surviving aliens was treated at a Victoria
hospital after complaining of nausea, diarrhea and lightheadedness
believed to be related to inhaling the gas, police said.
   Phostoxin is one of three commonly used fumigants for grain
products, said Max Woodfin, agricultural resources protection
officer for the Texas Department of Agriculture.
   He said Phostoxin leaves no residue once the facility has been
properly ventilated for at least 24 hours after fumigation.
</TEXT>
