<FIRST>u i AM-WhiskyWreck 1stLd-Writethru a0610 10-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whisky Wreck, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0610,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Raising Some Scotch on the Rocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf `Salvagers believe...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
that 2,000-4,000 cases of whiskey believed to be in wreck now. Picks up
5th graf pvs, `The owners ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a ship wrecked off
Scotland in 1941 with 20,300 cases of Scotch whisky on board said
Wednesday they plan to salvage what's left of the cargo.
   Despite the efforts of police and customs officers, most of the
cargo was looted by the Hebridean islanders of Eriskay and the
neighboring islands of South Uist and Barra when the Politician was
wrecked on rocks off Eriskay.
   The ship made Eriskay famous and brought it a tourist trade that
continues to this day.
   Salvagers believe the wreck, buried in sand in 20-foot waters
off Eriskay's north coast, still contains 2,000 to 4,000 cases of
whisky and possibly eight metal cases of Jamaican currency, said
spokesman Frank Gilfeather.
   The owners of the salvage rights include several financiers, a
diver and a lawyer, he said.
   The group plans to offer shares to the public to raise a minimum
of $800,000 needed to recover the sunken cargo, Gilfeather said.
The operation is expected to take place in the spring, he said.
   ``I don't think anybody would take the chance of drinking'' the
whisky, Gilfeather said. ``It would be a collector's item.''
   The booze was so plentiful on Eriskay in the 1940s that women
were seen pouring it on peat fires to make them burn more easily.
   The wreck gave novelist Compton Mackenzie the plot for his comic
novel, ``Whiskey Galore.'' It was made into a film of the same name
in 1948, but renamed ``Tight Little Island'' for release in the
United States.
</TEXT>
