<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2007EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Romania     10-11 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Romania,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romanian Baptists Sentenced for Building Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Romanians have been sentenced in that
communist country for their parts in building a Baptist Church
without government permission, Keston College reported Wednesday.
   The London-based research institute, which monitors religious
freedom in communist nations, said the four Baptists were sentenced
to ``corrective labor sentences'' Oct. 5 in Gheorghe Gheorgiu-dej.
   It said the men were required to pay part of their earnings to
the government and live under house arrest.
   Nicolae Iacob was sentenced to two years, eight months for his
role in building the Comanesti Baptist Church, Valentin Rusu to two
years, six months and Mihai Cretu and Gheorghe Iacobuta to one
year, the college said.
   One sentence was believed to have been suspended, Keston College
said, but added that it did not know which one or how much was to
be deducted from the men's wages.
   There are 200,000 Baptists in Romania, a nation of 23 million.
   Romanian authorities say the church, demolished May 31, was
built without proper authorization, but Keston College said the men
were charged with using stolen building materials.
   ``The sentences handed down on two of the Baptists ... appear to
exceed the provisions specified in Romanian law,'' it said in a
statement.
   ``Under the April 1973 amendments to the penal code ... the
maximum sentence of compulsory labor that can be imposed is two
years. Between 15 and 50 percent of a person's wages may be
deducted.''
   Keston College reported three other men ``who had apparently
transported the building materials'' were being tried, but ``there
is no information yet as to what sentences they received.''
</TEXT>
