<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0694 10-11 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>NOW, Other Pro-Choice Groups Hope to Ride Pro-Choice Wave into Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Florida Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to clarify that NOW and other groups are not sponsoring
candidates; INSERTS two grafs after 5th, ``What we're ..., to UPDATE with
comment from action fund spokesman. Pick up 6th graf pvs: `In Florida ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organization for Women and
other groups, buoyed by the Legislature's refusal to toughen
Florida's abortion laws, hope a new women's-rights wave will propel
pro-choice candidates into state and national offices, activists
said Wednesday.
   ``This is creating a new wave of feminism that we have not had
since the 1960s,'' said Patricia Ireland, NOW's national vice
president. ``We're seeing the impact of this session all over the
country.''
   The pro-choice forces were shocked by the U.S. Supreme Court
decision allowing states to restrict abortions, and this
legislative session became a rallying point for action, the
activists said.
   Ireland said NOW and other groups would target anti-abortion
candidates for Congress, governorships and statehouses for defeat
in 1990.
   ``What we're seeing this session is a shift by women's rights
supporters from the defensive to the offensive,'' she said. ``This
is one of those junctures where the political climate has clearly
changed.''
   Arthur J. Kropp, president of People for the American Way Action
Fund, a liberal political action group, said politicians across the
country should take note of what happened in Florida.
   ``Today's victory will be a rude wake-up call for politicians
hoping to score points at the polls by rolling back reproductive
freedom,'' Kropp said. ``Legislators in other states should take
heed: pro-choice politics is winning politics, even in conservative
states.''
   In Florida, NOW state President Jane Blimling said the
organization hopes to elect eight more women in the House and five
in the Senate. At present, there are 16 women in the House and 10
in the upper chamber. The House has 120 members; the Senate 40.
   She said the organization's 36 Florida chapters are gathering
information on anti-abortion legislators and would use their
stances in the next round of elections.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, a Republican who called the special
legislative session, has seriously harmed himself among pro-choice
women voters who won't forget, said Eleanor Smeal, president of the
Fund for the Feminist Majority. Martinez is up for election to a
second term next year.
   The two Democratic candidates for governor, state Sen. George
Stuart of Orlando and U.S. Rep. Bill Nelson of Melbourne, have both
criticized Martinez for calling the session. On the Republican
side, state Sen. Marlene Woodson-Howard of Bradenton just announced
her intention to oppose the governor in a GOP primary. She, too,
cited his anti-abortion stance.
   Congressional seats will be reapportioned following the 1990
Census, and Florida could pick up as many as four seats in the
House. Smeal and Ireland said much of their groups' resources would
be concentrated on races in Florida.
   All three women said the special session, called soon after the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled in July that states could further restrict
abortion laws, had galvanized women _ especially younger women _
into political action.
   NOW organized a ``caravan for choice'' to 17 Florida cities,
where they lobbied people and organized them to work against making
state abortion laws more restrictive. Groups on the other side also
organized their forces.
</TEXT>
