<FIRST>u w AM-Spending-Taxes     10-11 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending-Taxes,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaders Still Arguing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders made a last-ditch search
Wednesday night for a way to consider President Bush's cut in
capital-gains taxes without slowing work on a major
deficit-reduction bill.
   In the House, which already has passed a deficit bill that
includes a capital-gains cut, leaders bowed out of the hunt. ``We
basically have done our work,'' Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif.,
chairman of the House Budget Committee, told reporters. ``Now the
Senate has to do its work.''
   ``The Senate has to work out its own problems,'' added Rep. Bill
Archer of Texas, senior Republican on the House Ways and Means
Committee.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, planned one
last meeting on the issue with senior colleagues, even as the
Senate prepared to deliberate the deficit bill.
   ``Hope springs eternal,'' Mitchell said, while assailing the
Bush administration's insistence on the capital-gains reduction.
   A series of closed-door leadership meetings in the House and
Senate has been aimed at stripping all non-deficit issues from the
deficit-reduction bill. Presumably, the big extraneous issues,
including capital gains and the Democrats' proposal to expand
tax-deductible Individual Retirement Accounts, would be added to a
new bill and considered later this year.
   Barring a major suprise, the Senate will begin work Thursday on
the bill, a package of spending reductions and tax increases that
would cut the deficit by about $14 billion this budget year. That
bill does not include a capital-gains reduction, although
supporters may try to have one added during the debate.
   Whether to reduce the tax on capital gains, which are profits
from the sale of investments, has dominated development of the
deficit-reduction bill.
   Bush wants a cut, contending it would spur the economy and, at
least in the short run, generate additional revenues for deficit
reduction.
   Most Democrats oppose the reduction because 80 percent of the
tax saving would go to those with incomes over $100,000 a year.
They say the cut would deepen the deficit by $67 billion over the
next 10 years.
   Under Senate rules, it would require 60 votes _ rather than the
usual majority of 51 _ to add a capital-gains cut to the deficit
bill.
   Richard G. Darman, director of the White House Office of
Management and Budget, said Thursday night: ``We think we have the
votes to win on this,'' presumably meaning 51. ``Why not have a
vote?'' he asked in an interview on the MacNeil-Lehrer Newshour on
PBS.
   ``A majority has expressed support for some form of
capital-gains or another,'' Mitchell said on the same program,
``but no majority has agreed to any particular plan ... No plan may
possibly get a majority.''
   Mitchell accused the administration of demanding special
treatment under Senate rules so that a bare majority would be able
to approve a capital-gains cut. He recalled that the minority
Republicans used the same rule to their benefit earlier this year
and prevailed over Democrats on a bill bailing out the savings and
loan industry.
   ``The same rules apply to everyone equally,'' Mitchell said.
``It is the height of hypocrisy, the height of unfairness to say
they should benefit from the rules when they are advantaged'' and
that Democrats should not when the tables are turned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
