<FIRST>u a AM-SchoolSkirmishes     10-11 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Skirmishes,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racially Inflamed Fights Break Out at Alabama, Arkansas Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   One student was stabbed and six others arrested in a racially
inflamed melee at an Alabama high school, and at least 300 students
at Central High School in Little Rock, Ark., were involved in
similar fistfights Wednesday, authorities and witnesses said.
   Students were sent home at Minor High School near Adamsville,
Ala., after days of racial tension sparked violence that began in
the school cafeteria.
   Principal Judson Jones had called students to the cafeteria to
discuss friction among black and white students, when a shove
escalated into a Mace-spraying, gunshots-firing melee, witnesses
said.
   ``While we were in the lunchroom, two white guys came into the
lunchroom, stood up on some tables and began spraying Mace in the
faces of (black) students,'' said 15-year-old student Kimberly
Nixon. ``Then fights broke out all over the school, inside and
outside the building.''
   A teacher, who was not identified, fired gunshots into the air
in an attempt to break up fighting, and a 17-year-old senior,
Johnny Drummonds, was treated for a shoulder stab wound and
released from Lloyd Noland Hospital. The principal received minor
cuts when he tried to intervene.
   ``There was mass confusion, running and screaming everywhere,''
said police Sgt. Ronald Benson. Thirty patrol cars were called to
the school, where classes were expected to resume Thursday under
tight security.
   The gun-toting teacher will be disciplined, said Nez Calhoun,
spokeswoman for the Jefferson County school board.
   At least 60 students, half blacks and half whites, were
involved. About 25 percent of the school's 967 students are black.
   Police said tension at the school was due partly to black gang
activity and what black students perceive as taunting by white
students.
   Miss Nixon said black students were angered during homecoming
festivities last week when a white student came to school with
black paint on his hands and face and an afro wig on his head.
   A pep rally Friday at Minor High was marred by yelling and
pushing between black and white students.
   The six students arrested, one 18-year-old and five juveniles,
had not yet been processed at the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department and specific charges against them were not immediately
available, said Lt. Earl Patterson.
   In Little Rock, at least a half-dozen fistfights broke out after
a burning effigy of a red devil, mascot of a rival school, fell
from a tree across from Central High onto the car of a black
student during an outdoor, homecoming pep rally, Principal Everett
Hawks said.
   Fighting spread quickly, spilling into school hallways.
   In 1957, President Eisenhower sent federal troops to protect
nine black students who integrated Central High in a mob-violence
atmosphere.
   ``It started out by being a ruckus, like 1957, except the blacks
were the majority and the whites were the minority. Simple as that,
and I'm black,'' senior class president Jay Brown said.
   The 16-year-old owner of the car said he instigated a fight
after friends pointed out a white student as the person responsible
for damage to the auto. Hawks said a white student is believed
responsible, but not the one attacked by the student and his
friends.
   A hubcap and side panel near a tire on the car were singed by
flames.
   ``It became a real significant racial issue. That's scary for us
and tragic,'' Hawks said.
   Central High has 1,813 students, 58 percent of whom are black.
   No charges were expected and no weapons were involved, city
police Officer Jason Shook said.
</TEXT>
