<DOCNO> AP891011-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-IAPA     10-11 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IAPA,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>IAPA President Says Press Freedoms Improving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hemisphere is showing a ``healthy
tendency toward freedom of expression,'' Manuel Jimenez, president
of the Inter-American Press Association said Wednesday.
   ``This year has been very significant in the history of freedom
of the press and expression in America,'' Jimenez said in his final
report to IAPA members at their 45th general assembly.
   Paraguay, whose dictatorship under Gen. Alfredo Stroessner ended
in a coup by Gen. Andres Rodriguez earlier this year, ``is on the
road to re-establishing, after many, many years, a real democracy
and also creating a climate of freedom of the press and
expression,'' Jimenez said.
   The two leading candidates for president of Chile, Hernan Buchi
and Patricio Aylwin, have been recognized by IAPA for their
struggle to re-establish press freedoms after 16 years of military
rule by Gen. Augusto Pinochet, he said.
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's announcment that
the government would sell its newsprint monopoly was received with
``great surprise and satisfaction,'' he said.
   ``There's no doubt that all the above represents extraordinary
news and that there exists in the continent a healty tendency
toward freedom of expression,'' Jimenez said.
   ``But as there have been exceptionally good things, the Republic
of Panama remains a dark and nebulous point,'' he added.
   ``There, the government of Gen. Manuel Noreiga recently
terminated the only vestige of freedom of expression and has seized
the last independent television channel,'' said Jimenez, of the
daily newspaper La Nacion in Costa Rica.
   The result of the Feb. 25 national elections in Nicaragua will
determine whether press freedoms are reinstated in that country, he
said.
   Regarding the Nicaraguan elections, IAPA members held a lengthy
debate over holding the organization's planned midyear meeting in
Managua in March.
   Although they decided to maintain the site, several members said
the organization should not become involved in the ``massive
fraud'' expected by the Sandinista government.
   ``All the signs show that the elections are going to be a
fraud,'' said German Ornes, former IAPA president and editor of the
daily El Caribe newspaper of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
   ``We are talking about a possible loss of money against people
who have lost their freedom and their lives,'' said Jim Hampton,
editor of the Miami Herald. ``I would be astonished if there
weren't fraud.''
   Violeta Chamorro, owner of the daily Nicaraguan opposition
newspaper La Prensa, has vowed to restore press freedoms if she
wins the elections.
   ``It's a statement of our principles and belief in free
expression. If a miracle occurs and Violeta wins, it would be a
hell of a celebration,'' Hampton said in an interview after the
debate.
   ``But if the expected occurs and the election is stolen than
it's an occassion for us to point out what happens, to deplore it
and let the Sandinistas know that we've got our eye on them,''
Hampton said.
   Not going to Managua would be ``handing the Sandinista
government a real victory'' and would demonstrate that ``somehow
we're afraid to go,'' said Michael McQuire, Chicago Tribune deputy
managing editor for national and international news.
   ``We would be denying ourselves an opportunity of fulfilling one
of our most noble purposes ... and demonstrating solidarity with
our collegues who are being suppressed and suffering indignities,''
McQuire said.
   In another IAPA matter, the organization's general assembly
recommended that member newspapers publish a 400-word editorial
regarding Tuesday's killings of Colombian journalists and the
attack on the life of a Salvadoran journalist and the death of his
wife.
   ``The climate of terror imposed by the drug cartels on the free
Colombian press has no comparison in the history of the
continent,'' said the editorial, written by Augusto Nunez of the
daily newspaper O Estado of Sao Paulo, Brazil.
   ``Dictatorships and authoritarian regimes that for many decades
have punished the American nations always have included independent
journalists among their favorite targets,'' he wrote.
   ``But those governments never have tried to institutionalize the
systematic extermination of those journalists that defend laws and
institutions,'' Nunez wrote.
</TEXT>
