<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     10-11 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Likud Hard-liners, Labor Doves Want To Scrap Israel's Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hard-liners in Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc demanded dismantling of the coalition
government Wednesday, saying the rival Labor Party was working
toward establishment of a Palestinian state.
   Doves in the left-leaning Labor Party, Likud's coalition
partner, also said the government should end.
   In the occupied lands, four Palestinians were shot and wounded
in clashes with Israeli troops, Arab hospitals said. The army
command said two soldiers were slightly hurt when acid was thrown
at them in the West Bank town of Hebron.
   Two firebombs were thrown at an Israeli car in annexed east
Jerusalem. The driver was burned on the arm and his leg was injured
when he lost control of the vehicle and crashed into a wall, police
spokesman Uzi Sandouri said.
   A bomb exploded under a truck in a Jewish neighborhood in
Jerusalem, slightly damaging the truck but causing no injuries,
police said.
   Likud hard-liners rallied in Tel Aviv to urge rejection of a
U.S.-proposed meeting of Israeli, Egyptian and American officials
to work out terms for Israeli-Palestinian talks in Cairo.
   Led by Industry Minister Ariel Sharon, among others, they view
U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III's idea as an attempt to
lure Israel into talks with the PLO and trade territory for peace.
   The two-hour, informal gathering was attended by hundreds of
representatives of Likud's 2,400-member governing central committee
who support hard-line ministers in the Likud-Labor government
formed last Dec. 22.
   ``If Labor continues to bother us in Parliament and the media
and to seek assistance of the Americans, the Egyptians and other
countries, I propose to go to elections,'' Economy Minister Yitzhak
Modai declared, to applause.
   ``They are going to lead us toward a Palestinian state, which
would endanger Israel's existence and which they see as a guarantee
of prosperity and peace. The rift is enormous.''
   Israel radio said Shamir had asked rebellious leaders to cancel
the session, saying it would complicate the political process.
   Senior officials in Finance Minister Shimon Peres' Labor Party
appeared willing to wait, but several dovish leaders in the party
said the government should be brought down.
   ``Likud's refusal to accept the Baker initiative would lead us
to government dismantling,'' said Chaim Ramon, head of Labor's
Parliament faction. ``The possibilities are open: elections ... or
a government led by us or being in opposition.''
   He told Israel TV after a meeting with other Labor ministers,
``We are united in our view that an end to the peace initiative
will lead to the end of our partership, but we are not united
regarding the timing now, or in two weeks or after Shamir's visit
to the United States'' in November.
   Israel has occupied the West Bank and Gaza Strip since capturing
them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. The United
States wants Israel to give up some occupied land for peace, but
Likud opposes returning any territory.
   ``This meeting confirms the real stand of Likud,'' said Sharon.
   He repeated his demand that the 22-month Palestinian uprising be
brought to an end before any negotiations start.
   Shamir leans toward the Baker idea, but only on condition the
tripartite meeting be devoted to Israel's own peace plan. It calls
for elections in the West Bank and Gaza Strip to choose Palestinian
negotiators for talks on limited autonomy.
   Baker advanced his proposal after Israel's decision-making,
12-member inner Cabinet split along party lines Friday and rejected
an Egyptian offer to act as host for an Israeli-Palestinian
discussion of the election plan in Cairo.
   Labor supported acceptance of the Egyptian invitation, designed
to bypass Israel's opposition to talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   The coalition was shaken further Wednesday when Shamir sent a
letter to Peres, demanding that Deputy Finance Minister Yossi
Beilin, known for his dovish views, be fired. Peres has refused to
dismiss his top aide.
</TEXT>
