<HEAD>Californian To Head Customs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carol Boyd Hallett, former California
legislator, U.S. ambassador and federal official, was named
Wednesday to become commissioner of Customs by Treasury Secreatary
Nicholas F. Brady.
   She will succeed William von Raab, who resigned under pressure
in July. In a parting shot, von Raab accused the federal government
of lacking the commitment to win the war on drugs.
   Mrs. Hallett, currently a consultant, served as ambassador to
the Bahamas from 1986 to 1989. She previously held serveral
positions in the Interior Department from 1984 to 1985, including
assistant to the secretary and West Coast representative of the
secretary.
   A California native, she served in the state's Assembly from
1976-1982, including that body's Republican leader from 1979 to
1982.
