<FIRST>r i AM-PuertoRico-Hugo     10-11 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Hugo,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Reports 26 Hurricane Deaths in Puerto Rico, Virgin Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo killed 26 people in
Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands when it swept through the
area in September, the American Red Cross said Wednesday.
   The figure brings to at least 74 the total number known dead
from the hurricane, which devastated several Caribbean islands as
well as parts of the Carolinas.
   The Red Cross said in a release that 18 people died in Puerto
Rico and eight died in the Virgin Islands, including five on the
resort island of St. Croix and three on nearby St. Thomas.
   Previous reports indicated 14 had died in Puerto Rico and three
in the Virgin Islands.
   The numbers include those killed during the storm Sept. 17-18
and subsequent hurricane-related deaths, such as injured victims
who later died and power linesmen killed while repairing downed
lines, said Red Cross spokeswoman Susan Clowe.
   The storm also killed 11 in Guadeloupe, 11 in Montserrat, one in
St. Kitts and 25 in North and South Carolina, authorities have said.
   The release also said the Red Cross has served more than 7
million meals in Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands since the
hurricane struck, including 113,000 Tuesday.
   It said 217 Red Cross shelters were currently housing 10,458
people in the two territories, down from 21,168 housed right after
the passage of Hugo.
   About 15,000 homes were destroyed and 35,000 damaged in Puerto
Rico, the release said.
   The Virgin Islands government estimated 90 percent of homes were
destroyed or damaged on St. Croix.
</TEXT>
