<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0746 10-11 0901</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0746,0925</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top-Ranking Trafficker Nabbed; Newspaper Closes Medellin Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with reported letter from Medellin
cartel leader seeking peace talks with the government; EDITS to trim. No
pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top-ranking member of the Medellin
cocaine cartel who resorted to plastic surgery to avoid arrest was
captured and will face extradition to the United States, police
said Wednesday.
   Meanwhile the reputed leader of the cartel, the largest in the
world, reportedly asked the Colombian government to begin peace
talks with drug traffickers. Pablo Escobar also said in the
reported letter that news reports of previous government
negotiations with drug lords were true.
   The Bogota daily El Espectador temporarily closed its Medellin
office after drug lords killed two of the newspaper's employees
there and threatened to murder the bureau's remaining staff of 11.
An executive of the anti-drug crusading newspaper said officials
will study how to improve office security.
   The Administrative Security Department said the suspected drug
trafficker who was captured, Jose Abello Silva, was arrested
Tuesday in a Bogota restaurant. The office said in a communique
that he had undergone facial surgery to avoid easy detection.
   It also said Abello is the fourth-ranking person in the Medellin
cocaine cartel and the most important suspect arrested since
Colombia began cracking down on cocaine lords Aug. 19.
   In Washington, Justice Department spokesman Harri J. Kramer said
a federal grand jury in Tulsa, Okla., indicted Abello in 1987 on
charges of conspiring to import and distribute cocaine.
   Kramer said the Justice Department had requested that Abello and
a suspect arrested Wednesday, Manuel Palma, be held for extradition.
   Palma is wanted by federal authorities in Miami on charges of
interstate travel in aid of racketeering in connection with an
operation to launder drug money, Kramer said.
   Details of Palma's arrest were not immediately available from
Colombia police.
   Neither Palma nor Abello is on the U.S. Justice Department's
list of 12 most wanted traffickers, but the department has said it
wants dozens of other Colombians on federal drug charges.
   Cornelius Dougherty, a spokesman for the Drug Enforcement
Administration, said in Washington Abello was responsible for
``major shipments of cocaine and marijuana into the states.''
   Colombia's Administrative Security Department said Abello was
the cartel's chief of operations for Colombia's northern coast,
where dozens of clandestine air strips are used to smuggle 300 to
400 tons of cocaine into the United States each year.
   The federal police force said legal documents from the U.S.
government for extraditing Abello were being processed.
   So far Colombia has extradited one suspected trafficker; four,
including Abello, are awaiting extradition.
   A letter reportedly signed by Escobar and delivered to the
director of a Bogota newspaper asked for mediation by the press,
political and church leaders and the judicial branch in a ``direct
dialogue'' between the government and the drug traffickers.
   The letter reportedly was addressed to Juan Carlos Pastrana,
director of La Prensa newspaper, and the text was read in a
broadcast by the national radio network Caracol.
   ``In the same way that war decrees can be issued so can peace
decrees be issued,'' Escobar said, refering to the hard-line
measures against drug traffickers adopted by President Virgilio
Barco after the Aug. 18 assassination of a leading presidential
candidate.
   As part of the decrees, Barco revived Colombia's extradition
treaty with the United States and confiscated hundreds of millions
of dollars in property believed to belong to drug lords.
   Escobar, the presumed leader of the Medellin cartel _ the
largest in the world _ heads the list of drug suspects wanted by
the United States.
   He is listed by Forbes magazine as one of the 20 wealthiest men
in the world with a fortune exceeding $2 billion.
   The letter attributed to Escobar said the drug lords and the
government first began talking before Sept. 1, 1988, when Barco
included the traffickers in a peace plan originally offered only to
Colombia's leftist guerrillas.
   The president never specifically indicated that drug traffickers
would be included, and government officials have repeatedly said
they never considered talking with the drug lords.
   La Prensa recently reported that Barco's closest adviser, German
Montoya, had received messages from the traffickers seeking a truce
beginning in September 1988.
   Montoya later admitted meeting once with the man carrying the
messages, former Interior Minister Joaquin Vallejo, but said he did
so without the president's knowledge.
   He said he told Vallejo from the beginning that a dialogue was
not possible.
   Vallejo said, however, that he met numerous times with Montoya
and that the contacts ended two days after suspected drug
traffickers assassinated Sen. Luis Carlos Galan Aug. 18.
   The newspaper El Espectador closed its office in Medellin after
an anonymous caller said the Extraditables _ a group of cocaine
traffickers _ had killed the two employees Tuesday and would kill
the others in Medellin if the office remained open.
   ``El Espectador declares that it will be able to survive as a
free newspaper only if the government fulfills its obligation to
protect our lives and properties,'' the paper's directors said in a
letter sent to Interior Minister Carlos Lemmos Simmonds.
   A spokeswoman for the minister's office said there had been no
official response to the letter.
   El Espectador has been the most vociferous of Colombia's
newspapers in editorials calling on the government to crush the
nation's drug trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
