<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary     10-11 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Hungarian Socialist Party Meets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Rezsoe Nyers of the new
Hungarian Socialist Party declared on Wednesday that ``at present,
there is no communist party in Hungary,'' although ``there are
communists.''
   In an interview with Hungarian TV, Nyers rejected claims by
orthodox communists opposed to the establishment of the new party
that the old party continued to exist.
   The presidium of the Hungarian Socialist Party held its first
meeting on Wednesday as conservative communists apparently kept up
efforts to revive the disbanded Hungarian Socialist Workers
(communist) Party.
   Nyers was chairman of the communist party. He was elected
Socialist Party president at a key party congress this weekend that
voted the old communist party out of existence and founded the new
one.
   He said membership of the party had ``become confused'' by the
change.
   Hungarian radio said 43 communists in the industrial center of
Csepel, just south of Budapest, announced ``they are going to
continue to organize the HSWP and (are) calling on all chapters to
follow suit.''
   They said the delegate they sent to the party congress ``was not
authorized to abandon Marxism-Leninism,'' the radio reported.
   Nyers conceded it was ``likely (they) ... will organize a
communist party.''
   But, he said, ``those who agree with the HSWP line and want to
continue must organize a new party. I do not think they can use the
name HSWP.''
   If the word ``new'' or ``original'' were added to the name,
however, then it ``would be acceptable,'' he went on.
   The English-language Daily News in Budapest said Wednesday
former party ideologist Janos Berecz confirmed he wants ``to stay
on'' as a member of the old communist party. Karoly Grosz,
secretary-general of the party until it was dissolved, repeatedly
has said he wished to remain a member of the old party.
   The independent daily Mai Nap quoted Berecz as saying Tuesday,
``We are staying in the HSWP and I hope that a significant segment
of the membership will do likewise.''
   Also on Tuesday, the state news agency MTI said the extreme
leftist Marxist Unity Platform was encouraging communists to rejoin
the old party.
   Another radical leftwing group, the Ferenc Muennich Society, is
also known to strongly oppose dissolution of the communist party.
   Nyers said the new 25-member presidium at its meeting Wednesday
discussed lower level organization, the fate of party-controlled
assets and of the Workers' Militia, the old party's paramilitary
body.
   He replied when asked about expected membership of the new party
that it was ``impossible to say'' how many of the old party's
720,000 members would want to belong. He speculated it could be
between 50 and 70 percent.
</TEXT>
