<DOCNO> AP891011-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Drugs     10-11 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Drugs,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Assembly Will Hold Anti-Drug Special Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key U.N. committee decided by
acclamation Wednesday to hold a special General Assembly session on
fighting the international drug traffickers.
   The General Assembly's general committee decided without debate
or dissent to have the entire assembly take up the issue Tuesday
and decide when the special session should be held. Most diplomats
expect the session to be held in February.
   Since nearly all of the 159 members of the General Assembly have
delegates on the general committee, approval of the anti-drug
special session is assured.
   The General Assembly seized the initiative after a British
effort to have the Security Council deal with the issue was
withdrawn after many developing nations opposed council involvement
in a social concern.
   Algeria and Brazil particularly opposed the expansion of the
Security Council into areas other than the military aspect of
security, said diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Colombia's President Virgilio Barco won a standing ovation from
the General Assembly on Sept. 29 when he called on all nations to
ratify the 1988 Vienna Convention on Narcotics Trafficking, which
closes legal loopholes giving drug dealers safe haven in some
countries.
   The treaty, strongly backed by Washington, requires nations to
make drug trafficking illegal, confiscate dealers' property and
bank accounts and extradite drug lords even if there is no
applicable extradition treaty.
   Twenty nations must ratify the treaty before it comes into
effect. So far, only the Bahamas has done so and Washington and
London are considering signing.
   About 100 countries have signed the treaty, the first step
toward ratification.
</TEXT>
