<DOCNO> AP891011-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RacistMonument     10-11 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racist Monument,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Road Work Leads To Removal Of Obelisk Dedicated to White Supremacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Liberty Monument, a Reconstruction-era
obelisk dedicated to white supremacy, is being removed from
downtown New Orleans' main street to make room for road
construction, city officials say.
   The stone monument stands in the middle of Canal Street near the
Rivergate Convention Center has been the target of civil rights
complaints for years.
   The obelisk is being removed to improve access to the
Mississippi River ferry and the Aquarium of the Americas, which is
scheduled to open next year. The marker will go into storage,
officials said Tuesday.
   It was erected to commemorate the so-called the Battle of
Liberty Place, fought nearby on Sept. 14, 1874.
   The White League, a group of prominent whites angered by alleged
corruption in the state's biracial Republican government, fought
the Metropolitan Police, which supported the Reconstruction regime.
   One source places the day's casualties at 27 killed and 105
wounded. The White League won the day, but Reconstruction was not
finally ended and white ``home rule'' restored until 1877.
   The cornerstone of the monument was laid in 1891. For many
years, wreath-laying ceremonies were held there each Sept. 14.
   In the 1970s, blacks demanding the monument's removal criticized
inscriptions added to it in 1932 extolling white supremacy. In
1974, a plaque repudiating the references to white supremacy was
added to the monument.
   In 1981, Dutch Morial, the city's first black mayor, tried to
have the memorial torn down, but his efforts were blocked by the
City Council. The controversial inscriptions were removed.
   Streets Department Director Betty Jo Everett said she did not
inform Mayor Sidney Barthelemy or the City Council before ordering
the monument removed.
   She said a decision on its fate will be up to a committee that
oversees all city monuments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Coming-OutDay     10-11 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coming-Out Day,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homosexuals Hold `Coming-Out' Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of gay men and women across the nation celebrated their
sexuality with rallies, films and discussions Wednesday on the
second annual ``National Coming Out Day.''
   ``National Coming Out Day is great. It's like a holiday,'' said
Tony Cheek, executive assistant at the Los Angeles Gay and Lesbian
Community Services Center, where about 500 people gathered.
   The celebration at the center included discussion of such films
as ``The Life and Times of Harvey Milk,'' about San Francisco's
murdered gay city supervisor.
   Cheek said the day's highlight was an open microphone at which
people could tell their own stories of coming out _ gay slang for
publicly acknowledging one's homosexuality.
   ``Some were funny, but there were a lot of tear-jerkers,'' he
said. ``We had a lot of first-timers.''
   In Providence, R.I., about 50 people attended a rowdy Statehouse
rally and said they hoped to inspire tens of thousands of others to
acknowledge their homosexuality.
   None of the demonstrators was ``coming out of the closet'' for
the first time, organizers said. Most were veterans of other gay
pride events, and they said the real coming-out process is one
that's done privately.
   ``My coming out was when I opened the dictionary at age 14 and
looked up the word `homosexual' and realized that applies to me,''
said John Blakeslee, 34, of Providence.
   At the University of Massachusetts in Amherst, students were
asked to wear black or pink to support the celebration. Black,
always a popular choice of students, proliferated on campus by
mid-morning.
   ``This campus is so diverse, civility and being aware of social
issues is really important,'' said Max Mitchell, a senior and
president of the school's Lesbian Bisexual and Gay Alliance.
   In Boston, the Massachusetts Senate gave all but final approval
Wednesday to a bill banning discrimination against homosexuals in
housing, credit and employment.
   The bill, which has died in the Senate for each of the last 17
years, moved along after Senate President William Bulger ruled that
amendments offered by several opponents were merely delaying
tactics.
   ``This really is the people's victory,'' David LaFontaine of the
Coalition for Lesbian and Gay Civil Rights. ``We are going to
herald this as a major step forward in the civil rights movement.''
   The Atlanta Gay Center sponsored a help-line and bought local
advertising to commemorate a homosexual rights march in Washington
two years ago. Gay residents had their names printed in the ads as
part of the commemoration.
   North of San Francisco Bay, the Marin County Board of
Supervisors voted 4-0 to proclaim Wednesday ``Marin Coming Out
Day,'' despite protests by evangelical ministers that the county
should not be endorsing gay lifestyles.
   Ken Searle, pastor at Marin Christian Life Church in Novato,
said he was ``very disappointed'' because the board's action ``will
be perceived by the community as an endorsement of the lifestyle.''
   Supervisor Al Aramburu, one of two who wore ``Coming Out''
buttons, said the proclamation reflects a ``spirit of respect.''
   ``I think we respect one another as human beings,'' he said.
   Cheek said holding the annual day helps end homophobia by
letting the heterosexual world know that there are gays and
lesbians all around them.
   ``If you find out your next door neighbor that you've known all
along is gay, then how can you hate him?'' Cheek said.
</TEXT>
