<FIRST>u w AM-CableTVBlackouts     10-11 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable TV Blackouts,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Industry Warning of Rerun Blackout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some aging but still popular TV shows may fade
from the nation's cable systems in January, and the cable industry
wants customers to know who's to blame _ the government.
   The National Cable Television Association is providing cable
systems with short announcements warning viewers that shows such as
``Cheers,'' ``Mork and Mindy,'' and ``Hee-Haw'' may disappear after
Jan. 1.
   The reason is the return of ``syndex,'' industry jargon for the
Federal Communications Commission regulations that allow local,
over-the-air television stations exclusive rights to the
syndicated, non-network programs they show in their market.
   The FCC is reinstating the rules it lifted in 1980 as a way to
boost the then-infant cable industry.
   If the rules survive pending court challenges, some reruns may
disappear completely in some cities. That could happen if cable
systems, forced to black out some time slots from ``distant''
stations that carry the same programs as local broadcasters, decide
to drop the out-of-town stations entirely.
   Cable operators, fearing a backlash from viewers, are using the
announcements as a pre-emptive strike to make sure customers knows
it's not their fault.
   Preston Padden, president of the Association of Independent
Television Stations, is a proponent of reinstating the syndex rules.
   ``Our entire constitutional copyright system is based on
recognizing and honoring contracts between creators and
exhibitors,'' Padden said.
   But Steven J. Simmons, chairman of Simmons Communications Inc.,
says the rules are ``terribly unfriendly to consumers.''
   Simmons, whose company has 350,000 subscribers in 20 states,
said broadcasters have indicated they will claim exclusivity for
programs such as ``The Oprah Winfrey Show,'' ``Who's the Boss?',
``Hee-Haw,'' ``Simon and Simon,'' ``The A-Team,'' ``Wheel of
Fortune,'' ``M.A.S.H.,'' ``I Love Lucy,'' ``Golden Girls,'' ``A
Current Affair,'' ``Donahue,'' ``Amen'' and ``Mork and Mindy.''
   Those shows would be carried on only one station in any market,
Simmons said in a telephone interview from his Stamford, Conn.,
office.
   ``The requirements could have such an impact that a cable
company, rather than have a subscriber sit there and watch
essentially Swiss cheese ... may just decide to drop the channel
altogether,'' Simmons said.
   The rules would affect national ``superstations'' such as WTBS
in Atlanta, WGN in Chicago and WWOR in New York and so-called
regional TV stations such as WPIX in New York and KTLA in Los
Angeles.
   Turner Broadcasting System, which owns WTBS, Turner Network
Television and Cable News Network, said WTBS would be
``syndex-proof.'' TBS is telling cable operators it will indemnify
them against any syndex problems.
   ``We've already made arrangements to have a blackout-free
schedule,'' Bert Carp, a TBS official in Washington, said in a
recent interview. He said TBS had managed to either acquire
national exclusivity for its programs or acquire new programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
