<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Labor     10-11 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Labor,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Changing of the Guard at Labor Federation a Political Coup for Menem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran labor leader Saul
Ubaldini was voted out of office Wednesday in a political victory
for President Carlos Menem.
   The secretary-general of the General Labor Confederation was
unseated at a rowdy congress punctuated the day before by
fistfights and clashes between rival union members wielding iron
bars, clubs, chains, bottles and stones.
   Guerino Andreoni, leader of the commerce workers union, was
elected to replace Ubaldini as head of the 3 million-member
confederation. Most of the members work at state companies,
including the national airlines and railroad, which have been
losing tens of millions of dollars annually for years.
   Ubaldini had been considered a rival capable of undermining
Menem's economic policy. Menem has held down workers' wages as a
way to halt inflation, which soared by 197 percent in July, the
month he took office. The September increase was 9.4 percent.
   The president also pressured state rail workers to end a strike
last month, and caused concern among state employees about their
jobs and benefits by pledging to sell money-losing public companies
to balance the budget.
   Ubaldini insisted he did not oppose Menem, but always stressed
his independence.
   ``Nothing and no one will impede our fight'' to improve workers'
welfare, he said on Aug. 17, hours after his car was damaged by a
bomb.
   During the 1983-89 presidency of Raul Alfonsin, which ended in
July, Ubaldini organized 13 general strikes and pressed for
increases in the national minumum wage, public programs to reduce
unemployment and a halt to payments on Argentina's foreign debt.
   Menem had tried to oust Ubaldini since his labor-based Peronist
Party swept presidential and congressional elections May 14,
offering the trade unionist a high-level post in an overseas
embassy, among other things.
   But the beer workers union chief, who has led the labor
confederation since 1980, refused.
   Menem made no immediate comment on Ubaldini's ouster, nor did
Labor Minister Jorge Triaca or their ally in the trade union
movement, foodworkers union chief Luis Barrionuevo.
   But soon after the confederation's entire 20-member board of
directors was replaced late Wednesday, Barrionuevo told reporters
he briefed Menem on the development and Government House officially
recognized the new confederation leadership.
   Ubaldini's term does not expire until February 1990, and the
fiery unionist pledged to stay on until then.
   ``We have not resigned,'' he told cheering, chanting supporters
gathered outside confederation headquarters in San Telmo
neighborhood near Buenos Aires' port. ``The secretary general
continues to be me.''
   In an editorial titled ``Labor At the Crossroad,'' the
English-language Buenos Aires Herald newspaper criticized the
scuffles that broke out Tuesday outside the convention hall where
1,600 confederation delegates gathered.
   ``At stake is whether the government can continue to tame the
inflation which has fallen from nearly 200 percent in July to
single digits in September, or whether a wage offensive spearheaded
by Ubaldini ... will drive a coach and horse through government
incomes policy,'' it said.
</TEXT>
