<DOCNO> AP891011-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CorporateVeil-Superfund     10-11 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corporate Veil-Superfund,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corporate Parent Of Polluter Held Liable Under Superfund Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company cannot hide behind a
``corporate veil'' to avoid funding the cleanup of a toxic chemical
spill caused by a subsidiary, a federal judge ruled Wednesday in
one of the first such cases in the country.
   Kayser-Roth Corp.'s tight control over subsidiary Stamina Mills
Inc. makes it liable to pay $846,492 to clean up a 1969 release of
trichlorethylene, or TCE, that the government contends contaminated
nearby drinking wells, U.S. District Judge Francis J. Boyle ruled.
   ``Kayser-Roth had the power to control the release or threat of
release of TCE, had the power to direct the mechanisms causing the
release, and had the ultimate ability to prevent and abate
damage,'' Boyle wrote.
   Deming Sherman, Kayser-Roth's attorney, and U.S. Justice
Department lawyer Cynthia Huber said they believed it was the first
Superfund case prosecuted by the federal government in which a U.S.
judge made a parent corporation liable for the actions of its
subsidiary.
   Kayser-Roth, a hosiery and apparel manufacturer, argued it could
not be forced to pay because it was protected from liability by a
``corporate veil'' that shielded it from the acts of its
subsidiary, which operated a now-defunct woolen mill in North
Smithfield.
   The corporate veil, a long-established legal doctrine, protects
investors in new ventures from losing all their assets and is a
major reason that most business activities are carried on by
corporations.
   The veil is rarely pierced, and only when a parent company is
shown to have overwhelmingly controlled its subsidiary.
   The judge said Kayser-Roth fit that category because of its
total control over Stamina's finances, its order that Stamina refer
environmental matters to Kayser-Roth's legal department, and its
approval of all Stamina real estate deals and capital purchases
greater than $5,000.
   Boyle also said Kayser-Roth executives served as most of
Stamina's officers and directors.
   ``Kayser-Roth has exhibited overwhelming pervasive control over
Stamina Mills,'' Boyle wrote.
   The judge said he was concerned primarily with furthering the
Superfund law's intent to let the government collect the cleanup
costs in hazardous waste cases.
   The law ``attempts to address nationwide public health and
environmental problems'' and ``places no special importance upon
the corporate structure,'' Boyle wrote.
   Sherman called it ``a pretty broad opinion'' and said he
believed Kayser-Roth would have case law on its side if it decided
to appeal.
   The Wall Street Journal recently reported that three federal
judges in the past five months, including Boyle, had declined to
dismiss cases based on corporate veil arguments. An agreement in
principal had been reached to settle one of those cases, against
T&amp;N PLC, an English holding company, the newspaper said.
   The government has sought to pierce the corporate veil because
parent companies often have greater resources to pay for hazardous
waste cleanups than do their subsidiaries.
   Boyle also rejected Kayser-Roth's argument that the government
could not prove the wells were contaminated by Stamina Mills.
   ``On this record it is sheer speculation to suggest that there
was any other source of TCE,'' the judge said.
   The judgment includes $660,612 to the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency and $185,879 to the Justice Department.
Kayser-Roth also will be liable for any future cleanup costs at the
Stamina site, Boyle wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0200 </DOCNO>
