<FIRST>r a AM-ProstituteSlayings     10-11 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prostitute Slayings,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect in Prostitute Slayings Arraigned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was arraigned Wednesday on two
counts of murder in the killing of two prostitutes, but police said
he was not a suspect in the slayings of four other Oakland
prostitutes in the last three months.
   Dewain Hall, 26, did not enter a plea during a brief appearance
before Municipal Court Judge Horace Wheatley. Investigators said
Hall has confessed to the charges, which include two counts of
attempted murder.
   Hall was arrested Monday night after he was turned in by a woman
who said he told her about the slayings, then forced her at
gunpoint to shoot a passerby so she would not turn him in to
authorities, police said.
   Hall, a paroled convict, is accused of killing Annie Green, 29,
on Sept. 20, and Teresa Ann Greenlee, 26, whose body was found five
days later.
   The attempted murder charges stem from the passerby shooting and
the Sept. 24 wounding of a third prostitute who refused to date
Hall, police said.
   Hall is not a suspect at present in the slayings of four other
Oakland prostitutes whose bodies have been found in recent months,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
