<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CensusDebate     10-11 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Census Debate,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Refuses to Consider Census Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday refused to take up a
measure that would have ordered the Census Bureau to exclude
illegal aliens from next year's census.
   It was a test of strength that pitted Sunbelt states whose
populations have been swollen by illegal aliens against Frostbelt
states that stand to lose House seats after the census.
   By 232-184, the House used a parliamentary maneuver steered by
Rep. Silvio O. Conte, R-Mass., to keep the census measure off the
floor.
   That was the vote by which the House instructed its negotiators
in House-Senate talks to accept a provision in the Senate version
of the State, Justice and Commerce appropriations bill to condemn
the continuation in power of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in Panama.
   The rules permit only one set of instructions to a conference
committee. Thus Rep. Thomas Ridge, R-Pa., was blocked from offering
his own set of instructions on the census question to the House
members of the same committee.
   Ridge's provisions would have ordered the House negotiators to
accept another Senate-passed provision, this one to barring the use
of any money for the Census Bureau to count illegal aliens in its
1990 head count.
   The census bureau has always counted residents regardless of
citizenship. Past efforts to exclude illegal aliens from the count
have always died in committee.
   The matter is important to several northeastern and midwestern
states which expect to lose House seats in redistricting following
that census.
   Under current census rules, California, Florida and Texas, with
many illegal aliens, expect to gain House seats while New York,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and Illinois are among those expected
to lose seats.
   Even though it was apparent they would not have a chance to get
a vote on the Ridge proposal, backers of the census change used the
hour devoted to the Noriega censure to debate the census issue.
   Ridge and others characterized it as a matter of political
fairness. ``I want equal representation for American citizens,''
argued Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa.
   Opponents argued that any change in census rules at this point
would cost $1 billion, including the cost of reprinting forms and
retraining the enumerators. They said it was not clear that the
census-takers could even get accurate information on citizenship.
   Rep. William Ford, D-Ky., called it, ``A fantasy'' that states
losing seats could save any by excluding aliens from the count.
   Opponents have said the Senate provision is clearly
unconstitutional, since the Constitution requires a census of
``persons.'' When the Constitution wants something to apply only to
citizens, it clearly says ``citizens,'' according to this argument.
   Supporters have argued that the Constitution gives Congress the
power to impose rules for the Census.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     10-11 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Opposition Party Accused of Tilt Toward Pinball Payoffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialist Party, Japan's major opposition
party, was challenged in Parliament on Wednesday to reply to
allegations that it tilted in favor of the pinball industry after
being fed sizeable donations.
   Koichi Hamada, a legislator of the governing Liberal Democrats,
cited a published report that eight Socialists helped water down
legislation regulating pachinko, a widely played form of pinball in
which winners receive prizes.
   The weekly magazine Shukan Bunshun said the eight received
donations from a national association of pachinko parlor owners
ranging from $1,400 to $3,500.
   Hamada, whose own party was badly hurt at the polls this year by
a major influence-peddling scandal, addressed his questions to the
justice minister during Budget Committee debate in the lower house.
   ``There have been allegations that some legislators have acted
to protect the (pachinko) industry while they were not supposed to
do so,'' he said.
   ``I will not name them right now, but the issue involves
something to be called the second Recruit scandal.''
   By Recruit Hamada was referring to a scandal in which leading
politicians and bureaucrats received donations or cut-price stock
shares from Recruit Co., a major information services conglomerate
accused of trying to influence government policy. Bribery charges
have been filed in that case.
   The justice minister replied he was aware of the allegations and
assumed that prosecutors were interested in the case.
   Tsuruo Yamaguchi, Socialist secretary-general, has acknowledged
that some party members received donations from the pachinko
association, including $31,000 for party chairwoman Takako Doi, but
said all the donations were legal.
   The magazine said donations to Ms. Doi, known to be a pachinko
fan, were in the form of ticket purchases for parties in her honor.
   The Recruit scandal and an unpopular new 3 percent sales tax
were major factors in the Liberal Democrats' losing their majority
in Parliament's upper house for the first time in 34 years in
elections in July. The Socialists were the major gainers in the
election.
   About 15,000 pachinko parlors operate across Japan, with annual
sales estimated at nearly $21 billion, Shukan Bunshun said.
   To help in investigating any tax evasion by the pachinko
industry, the National Police Agency has sought to introduce a
system in which customers would use prepaid cards, rather than
cash, to play pachinko machines.
   Socialist legislators strongly opposed such a system.
</TEXT>
