<DOCNO> AP891011-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     10-11 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>80 Bodies Of Sinhalese Youths Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bound bodies of 80 Sinhalese
youths, all shot and some set on fire, were found along a southern
road on Wednesday and authorities blamed pro-government death
squads.
   No one claimed responsibility, but authorities speculated the
killings were the work of death squads out to avenge the ambush
slayings of three Sinhalese soldiers in the district on Monday.
   The bodies were discovered one day before the government and
opposition parties wrap up monthlong peace talks aimed at resolving
Sri Lanka's ethnic differences. More than 16,000 people have died
in the strife.
   The bodies were found in groups of six or eight along a 20-mile
stretch of road between Panadura and Mataguma, said police
officials, who could not be identified under briefing rules.
   The towns are in Kalutara district, about 25 miles south of
Colombo.
   Officials said the victims were aged 18 to 30. Their hands were
tied behind their backs and the bodies bore gunshot wounds. Some
bodies were afire, they said.
   The ambush on Monday was blamed on Sinhalese militants of the
People's Liberation Front, a group trying to topple the government
for two years now.
   Human rights groups and opposition parties allege that vigilante
groups are killing sympathizers of the front, a charge denied by
President Ranasinghe Premadasa and his government.
   A Foreign Ministry official said Wednesday that a team of the
International Committee of the Red Cross will arrive Oct. 17 on an
invitation by Premadasa to monitor human rights practices in Sri
Lanka.
   The official, who also could not be identified under briefing
rules, said the Geneva-based body will send a preliminary team. He
had no details.
   Officials have said about 25 people a day are being killed in
the battle between Sinhalese radicals, the military and death
squads.
   Independent groups say the government encouraged the vigilantes
after the military failed to put down Sinhalese extremists.
   The front began attacking the Sinhalese-dominated government
after it signed a peace accord in July 1987 designed to give
greater autonomy to the island nation's Tamil minority.
   The accord followed six years of Tamil insurgency in the
northeast where most Tamils live and want to set up a separate
homeland. The insurrection has claimed 11,000 lives.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They
allege discrimination in jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who
make up 75 percent of the population and control the government and
the military.
   Last month Premadasa convened a peace conference of 21 of the
country's 27 recognized political parties. It was boycotted by the
front.
   The conference is due to hold its final round of talks Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
