<DOCNO> AP891011-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Exile 1stLd-Writethru a0754 10-11 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Exile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adjustment Takes Time After 7,904 Days in South African Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 21st graf `After a ...' with 1 graf to ADD that he visited
his daughter in Israel before going to Britain. Pickup 22nd graf `I told
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denis Goldberg no longer feels uneasy in a crowd.
But whenever he sits down to write his memoirs, the recollections
of 21 years in a South African prison still overwhelm him.
   He served the longest prison term imposed on a white militant,
and now is in his fifth year in British exile. But he says the
ideals that got him, Nelson Mandela and six other black
nationalists locked up for plotting to overthrow the white-led
minority government made his life sentence bearable.
   ``I didn't count every day I was in prison, but I calculated
it,'' Goldberg, now 56, says in an interview. ``I was there 7,904
days. I don't regret one day, it was worth it.
   ``I certainly do not repudiate my past actions. I do not
repudiate the armed struggle _ I think it's essential.''
   At 29, Goldberg was an engineer turned bomb-maker for the
African National Congress, the banned black nationalist movement.
He was arrested at an ANC hideout in Johannesburg and given three
life sentences in June 1964 for ``campaigning to overthrow the
government by violent revolution.''
   Deported in 1985 after undertaking not to participate in
political violence, he now runs the ANC's mail order business in
north London selling mostly T-shirts and posters. He lectures
occasionally in Britain and abroad.
   On Tuesday, President F.W. de Klerk said he will free five of
Goldberg's co-defendants, including ANC political strategist Walter
Sisulu, but not Mandela.
   The other co-defendant, Govan Mbeki, was freed in 1987.
   Goldberg calls their release ``a public relations exercise to
show de Klerk is amenable to change.''
   It took Goldberg two years to adjust to freedom in London.
Finally, one morning, ``suddenly I felt at ease; The crowds didn't
bother me.''
   ``There's a lot of softness and gentleness outside that is
enriching,'' he says. ``It sounds corny but it's very, very true. I
find life incredibly exciting, fulfilling and worthwhile.''
   His wife Esme, 60, says: ``Prison made him tender.''
   But the memories of prison run deep.
   ``I find that when I do sit down to write about it, I simply
don't sleep,'' he said. ``A recollection of one incident brings
back a whole chain of incidents and events, and I find that this
just overwhelms me.''
   The former engineer said he gradually was driven to violence by
revulsion for apartheid, the race-separation system under which 5
million whites disenfranchise 28 million blacks.
   He's chubbier now and losing his hair, and his quirky humor
masks a deep hurt at having missed seeing his two children grow up.
   His son, David, was 8 and his daughter, Hilary, 5 when he left
Cape Town in May 1963, intent on fleeing abroad. A bomb had
exploded in his garden, obscenities were painted on his car and
police were clamping down on dissidents. He stayed on briefly to
organize arms production for the ANC.
   ``Had I not been arrested, I would have gone on to start
production of land mines and grenades and timing devices and so
on,'' he says. ``Bomb-maker is a pejorative term. My people said
that what I was doing was just and justified.''
   Goldberg served most of his sentence in the whites-only Pretoria
Prison.
   ``In a country where prison is the norm in the lives of most
black South Africans, it was perhaps a way of identifying,'' he
said. ``That we could survive and come out relatively whole people
is really a victory over people who try to smash us.''
   He first visited his daughter at a kibbutz in Israel before
flying to Britain, where his wife and son moved during his trial.
Goldberg said his son, who in 1985 was 29 and married with
children, ``needed me to tell him I hadn't left him.''
   ``I told him I didn't see how I could ever make my family above
all other families,'' he says. ``Kids suffer and starve not because
their parents are politically active, but that's the nature of
apartheid, and I felt I had to do something.''
   His eyes reddened with emotion behind horn-rimmed glasses.
   ``I've had some suffering. So! Lots of people have died. People
are getting hanged, people are getting shot. I'm alive. Life's
great.''
</TEXT>
