<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India     10-11 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Tries to Shout Down Gandhi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition members shouted slogans and
walked out of the upper house of Parliament Wednesday after the
house chairman rejected demands that Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
answer allegations in a multimillion dollar arms scandal.
   Gandhi was not present during the uproar in the Rajya Sabha, or
house of the nation, but was heckled by opposition members who
returned when he entered the chamber to announce a new employment
scheme.
   Opposition members waved copies of a newspaper that published
the allegations and demanded Gandhi explain news reports of
kickbacks being paid in the 1986 purchase of artillery from the
Swedish company, AB Bofors.
   Members of Gandhi's Congress Party, who have a 142-100 majority
in the house, shouted back, trying to drown out opposition members
chanting ``Corrupt Rajiv Gandhi, resign, resign.''
   The opposition legislators walked out when the house chairman,
Vice President Shankar Dayal Sharma, said he would permit a
discussion on the newspaper report but would not summon Gandhi.
   They returned 90 minutes later when Gandhi entered to read a
statement on creating 1 million new jobs throughout the country,
and drowned most of his 30-minute speech in continuous
slogan-shouting and catcalls.
   The Hindu, a Madras-based daily, said in a front-page story
Monday that there was new evidence to prove kickbacks were paid in
the $1.4 billion deal to purchase Bofors' howitzer guns.
   Newspapers have alleged that Bofors paid $50 million to clinch
the contract and that some of the money went to senior members of
the government. Gandhi has repeatedly denied the charges.
   The allegations were first made in 1987 but have re-surfaced in
recent months as the usually fractious opposition tries to form a
coalition in an effort to unseat Gandhi in national elections due
by January.
   The opposition's efforts to focus public attention on the issue
have included the resignations of 100 Parliament members from the
542-seat lower house, or Lok Sabha, in August. The resigning
members claimed the Congress Party was using its majority to stifle
discussion on the Bofors gun deal.
   Monday's article in The Hindu said secret portions of a report
by the Swedish National Audit Bureau reveal that at least $31
million were paid to a Panama-based company, whose majority owner
was the Indian agent of Bofors in New Delhi.
   The article said the Indian and Swedish government's appeared to
have colluded in keeping that portion of the report secret and
releasing a ``sanitized'' version.
   The newspaper printed photocopies of what it said were the
withheld portions of the report. Next to the photocopies, The Hindu
reprinted three public comments of Gandhi reiterating that no
Indian had received money from the Swedish company.
</TEXT>
