<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-Seizure     10-11 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Seizure,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bail Denied For Trio in Biggest Cocaine Seizure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men facing charges in the world's
largest cocaine seizure were denied bail Wednesday by a judge who
citied a substantial risk of flight by the three, one of whom is a
professional pilot.
   U.S. Magistrate Volney Brown agreed with prosecutors that James
McTague, 41, of El Paso, Texas; Mauricio Monroy, 36, of Mexico
City; and Hugo Fernando Castillon, 32, of Los Angeles, had no
reason to remain here.
   A separate bail hearing was set for Thursday for Miguel Garcia
Chavez, 34, Los Angeles. Pending indictment, all four men face a
federal complaint of possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute.
   They were arrested in the Sept. 28 seizure of what officials say
was 21 tons of cocaine, which has since been destroyed, and about
$12 million in cash discovered at a warehouse in suburban Sylmar.
It was the largest seizure of cocaine on record.
   One defense attorney tried to close the bail hearing to the news
media and another launched an attack on the chain of custody for
their clients, who had faced state charges before being handed over
to federal authorities.
   ``A lot of local politicians and officials have ridden on the
backs of these defendants to enhance their careers,'' said attorney
Marlene Gertz, representing Castillon and Monroy, the pilot.
   ``There's been lots of publicity, and this publicity has been
very detrimental,'' she said in arguing for a closed hearing.
``This bad publicity will continue unless the press is excluded.
The press has already convicted these defendants.''
   Brown denied the motion without comment, along with a motion by
McTague lawyer Michael Pancer to dismiss the charges because the
change from state to federal custody was ``an unnecessary and
improper delay.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James Walsh said that with several
agencies involved in the investigation, officials needed time to
sort out the proper jurisdiction for prosecution.
   County prosecutors dropped charges Friday against the four men
so they could face charges in federal court where drug conviction
penalties are stricter.
   Brown set a hearing date of Oct. 24 and a post-indictment
arraignment on Oct. 30 for all four defendants in Los Angeles.
   Also Wednesday, prosecutors gave an account of how much cocaine
was seized at the warehouse.
   Federal agents and local police said the haul from the warehouse
weighed 42,800 pounds, including packaging. They subtracted about
800 pounds for packaging, leaving 21 tons.
   McTague is the brother-in-law of Hector Tapia Anchondo, 38, one
of the alleged leaders of the smuggling operation. Authorities said
McTague also identified the mastermind of the drug ring as Rafael
Munoz of Juarez, Mexico.
   Tapia and Carlos Tapia Ponce, 68, father of Tapia Achondo, were
arrested in Las Vegas on Saturday in connection with the cocaine
find. Munoz remains at large.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
