<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Storm 1stLd-Writethru a0732 10-11 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Storm, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Dan Leaves 21 People Dead, Thousands Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with further deaths, other details.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Dan, the ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Dan pummeled the Philippines
Wednesday with 74 mph winds, killing at least 21 people, injuring
57 and forcing more than 125,000 to flee their homes, officials
said.
   In addition, at least 33 fishermen were missing after Dan
battered Manila and southern areas of Luzon island.
   The storm was heading for Vietnam early Thursday.
   Dan was upgraded from a tropical storm to a typhoon late
Wednesday when its winds increased from 62 mph to 74 mph.
   It left five people dead in the Manila area, four on Marinduque
Island, four in Laguna province, two in Cavite province, three in
Bataan province, two in Pampanga province and one in Quezon
province, rescue officials said.
   Officials said about 126,000 people, especially coastal
residents, were evacuated to churches, schools and relief centers.
   Officials said 13 fishing boats ran aground in Batangas
province, 60 miles south of Manila, and one near the U.S. naval
base at Subic Bay, 50 miles west of here, during the storm.
   Red Cross spokeswoman Lourdes Masing said 14 fishermen were
missing aboard seven boats that disappeared in Subic Bay. Another
10 people were missing after the Simon Peter, a boat used in deep
sea diving, ran aground in Subic, Ms. Masing said.
   Seven people swam safely to shore but rescuers were still
looking for 10 other people.
   In Batangas province, the coast guard said 10 people were
rescued after two fishing boats sank when they collided Tuesday off
Bauan, 50 miles south of Manila. Nine people were missing,
officials said.
   An average of 20 typhoons or tropical storms strike the
Philippines each year.
   Dan, the 16th this year, slammed into Sorsogon province late
Tuesday on the southeastern tip of Luzon. It raced across Luzon,
passing just south of Manila before entering the South China Sea.
   President Corazon Aquino ordered government offices in Manila to
close Wednesday except for essential services and trading was
canceled on the Manila and Makati stock exchanges.
   U.S. Air Force officials at Clark Air Base, north of Manila,
said Dan knocked out 80 percent of the electricity in the camp's
housing area.
   About 95 percent of the Manila area, which has a population of
more than 7 million, was without electricity as strong winds ripped
down power lines.
   Sen. Vicente Paterno called on the government to declare a state
of calamity in the affected areas to prevent profiteering on basic
goods such as rice and cooking oil.
   Philippine Airlines canceled 36 domestic flights and
international service was disrupted.
   At Manila's airport, Dan's winds pushed the Boeing 707 of
visiting Deputy Prime Minister Qais al-Zawawi of Oman into the
DC-10 that brought President Hussain Muhammad Ershad of Bangladesh
here Monday for a four-day visit.
</TEXT>
