<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv12   10-11 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 12,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Oct 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trading Dollars For Hours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Time is money.''
   Though that proverb dates to ancient history, repeated over the
centuries by sages like Benjamin Franklin and Charles Dickens, it
is by no means worn out.
   In fact, in an era of two-income families, convenience stores,
fax machines and microwave ovens, it has taken on new relevance as
one of the most common, and important, principles people apply to
the business of their daily lives.
   A ``service economy'' like that of the United States today
provides more and more situations in which you can, or must,
exchange one of those valued commodities for the other.
   So the questions naturally arise: How much is your time worth in
dollars? And, by no means incidentally, how much are your dollars
worth in time?
   For most people who work for wages or salaries, one quick answer
to that question is available from the stub on your last paycheck:
$5 an hour, or $10, or $50, or $500. Perhaps overtime gets you
time-and-a-half, or 50 percent more.
   Similarly, anyone with a hand-held calculator can estimate the
``time value'' of his or her money. If you invest $3,650 at a 10
percent yield in a one-year certificate of deposit, the bank pays
you about about $1 a day for the use of your money.
   But the reckoning gets more complicated once you start to deal
with problems involving more variables that are harder to quantify.
   For example, what is the net income your household realizes from
a second job that requires extra expenses for day care,
transportation and convenience foods? How much return per hour do
you actually get from clipping and filing supermarket coupons?
   And how high must the hourly labor rate charged by a plumber or
electrician go before it behooves you to take on the labors, and
risks, of home repairs yourself?
   Often, of course, necessity makes the decision for you. If you
lack the money, you find the time somehow. If an urgent mission is
beyond your time and skills, you endeavor to scrape up the money
somewhere.
   Still, even in cases like these, there can be tradeoffs
involved. Suppose you have a household problem for which you must
hire a contractor.
   By the traditional wisdom, notes John T. Reed in his newsletter
Real Estate Investor's Monthly, you should get estimates from at
least three contractors before you hire one for the job. To get the
best possible price, you might even call in every contractor in
your area.
   The more exhaustive your selection process, though, the more
time you are likely to spend trying to save money.
   Cases like this give you an opportunity to perform an
instructive exercise. If you keep track of the money saved and the
time spent on a given project, you can simply divide the dollar
amount of savings by the number of hours you put in.
   The result of that one-step calculation gives you the value in
dollars per hour you have set for yourself on your time.
   Conversely, if you pay someone else to tackle something you
might have done yourself, you can divide the extra expense by your
estimate of how many hours of work you saved. That tells you how
much money you are willing to spend in exchange for an hour of your
time.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Oct. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1402EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv12   10-11 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 12,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Oct. 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Greenspan Remains on Course</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you examine an economist carefully, you
generally will find an individual who believes inflation is one of
the great threats to mankind _ not just to man's economy, but to
his existence.
   They have good reasons for the feeling, because inflation not
only corrupts the currency but eventually erodes quality, morality,
ambition, contracts, values and responsibilities at individual,
group and governmental levels.
   Still, not all economists put inflation at the top of their
lists of things to avoid. There is another group that says constant
worry and maneuvering to avoid inflation can produce equal or worse
consequences.
   Those two groups are now fighting it out, and it could be a
slugfest. In one group is a White House that sees economic growth
as a more important goal than inflation fighting. In the other is
the Federal Reserve.
   They aren't likely to identify themselves as opponents, because
conflict tends to cause too much excitement in the marketplace, but
the scrap will be hard to disguise. These are two heavyweights.
   Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Fed, had made clear his position
that inflation is the bigger threat, and his actions suggest that
he is even willing to incur a mild recession in order to keep it
submerged.
   Greenspan hasn't just recently joined the anti-inflation group.
Back in the mid-1970s he chaired an anti-inflation commission for
President Ford that campaigned on the WIN ticket _ Whip Inflation
Now.
   Critics forgive him for that, because double-digit inflation was
a scourge of the 1970s, rising to double-digit levels that, while
making some people rich, disrupted markets, threatened banking
stability and destroyed savings.
   Greenspan's timing was less forgivable, since the WIN campaign
was launched while the nation's economy was about to plunge into a
recession, which for limited practical purposes can be called the
opposite of inflation.
   Ever since becoming Federal Reserve chairman in the Reagan
administration, Greenspan has continued to signal his fear of
inflation. While many economists celebrated inflation of less than
5 percent, Greenspan said it wasn't enough.
   In July 1988, when some economists were discussing the economy's
slow growth, Greenspan told the Senate Banking Committee that
unemployment was nearing its lower limit and industrial capacity
its upper limit.
   When those limits are reached, a true inflation fighter knows
that interest rates must be raised. Greenspan saw to it, and over
the next four months the Federal Funds rate increased a full
percentage point to 8.5 percent.
   Whether Greenspan saved the economy from inflation will be
debated forever; more important was the perception that he viewed
the economy as too hot when some of his brother economists thought
it was somewhat cool.
   Rather than raising interest rates, some of these colleagues
argued, shouldn't the country seek to expand its capacity? Expanded
capacity, new equipment and more efficient plants also could remove
an inflation threat.
   Edward Yardeni, Prudential-Bache economics director, expressed
the latter view late in 1988. If Greenspan tightened too much, he
said, he could abort the capital spending needed ``to expand
capacity he fears there isn't enough of.''
   This week, Greenspan seemed to issue another warning, advising
people not to expect easier money in the interest of expanding the
economy. He said in effect that the bigger threat is still
inflation rather than recession.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Oct. 12.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv13   10-11 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 13,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Oct. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Negotiating Pastors Challenging Methodist Tradition of Itineracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Lester Meyer remembers the phone call he received one
Saturday from another pastor wondering when Meyer and his family
were going to move out so he could move in.
   The other minister was embarrassed to learn Meyer had no idea he
had been transferred, but a generation ago it was not unusual for
the bishop to order a pastor to pull up stakes within a few days
and move to another outpost in the United Methodist Church.
   Now a member of the hierarchy himself, Meyer finds the
centuries-old tradition of the itineracy _ in which ministers are
guaranteed jobs for life in return for going where they are sent _
under challenge from clergy who no longer can or want to uproot
their families to serve a small, rural church or a poor urban
church.
   ``Formally, they still take the same vow. Practically speaking,
there is a different philosophy,'' said Meyer, district
superintendent of the Oklahoma City North District, part of the
United Methodists' Oklahoma Conference. ``The autocratic assignment
process simply would not work in the present social times.''
   The 9 million-member church that once operated on the principle
that ``a pastor always has a church, a church always has a pastor''
has had to adjust to the advent of clergy couples and working
spouses and to theological changes stressing the partnership of
bishops and clergy.
   The future of the itineracy is being weighed by a Commission for
the Study of Ministry. It began work in 1984 and expects to produce
a preliminary report early next year. The final report is to be
presented before the 1992 General Conference, the church's chief
policy-making body.
   The issue is not unique to the United Methodist Church.
   In the Roman Catholic Church, bishops have been consulting more
frequently with priests and parishes on clergy assignments in the
last 20 years, said the Rev. David Brinkmoeller, executive director
of the Secretariat for Priestly Life and Ministry of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops.
   ``It's a theological conviction'' that everyone has some
understanding of God's will, not just the bishops, Brinkmoeller
said.
   United Methodist Bishop Bruce Blake of Dallas, vice-chairman of
the Commission on Ministry, said the hierarchical ministry is being
phased out in many churches.
   ``I think what is happening in the itineracy is sort of symbolic
of what's happening in the church in general,'' Blake said.
``Collegiality, throughout the church, is replacing hierarchy and
competition.''
   In addition, pastors and their families have more at stake today
when considering a move.
   The ordination of women, for example, has produced the
corresponding phenomenon of clergy couples. There are about 600
clergy couples among the more than 38,000 ordained ministers in the
United Methodist Church.
   The rise in two-income families also has decreased mobility as
spouses veto moves too far from present jobs. Meyer estimates 80
percent of the clergy in his area have working spouses.
   But Brinkmoeller says ``the rub in the system'' of greater
consultation on personnel moves is that few changes are currently
possible; jobs in inner cities and remote areas still must be
filled.
   Some Episcopal bishops, in a recent ``Excellence in Ministry''
report for the church, ``commented sardonically that there was no
job shortage in some of the less attractive jobs in remote areas
and the inner cities.''
   Some within the United Methodist Church are concerned that
giving clergy veto power over jobs would make it more difficult to
fill less attractive positions, while the large, well-off churches
could shop around for the best and the brightest clergy. Nearly
two-thirds of United Methodist congregations have fewer than 200
members.
   What happens in practice, Meyer said, is that ``lesser
qualified'' clergy are sometimes appointed to rural churches.
   Blake said there is a tension within clergy between their call
to be in ministry and ``careerism,'' which he defined as a ``gross
national product'' understanding of vocation that equates bigger
with better.
   In Britain, Methodists have dealt with the issue by
standardizing clergy salaries. Proposals to do the same in the
United States have consistently been defeated, but Blake said the
issue will not go away.
   ``That is on the table. We must resolve it,'' Blake said. ``If
the guiding principle of one's ministry is one's career, that is
not theologically or ecclessiastically defensible.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Oct. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
