<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-11 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix cycle designator.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA announced that its planned
$1.5 billion takeover by Australia's Qintex Group has fallen apart.
   The deal was placed in jeopardy last week when MGM-UA revealed
that Qintex, an entertainment concern, failed to make a scheduled
$50 million down payment. MGM-UA said Tuesday that the deal had
collapsed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. is suing American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., claiming AT&amp;T tried to protect its
eroding share of the long-distance market through maliciously false
and deceptive advertising.
   The U.S. District Court suit filed Tuesday charges that
beginning in January this year, AT&amp;T launched a counterattack
against its competitors to regain market share, and in July began
targeting MCI's new cut-rate long-distance calling plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan says
Soviet economists appear largely unfettered by ideology as they
search for ways out of the country's financial woes.
   In a meeting that would have been unthinkable just a couple of
years ago, Greenspan on Tuesday held discussions with nine of the
top economic minds of a system that has been at the opposite end of
the philosophical spectrum for decades.
   Greenspan also hinted that U.S. interest rates would remain firm
in the near term despite the recent rise in the dollar.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AB Volvo says is holding discussions
with France's Renault, although it will not confirm published
reports that the automakers were in final negotiations for a merger
or joint venture.
   The business magazine Veckans Affarer, in its Wednesday edition,
said it had confirmation from sources at Volvo, Renault and the
Swedish government of the merger talks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The London International Financial Futures
Exchange plans to introduce an electronic trading system next month
to extend its trading hours in hopes of attracting more
international business.
   With a Nov. 30 launch date, the LIFFE, would beat the much
larger Chicago futures exchanges to the punch with an automated
trading system. The system would have an 11-hour day. The Chicago
Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange are planning
around-the-clock trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. has sweetened
its bid for LIN Broadcasting Corp., but also taken a step backward
by saying it would would seek only enough shares to control the
company rather than buy it outright.
   McCaw, based in the Seattle suburb of Kirkland, said Tuesday it
would pay $125 a share in cash for 22 million of LIN's
approximately 54 million outstanding shares, or $2.75 billion. The
total would give McCaw slightly more than 50 percent of LIN.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will file a fair-trade
complaint against the European Community over a non-binding quota
system designed to limit imported TV programs to no more than half
of all shows aired, U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills says.
   Hills, who previously said the United States would fight any
local content rules the European Community implements for
television as part of its plan to remove trade barriers among its
member nations by 1992, said Tuesday she was ``deeply disturbed''
by the Oct. 3 decision on TV.
