<TEXT>
   Stock prices lost ground Tuesday as many investors decided to
cash in on the market's recent gains. The Dow Jones industrials
average, falling for the first time this month, declined 6.08
points to 2,785.33.
   The dollar ended sharply higher after Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan hinted that U.S. interest rates would
remain firm in the near term.
   Bond prices fell as traders cashed in gains.
   Copper futures prices rose to new highs before plunging on
reports that a 3-month-old strike at a Canadian copper mine was
nearly settled; soybeans sank to 23-month lows while grain futures
were mixed; energy futures rose strongly; precious metals
retreated; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
