<DOCNO> AP891011-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FDA-FoodPackages     10-11 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Food Packages,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Ponders Safety Regulations for Microwave Packaging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration says it will
evaluate heat-sensitive food packaging materials designed for
microwave cooking to determine whether new safety regulations are
needed.
   The FDA is asking for information about heat susceptors,
metalized surfaces in the packages of food intended for microwave
cooking. These heat susceptors absorb microwave energy and become
very hot, allowing the food to become brown and crisp.
   Because the susceptors become so hot, the FDA said Tuesday it is
concerned that other parts of the package, including adhesives,
polymers, paper and components of plastic films, may migrate into
the food at high levels.
   The FDA has regulations governing the safety of packaging
materials that contain substances that could migrate into food, but
the agency said that at the time many of the rules were written
these materials were not commonly used at temperatures above 300
degrees Fahrenheit.
   Heat-susceptor packaging can raise the temperature to more than
500 degrees Fahrenheit.
   The FDA said it does not have enough data to determine whether
at these high temperatures the packaging materials are safe. It is
asking the industry and the scientific community to submit
information the agency can use to consider amending the regulations
for food packaging.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
