<FIRST>r f PM-IntegratedResources     10-11 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Integrated Resources,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buyer Seeks Lower Price for Integrated Resources Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc., a struggling
financial concern, was dealt another blow when Whitehall Financial
Group said it could not obtain financing to buy Integrated's core
financial services businesses.
   Integrated also said Tuesday that Whitehall was seeking a
``significant adjustment'' in the $310 million purchase price and
proposed to pay for the business partly with securities in the new
core group.
   The snag raises further doubts about Integrated's ability to
make payments on some $1.75 billion in debt. Integrated has not
paid any principle or interest to bondholders since June, when it
said it would have to default because of worsening troubles
stemming from its difficulty in diversifying out of real estate
into financial services businesses.
   Whitehall, a family-owned partnership, had reached a tentative
agreement in August to buy Integrated Resources Life Insurance Co.,
Integrated Resources Equity Corp., Integrated Resources Asset
Management Corp., Resources Trust Co., and Financial Clearing and
Services Corp.
   After the spinoff of subsidiaries, Integrated's main business
would be management of existing public and private limited
partnerships and real estate investment trusts.
   Integrated, once a high-flying real estate investment concern,
said it was continuing negotiations with Whitehall and ``is also
engaged in serious discussions with another party.''
   Integrated said it still wants to reach an agreement to sell the
core businesses by Sunday.
   Integrated had said it would try to sell its core financial
service companies for $450 million to $525 million, but Whitehall
was interested in only part of the holdings. The $310 million price
was put at $20 million to $30 million below the low end of the
desired price for the financial businesses.
   Integrated also said it had agreed to pay Whitehall a $4 million
breakup fee of the deal was dropped.
   Whitehall is half-owned by members of the de Gunzburg branch of
the Bronfman family of Canada, heirs to the Seagram Ltd. distilling
fortune, and half-owned by the Moross family of London, which has
extensive financial services interests. Whitehall has holdings in
life insurance and property and casualty brokerage.
   Under the deal, Whitehall would not buy Integrated's Capitol
Life Insurance Co., its tax-sheltered annuity business, its
ordinary life insurance business or United Resources.
</TEXT>
