<SECOND>AM-Lawyer Arrested,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adviser to Guinness Charged, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington lawyer who advised a British
company during its hostile takeover of a Scottish distiller has
been arrested on British charges of theft, according to The
Washington Post.
   The lawyer, Thomas J. Ward, was released and will face
extradition proceedings soon, according to the newspaper's account
in Wednesday editions.
   The newspaper said a spokesman for the Justice Department
confirmed the arrest by U.S. marshal's last week, though the U.S.
attorney's office declined to comment.
   David Dunkel, chief spokesman for the department, told The
Associated Press Tuesday night he was not informed about the case.
There was no answer at the home telephone of the colleague to whom
he referred questions.
   Ward's lawyer, David Aufhauser, was out of town, said a woman
who answered the telephone at his home.
   The British theft charge concerns a payment of $8 million Ward
received from Guinness PLC after Guinness succeeded in taking over
Distillers Co. in 1986, the newspaper said.
   Former Guinness Chairman Ernest Saunders and several other
people are expected to go to trial soon in Britain on charges
arising from their roles in alleged stock market manipulation that
enabled Guinness to succeed.
