<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   10-11 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>ALPA Votes To Continue Strike Payments to Eastern Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Air Line Pilots Association gave
striking Eastern Airlines pilots a bracing morale boost by voting
to continue special payments to the Eastern strikers.
   ALPA, which represents pilots at nearly all the nation's major
carriers, announced late Tuesday that a majority of its members
voted to maintain the strike benefits for Eastern pilots. ALPA
declined to reveal the vote tally, saying only that a simple
majority of the returned ballots was needed to continue the
payments for six months.
   The announcement gave a lift to the 2,400 or so Eastern pilots
in their eighth month of a walkout, after numerous setbacks in
their fight against Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent
Texas Air Corp. Pilot leaders had warned that if ALPA abandoned the
Eastern pilots, the national union's bargaining position with all
the carriers would have been weakened.
   When the strike against Miami-based Eastern began March 4, there
were about 3,600 pilots at the airline. Their ranks have thinned
since as financial pressures have forced scores back across the
picket lines and others have retired or found jobs at other
carriers.
   Ron Cole, a spokesman for the striking pilots, said the ALPA
vote will bolster people still on the picket lines.
   ``It wasn't unexpected, because professional pilots understand
that the outcome of the Eastern strike will have a direct bearing
on their own futures,'' he said. ``I think it gives them a show of
support from their fellow pilots and will help continue their
strong resolve.''
   The 40,000 or so ALPA members were asked to vote last month on
whether they wished to keep paying about 3 percent of their salary
to their colleagues at Eastern, which is trying to emerge from
bankruptcy protection as a smaller carrier. ALPA declined to say
how many pilots voted.
   The benefits to Eastern pilots averaged about $2,400 a month per
flier since the walkout began.
   The pilots were a crucial element of support in the strike that
started with Eastern's Machinists union, which also was joined by
the airline's flight attendants.
   ``It's a tremendous morale boost,'' Eastern Machinists leader
Charles Bryan said in a telephone interview from Miami. ``It will
certainly give our people a boost to know that ALPA supports their
strike that strongly.''
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the airline had no
comment on the matter.
   Later this week the Senate could vote on a bill, supported by
the Eastern unions, to set up a blue-ribbon commission that would
investigate the Eastern dispute. In a vote last week, the Senate
decided to cut off debate on the bill.
   But the White House and the Transportation Department have
lobbied heavily against the bill, and President Bush is likely to
veto it. In that case, if Congress couldn't muster the votes to
override his veto, the pilots could suffer a blow to morale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-P&amp;G Bjt   10-11 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-P&amp;G, Bjt,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>P&amp;G Chairman To Step Down, Sparking Top-Level Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co., one of the nation's
largest consumer products companies, will head into the 1990s
looking to increase its overseas sales under a new top executive.
   The Cincinnati-based company will get a new chairman and chief
executive officer Jan. 2 when Edwin L. Artzt takes over for John G.
Smale, the company's leader for the last nine years.
   Smale, 62, surprised shareholders at their annual meeting
Tuesday by announcing he will stepping down to spend more time with
his family. That set in motion of series of top-level shifts that
will leave Artzt head of the diversified company, which had more
than $21 billion in worldwide sales last year.
   Artzt, 59, has been vice chairman of the board and president of
Procter &amp; Gamble International since 1984. His first major
promotion came in 1969, when he was named vice president of the
food products division.
   In another move, company President John E. Pepper will give up
most of his responsibilities for P&amp;G's domestic operations to
oversee the international business.
   During his tenure, Smale helped the company branch out into
foreign markets. Roughly 39 percent of its sales in the last fiscal
year came from outside the United States, and Smale said the figure
should top 50 percent in a few years.
   ``Procter &amp; Gamble is well along the way towards changing from
being a United States-based business that sells some of its
products in international markets to being a truly world company,''
Smale said.
   Smale also led the company into new product lines and oversaw an
$805 million reorganization two years ago aimed at streamlining
management. Under his leadership, the company acquired
Richardson-Vicks, the Noxell Corp. and some major brands from G.D.
Searle. Those moves gave the company a wide base in
over-the-counter drugs and beauty products.
   P&amp;G had sales of $21.4 billion in the fiscal year ended June 30,
earnings of $1.6 billion and dividends of $3 per common share _ all
company records.
   Smale cited personal reasons for deciding to give up his
executive position Jan. 2. He said he will remain an employee and
will serve as a director and as chairman of the board's executive
committee.
   ``By January, I will have been president and then chairman of
Procter &amp; Gamble for nearly 16 years,'' he said. ``I will have been
the chief executive officer of the company for nine years. I've
reached the conclusion that for me as well as for my family it's
time to turn this responsibility over to someone else.''
   In other personnel moves, P&amp;G announced that:
   _B. Jurgen Hintz, a group vice president, was elected an
executive vice president. He will be responsible for the company's
domestic paper products, cellulose and chemicals, and food and
beverage businesses.
   _Durk I. Jager, a group vice president, was chosen an executive
vice president. He will be responsible for domestic soap, detergent
and health and beauty care businesses.
   _Gerald V. Dirvin, senior vice president, becomes an executive
vice president. He will continue to oversee most of P&amp;G's staff
functions, such as sales, advertising, marketing services and
public affairs.
   Smale announced the sweeping changes at a shareholders meeting
punctuated by an animal-rights demonstration. Several dozen
activists picketed outside the company's headquarters while others
questioned Smale during the meeting about P&amp;G's continued use of
animals for product-safety testing.
   Smale repeated the company's position that marketing certain
products without animal testing would be unsafe.
   ``Animal tests are used only when no other acceptable methods
are available,'' he said.
   Animal-rights activists, who have targeted P&amp;G in recent years,
have failed to gain approval at recent shareholder meetings for
proposals to stop the use of animals in product testing.
   Smale declined to say how many animals are being used for such
purposes. He did say the company reduced the number of animals it
uses by one-third in the past five years and will continue to look
for alternatives.
   In other matters, shareholders approved a 2-for-1 stock split
effective Oct. 20, and increased the authorized number of common
shares from 500 million to 1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
