<DOCNO> AP891011-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Soviet-Greenspan     10-11 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Greenspan,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Chairman Says Soviets Pragmatic, Not in Panic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board, says Soviet economists appear largely unfettered by
ideology as they search for ways out of the country's financial
woes.
   In a meeting Tuesday that would have been unthinkable just a few
years ago, Greenspan held discussions with nine of the top economic
minds of a system that has been at the opposite end of the
philosophical spectrum for decades.
   He told a news conference the Soviets are ``willing to reach
beyond the usual confines of what economic policy-makers are
willing to do.''
   ``They are broadening their view to see whether there are
applicable views outside their immediate circle,'' Greenspan said.
   ``Did we get into an ideological debate over values? No,'' he
said.
   Greenspan said he was not able to offer specific suggestions to
many Soviet economic problems because of his lack of detailed
knowledge of its system. But he did discuss such issues as reform
and convertibility of the Soviet ruble.
   The decades of ideological differences resulted in an initial
sense of akwardness. ``If I didn't feel odd, I must say, I would be
peculiar,'' Greenspan said. But the Soviets' non-ideological
approach dissipated the sense of uncertainty, he said.
   Greenspan, who was chairman of the President's Council of
Economic Advisers under President Gerald Ford and also headed a
commission on social security reform, met with Finance Minister
Valentin Pavlov, Deputy Premier Leonid Abalkin, and other top
officials and economic theorists.
   Those officials are trying to right an economy struggling with a
huge budget deficit, bare store shelves, increasing consumer fears
of even worse conditions, strikes, and a near-worthless currency.
   Despite their troubles, Greenspan said there is no sense of
crisis among the Soviet economists.
   In their meetings, Greenspan said the Soviets sought information
on the Western approach to solving individual economic problems.
But they will not try to superimpose capitalism on their own
system, he said.
   The nited States can help by providing economic expertise on
particular issues, but discussion of U.S. economic aid, as some
Soviet officials have suggested, was not on the agenda, he said.
   ``What they have basically is an understanding that they have to
restructure and that the issue of success is theirs,'' Greenspan
said.
   Greenspan also turned his attention to exchange rates in the
world market in a speech for delivery later to U.S. and Soviet
officials at the U.S. ambassador's residence in Moscow.
   In an advanced text released in Washington, Greenspan said that
``attempts to maintain unrealistic exchange rates may lead to
destabilizing international capital flows, and ultimately have to
be abandoned.''
   He said that paying inordinate attention to intermediate targets
in setting monetary policy ``may not promote the attainment of
long-term goals.''
   Greenspan made his remarks as the Federal Reserve Board finds
itself under pressure from the Bush administration to take action
to bring the dollar down from its steep rise against foreign
currencies this year.
   The fed also is being urged by some administration officials to
ease its grip on credit to steer the economy clear of recession.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
