<DOCNO> AP891011-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CFCs-Industry     10-11 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CFCs-Industry,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Companies Form CFC Clearinghouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine major companies say they are forming a
clearinghouse to promote cooperation among themselves and others in
ending use of chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, as cleaning agents.
   Some of the companies who made the announcement Tuesday had made
clear previously their intention of seeking substitutes for CFCs.
   CFCs are used widely as refrigeration fluids in air conditioners
and refrigerators as well in as cleaning solvents for metals and
electronic components. They escape into the atmosphere where they
damage the high-altitude ozone shield that protects the earth from
the sun's ultraviolet radiation,.
   The United States and 44 other countries have agreed to phase
out the production of CFCs with hopes of eliminating them
altogether by the turn of the century.
   The companies participating in the announcement Tuesday were
AT&amp;T, Boeing, Digital Equipment, Ford Motor, General Electric,
Honeywell, Motorola, Northern Telecom and Texas Instruments.
   The organization, called the Industry Cooperative for Ozone
Layer Protection, will act as a clearinghouse for information on
new substitute solvents, encourage the prompt adoption of safe
substitutes, and work with producers and the government to
distribute information about substitutes to developing countries.
</TEXT>
