<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-EuropeanCommunity     10-11 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-European Community,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Complains About European Limits on Imported TV Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will file a fair-trade
complaint against the European Community over a non-binding quota
system designed to limit imported TV programs to no more than half
of all shows aired, says U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills.
   Hills, who previously said the United States would fight any
local content rules the European Community implements for
television as part of its plan to remove trade barriers between its
member nations by 1992, said Tuesday she was ``deeply disturbed''
by the Oct. 3 decision on TV.
   Although the Television Without Frontiers directive was not
binding on member nations, Hills said it was ``blatantly
protectionist and unjustifiable, and discriminates against U.S. and
other non-EC film goods.''
   In Brussels, Belgium, House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt,
D-Mo., and other members of Congress held what Gephardt called a
``spirited exchange'' with European Community officials about the
new TV measure.
   ``We feel very strongly about this issue,'' said Gephardt.
``It's especially troubling for Americans to see a product that we
do have some skill in ... and some advantage to be closed down to
any extent.''
   Hills said she ``will take immediate action to address that
decision'' under the 96-nation free-trade accord known as the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   ``The United States government believes that the local content
requirement in the broadcast directive is inconsistent with the
community's obligation not to discriminate against foreign products
_ to give equal treatment _ under the GATT. I am initiating prompt
action in that forum,'' Hills said in a prepared statement.
   GATT has no police power over its member nations, but Hills'
action indicates the Bush administration is having second thoughts
about the European Community's 1992 program.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher last week told a House
foreign affairs subcommittee that the United States may have to
reassess its position if the European Community continues towards
local content rules in areas such as television, computer chips,
telecommunications equipment and automobiles.
   According to industry figures, the United States realizes a $3
billion annual surplus balance of trade through film and TV
exports, and Europe is the leading market for such programs with
about $700 million in purchases yearly.
   TV series such as ``Miami Vice'' and ``Dallas'' are enormously
popular in Europe, which has caused legislators there to decry the
``Americanization'' of their populaces.
   Officials estimate that out of 125,000 hours of TV shown in
Western Europe annually, only 20,000 hours are produced in Europe.
Japan, Australia and the United States provide the remainder.
   France had urged mandatory quotas be placed on TV programming,
but the EC declined to do so.
   Hills said the cultural argument was a smokescreen for economic
protectionism.
   ``We do not understand why the Spanish culture is more protected
by a film produced in Germany by `Europeans' than by a Spanish film
of Mexican origin, or why the English culture is promoted more by a
film produced in France by `Europeans' than by a film of New
Zealand origin. ... The definition of `European works' is economic,
not cultural,'' she said.
   She added that U.S. concerns were further heightened by press
reports that the EC is pledging hundreds of millions of additional
dollars in subsidies to European producers and writers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
