<FIRST>r f PM-Trump-AMR     10-11 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trump-AMR,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Pledges to Keep AMR in Dallas If He Wins Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If he succeeds with his bold $7 billion buyout
bid for AMR Corp., developer Donald Trump pledges to keep the
parent of American Airlines at its headquarters in Fort Worth,
Texas.
   ``I have absolutely no intention of moving American from the
Dallas-Fort Worth area,'' Trump said Tuesday in a telephone
interview from his New York office.
   Trump, who said he knows and likes the Dallas-Fort Worth area,
appeared to make the statement to reassure AMR employees. The head
of American's second-largest union, the 16,000-member Association
of Professional Flight Attendants, recently met with advisers to
discuss possible ways to help management fend off Trump's bid.
   AMR has had little to say about Trump's offer beyond its initial
response that the bid would be considered ``in due course,''
although the company said it preferred to remain independent.
   Trump's $120-a-share cash offer for the nation's largest and
most profitable airline has been met with suspicion by many in the
financial community, who see it as a ploy to drive up the price of
AMR stock and enhance Trump's own holdings.
   AMR tumbled $3.375 a share to $101.375 Tuesday in active trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, apparently reflecting investor
skepticism about Trump's offer.
   A major institutional investor said Tuesday it had joined the
list of Trump doubters.
   Since Thursday, when Trump's offer was made public, Windsor Fund
sold its 425,000 shares to take advantage of the increase stock
price, said John B. Neff, who has managed the fund for 25 years.
   ``I have a hard time taking Mr. Trump seriously. $120's a very
full price, and I don't know where the financing is going to come
from,'' Neff said. ``This isn't loose change.''
   But the real estate tycoon insists his intentions are real.
``I'm very serious about it,'' he said. ``I think this is a company
with great potential and I look forward to getting it.''
   Trump declined to provide details of his financing plan,
although he said it involves ``relatively little leverage'' and no
foreign investors _ two major areas of concern raised by the
Department of Transportation regarding the current wave of airline
buyouts.
   Trump told AMR last week that he would put up $1 billion of
equity in the deal and believes financing is readily available for
the remainder.
   The developer has a reputation as a good customer who has paid
off debts and has warm relations with bankers. His blue-chip real
estate and casino properties could be readily borrowed against,
while AMR's assets also could be considered as collateral,
observers say.
</TEXT>
