<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-11 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher, Stocks Plunge in Tokyo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the yen today
despite the Bank of Japan's discount rate increase and massive
dollar selling, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index plunged.
   The dollar closed at 143.90 yen, up 1.67 yen from Monday's close
of 142.23 yen. It opened at 144.90 yen and moved between 142.55 yen
and 144.95 yen.
   Currency and stock markets were closed Tuesday for a Japanese
holiday.
   The dollar's high opening followed overseas rallies overnight,
but it edged down in early trading amid rumors of an increase in
the discount rate, the charge for funds borrowed by banks from the
central bank.
   After the morning session, the bank raised the rate by 0.5
percentage point to 3.75 percent. Higher interest rates tend to
make a country's currency more attractive to investors, pushing up
its value.
   ``The decision came in consideration of recent currency market
fluctuations, movements in foreign interest rates, domestic
economic trends, consumer prices and the money supply,'' Bank of
Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita told a news conference.
   The dollar had climbed to a closing of 145 yen on Sept. 22
before monetary officials of seven major industrialized nations
decided on efforts to check its rise. It dropped to 139.30 yen on
Oct. 2, but has been moving generally upward since.
   ``The Bank of Japan hopes the rate hike will contribute to
sustainable growth led by domestic demand while maintaining
consumer price stability,'' Sumita said, adding that the move was
intended to stem inflation.
   Although West Germany also had raised its official discount rate
last week, Sumita said Japan's decision was reached independently.
   Toru Kanai, foreign currency analyst with New Japan Securities
Co. Ltd., said, the discount rate increase ``came out of the blue,
and many of us had expected the U.S. discount rate cut to come
first.''
   Daiwa Securities dealer Kazuyuki Suzuki added: ``I never dreamed
that the Bank of Japan would take such a step prior to reports of
important economic indicators such as the U.S. wholesale price
index, due out Friday.''
   Yoshitsugu Hanada, a senior trader with Mitsui Bank, said the
central bank also sold large amounts of dollars in the afternoon in
an attempt to push the dollar down, but the U.S. currency still
showed strength.
   ``Speculative investors were still inclined to buy the dollar
because that's one of their few decent choices of investment,
considering the uptrend in domestic interest rates, narrowing the
gap with those overseas,'' Hanada said.
   The Nikkei Stock Exchange lost 136.28 points, or 0.39 percent,
closing at 35,240.07. It had gained 167 points Monday.
   The index plunged about 360 points after the discount rate
increase was announced, but recovered as some investors took
advantage of lower prices to buy various issues, Suzuki said.
   ``But the latest discount rate hike will certainly damage the
stock market, which no longer will grow as fast as it used to,'' he
added.
   Stock trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated
at 750 million shares, up from Monday's 700 million.
   It was the second discount rate increase this year. On May 30,
it was raised 0.75 percentage points, to 3.25 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
