<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today,
despite a half-point increase in the Japanese discount rate and
massive dollar-selling in earlier Asian trading. Gold prices fell.
   ``Half a point was too little. The market had expected a full
point, so we will probably go a bit firmer,'' said one dealer at a
private bank in Frankfurt.
   The Bank of Japan and the U.S. Federal Reserve were both
reported to have sold dollars in East Asian markets.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 143.90 yen, up 1.67 yen from Monday.
The Tokyo market was closed Tuesday for a national holiday. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 144.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9138 West German marks, up from 1.8965; 1.6720
Swiss francs, up from 1.6545; 6.4800 French francs, up from 6.4300;
2.1525 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1290; 1,401.38 Italian lire, up
from 1,382.40; and 1.1765 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1735.
   In London, the British pound steadied. It was quoted at $1.5523
at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's $1.5580.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $361 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $362. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $360.20, down from $362 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 72 cents to close at a bid
$362.36.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.06 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Tuesday.
