<FIRST>r f PM-TelerateOffer     10-11 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Telerate Offer,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telerate Panel Rejects Dow Jones Offer for Remaining 33 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. says it intends to proceed
with its $576 million tender offer for the 33 percent of Telerate
Inc. that it does not already own even though Telerate's directors
found the offer inadeqaute.
   ``We are proceeding with our $18 per share offer and continue to
believe that the offer is fair to all Telerate stockholders,'' Dow
Jones Chairman Warren H. Phillips said Tuesday.
   Wall Streeters evidently expect that Dow Jones will have to
sweeten its bid, however. Telerate rose 12{ cents a share to close
at $20.37{ on Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Telerate, a provider of computerized financial information, said
a special panel of its directors urged shareholders not to tender
their stock under terms of the Dow Jones offer and urged Dow Jones
to arrange a meeting ``in order to achieve a mutually agreed upon
transaction.''
   Dow Jones, publisher of the Wall Street Journal, said it was
disappointed by the panel's assessment of its offer but indicated
it has no plans to raise it or negotiate with the committee.
   Peter Skinner, Dow Jones' vice president, corporate counsel and
secretary, said Dow Jones ``has no plans to meet with the Telerate
special committee'' and no plans to raise its bid.
   Dow Jones, which also publishes Barron's magazine, community
newspapers and electronic business information, became involved
with Telerate in 1985 when it purchased a 32 percent stake in the
company. It subsequently increased its stake to 67 percent.
   On Sept. 21, Dow Jones said it planned to offer $18 a share for
the remaining Telerate shares, and began the tender offer five days
later. The offer and withdrawal rights are scheduled to expire Nov.
3.
   Skinner said Dow Jones' investment bankers have since met with
those of the Telerate special committee to describe how it came to
the pricing of its offer, although not to negotiate any terms.
   In its announcement Tuesday, Telerate said that the special
panel, with concurrence of other Telerate directors who are not
employed by or consultants to Dow Jones, found the $18 a share
offer ``inadequate and not in the best interests of its
stockholders.''
   Telerate's founder and chief executive, Neil S. Hirsch, said he
will not tender any of his shares, which represent about 6 percent
of the company's stock, and that no other director or executive of
Telerate would tender under the current offer.
   Hirsch said the special committee had ``received clear
indications'' from stockholders owning another 5 percent of
Telerate's stock of their ``genuine dissatisfaction with the price
Dow Jones is offering.''
   On Monday, Telerate reported its third-quarter earnings dropped
17.4 percent compared with a year earlier and said it is in
negotiations to buy the 50 percent stake that its partner American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. owns in the joint venture Global
Transactions Services Co.
   Telerate and AT&amp;T began the venture in 1987 to develop an
electronic service for foreign-exchange transactions. The service
was recently launched.
</TEXT>
