<DOCNO> AP891011-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 0902EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoHallofFame     10-11 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Hall of Fame,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Industry in `Thermonuclear Warfare' Exec Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life for Chrysler Corp. executive Bennett Bidwell
would have been a lot easier if Soichiro Honda hadn't done what he
had done.
   Bidwell, speaking Tuesday night at the annual Automotive Hall of
Fame dinner, said competition among automakers in the 1990s will be
tougher than ever and part of that is because of Honda.
   The 82-year-old founder of Honda Motor Co. Ltd. was among four
people inducted into the Automotive Hall of Fame. He is the first
Japanese national honored by the group that began in 1939 as the
Automobile Old Timers.
   Honda was a man ``without whom my life would have been a lot
easier,'' said Bidwell, chairman of Chrysler's manufacturing arm,
Chrysler Motors Corp.
   There has been speculation that if Honda's U.S. sales keep
growing and if Chrysler's keep falling, the Japanese company could
become the third-largest selling auto company in the United States.
   Earlier in the day, Honda brushed aside such speculation,
saying, ``If we make progress, so will Chrysler. So I don't think
the difference between the two companies will become that much
smaller.''
   But competition is high on the mind of Bidwell and other auto
executives.
   ``There is conventional, nuclear, and thermonuclear warfare,''
he said. ``We are at stage three.
   ``I said for five years it is a jungle out there. It isn't
anymore. It's worse.''
   He said that for a time Chrysler had pretty much locked up the
market on three segments _ minivans, four-door sport-utility
vehicles and convertibles.
   ``Now they (the market segments) look like Grand Central
Station,'' Bidwell said. ``There is a fight to the finish and in a
fight to the finish ... the low-cost producer wins, the high-cost
producer loses.''
   Bidwell made only a passing remark about the company's effort to
slash $1 billion out of its $26 billion budget by the end of next
year. Included in that are the elimination of about 8 percent of
the salaried work force, or about 2,300 jobs.
   ``We will take suggestions (about cost cutting) about anything
from anywhere,'' he said.
   Honda's motorcycle company began making cars in 1963. It became
the first Japanese company to set up a manufacturing plant in the
United States and later this year will open its second. Both, along
with an engine factory and a research facility, are located in Ohio.
   ``Our company in Ohio has been so well accepted ...'' he said,
``that I truly believe it is an American company.''
   Inducted with Honda were:
   _Gordon Buehrig, the chief engineer of the Dusenberg, Cord and
Auburn Speedster automobiles.
   _Frank Kent, a Cadillac dealer in Fort Worth, Texas.
   _Elmer Wavering, who installed the first radio in a car and went
on to develop the first commercially successful car radio in 1930.
He later became associated with Motorola Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
