<FIRST>u f PM-NuggetsSale 1stLd-Writethru f0044 10-11 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuggets Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0044,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Investors' Plan to Buy Denver Nuggets Falls Through</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf pvs, `Bynoe and ...' to UPDATE
with denial from one investor, other investor not available. A longer version
moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the Denver Nuggets says he has called
off the $65 million sale of the basketball franchise to two
businessmen who stood to become the first black owners of a major
U.S. professional sports team.
   Sidney Shlenker said in a statement Tuesday that he was allowing
the contract for the sale of the NBA team to Peter Bynoe, 38, and
Bertram Lee, 50, both of Chicago, to expire. The two had planned to
buy the club in a deal announced in July.
   Bynoe and Lee had missed at least two deadlines for completing
the deal since it was announced, and there had been several signs
in recent weeks that the deal was shaky.
   However, Lee, reached at home in Chicago today, said, ``No,
that's not true,'' when asked about the deal falling through. He
referred further questions to a public relations firm, which did
not immediately return calls. Bynoe also did not return calls.
   Shlenker had earlier set a deadline of 5 p.m. Tuesday for Bynoe
and Lee to complete the deal, but team officials said work was
continuing after the deadline. About four hours later, the team
said Shlenker had backed out.
   Bynoe and Lee apparently had the financing in place but the
documentation was incomplete, said Dave Checketts, who was to take
over as president under the new ownership.
   ``It's just a matter of going through all the documents,'' Bynoe
said on Monday. ``I am optimistic we will be able to do what needs
to be done, but I can't speak for Sidney.''
</TEXT>
