<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UnitedTelecom-Sprint     10-11 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-United Telecom-Sprint,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Telecom Announces Consolidation With US Sprint Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Telecommunications said today it
will consolidate operations with its US Sprint long-distance
company to make the corporation more efficient as Sprint continues
rapid growth.
   ``These organizational changes will allow United Telecom and US
Sprint to operate largely as a single company,'' said William T.
Esrey, president and chief executive officer of both United Telecom
and Sprint.
   It also will make the company better at setting strategy and
increase profits by cutting down on duplications, he said.
   United Telecom now owns 80.1 percent of Sprint, the nation's
third-largest long-distance company. GTE Corp. of Stamford, Conn.,
owns 19.9 percent.
   Sprint was started in July 1986 as a joint venture between
United Telecom and GTE. United Telecom bought controlling interest
in January, and spokesman Don Forsythe said the company has an
agreement to buy GTE's remaining shares at some point in the future.
   Sprint, which lost more than $1 billion for its parent companies
from mid-1986 to the end of 1988, began showing its first-ever
quarterly profits in March thanks to strong sales growth on its
fiber-optic long-distance system.
   On Tuesday, United Telecom reported its profits jumped 75
percent in the third quarter because of Sprint's second straight
quarter of billion-dollar sales. The company projected further
growth as Sprint begins work on a contract to provide 40 percent of
a new communications system for the federal government.
   Under the realignment of the two companies, Esrey, 49, will
remain in his United Telecom post but switch to chairman and CEO of
Sprint.
   Ronald T. LeMay, 43, will become president and chief operating
officer of Sprint and president of United Telecom's long-distance
division. LeMay previously served as executive vice president of
corporate affairs for United Telecom.
   The companies' legal, financial and data systems operations will
be consolidated, and the company will form a US Sprint
International Systems and Services Group in Reston, Va.
   Both companies have their headquarters in the Kansas City area.
   In addition to Sprint, United Telecom also owns local telephone
companies in the South and Midwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
