<HEAD>Most Crop Futures Rise Technical Recovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, bouncing back
from recent steep losses on buying inspired by technical factors
and new export business.
   Soybean futures displayed the greatest strength in early trading
after falling to 23-month lows Tuesday under heavy harvest-related
selling.
   ``The markets have really gotten battered around lately and were
oversold,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst at Research Department
Inc. in Chicago.
   Some of the recent losses were linked to expectations that the
Agriculture Department will increase its 1989 corn and soybean
harvest estimates in a crop report due out after the close of
trading on Thursday.
   But Conrad Leslie, an influential private crop analyst based in
Chicago, released pre-report estimates late Tuesday that fell below
general market expectations, prompting some buying this morningg.
   Additional support today stemmed from USDA confirmation late
Tuesday that the Soviet Union purchased 150,000 metric tons of U.S.
soybean meal.
   In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent lower to 1\ cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06} a
bushel; corn futures were { cent to 1{ cents higher with December
at $2.34} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with
December at $1.41{ a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 6 cents
higher with November at $5.56\ a bushel.
   Livestock futures were narrowly mixed while pork bellies were
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent lower to .05 cent higher with October
at 72.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .13
cent higher with October at 82.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .10
cent lower to .28 cent higher with October at 47.55 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .95 cent higher with February
at 46.97 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures advanced on Tuesday while pork futures were mixed.
