<FIRST>r f BC-May-Caldor     10-11 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-May-Caldor,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>May Department Stores Sells Caldor For $500 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. said Wednesday that
it has reached an agreement to sell its Caldor discount stores for
$500 million to CAL Holdings, Inc.
   CAL Holdings is a new company formed by Odyssey Partners, L.P.,
Caldor management led by Don R. Clarke, chairman and chief
executive officer, and Marc I. Balmuth, president, and Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Capital Corp.
   May, one of the nation's leading department store companies, has
been trying to sell Caldor and its other chain of discount stores,
Venture, for several months.
   CAL Holdings will pay $500 million in cash and assume $52
million in debt and lease obligations to get Caldor, a chain of
more than 100 stores located primarily in the Northeast. May also
will acquire a 20 percent equity interest in CAL Holdings.
   Linda Kristiansen, a stock analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds in
New York, said she was not happy with the deal because she thought
the Caldor chain was probably worth more.
   The deal is expected to be completed early next month.
   May, headquartered in St. Louis, owns 14 department store chains
in 29 states and the District of Columbia, 75 Venture stores in the
Midwest, 2,663 Payless shoe stores.
