<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CopterCrash 2ndLd-Writethru   10-11 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Copter Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Trump Gaming Execs Among Five Killed in Copter Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with denial that Trump had planned
to be aboard. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `State Police ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LACEY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter apparently lost its
main rotor and crashed onto a highway median, killing all five
people aboard, including three executives of Donald Trump's casino
empire.
   ``There was a loud bang, like a piston rod going,'' said Tom
Murray, 38, of East Providence, R.I., who was camping near the site
of Tuesday afternoon's crash, a wooded thicket between lanes of the
Garden State Parkway.
   ``It fell below the tree-line and I didn't see it crash,'' he
said. ``It went straight down. ... It seemed like an eternity
watching it.''
   No one on the ground was hurt.
   A Trump executive today disputed a report in the New York Daily
News that the billionarie developer had been scheduled to take the
one-hour flight to Atlantic but canceled at the last moment because
he got too busy.
   ``Trump had definitely never planned to be on it,'' said Bernie
Dillon, the vice president of Trump Sports and Entertainment.
   State Police Sgt. Anthony Aceto said the main rotor was found a
quarter-mile from the crash site about 30 miles north of Atlantic
City, where the helicopter was returning the executives from New
York City.
   The National Transportation Safety Board investigators were
looking into a rotor malfunction, said Frank Ghiorsi, the agency's
regional director.
   ``If the main rotor separated from the rest of the aircraft, it
was out of control,'' Ghiorsi said.
   He said investigators were looking for the tail rotor to help
them re-create the problem. Investigators said the loss of one of
the two rotors could have caused the other to fall off.
   Trump spokesman Dan Klores identified the executives as Stephen
Hyde, 43, chief executive officer of Trump's Atlantic City casino
operations; Mark G. Etess, 38, president of the Taj Mahal casino
project; and, Jonathan Benanav, 33, senior vice president of Trump
Plaza casino hotel.
   ``They were three fabulous young men in the prime of their
lives,'' billionaire developer Donald Trump said in a statement
from his New York office. ``No better human beings ever existed.
We're deeply saddened by this devastating tragedy. Our hearts go
out to their families.''
   The others killed were pilot Robert Kent of Ronkonkoma, N.Y.,
and co-pilot Lawrence Diener of Westbury, N.Y., State Police said.
   The helicopter, a 1982 Agusta 109A, was leased from Paramount
Aviation of Lincoln Park, and had taken off from Manhattan for
Atlantic City, officials said. Officials at Paramount Aviation said
they could not answer questions about the crash.
   Traffic was delayed because of the crash, but the road remained
open.
   Joe Librizzi, manager of a parkway maintenance crew, said he was
one of the first to reach the wreckage.
   ``I walked in and turned right around,'' he said. ``I walked in
there and all I saw was one body thrown out of the helicopter. ...
I saw another slumped over.''
   Investigators were trying to determine if the pilot was in radio
contact with air traffic controllers before the crash, said Alan
Yurman, an NTSB air safety director.
   Helicopters are not equipped with flight data and cockpit voice
recorders _ the ``black boxes'' aboard commercial airliners.
   The Trump executives had been in New York City for a news
conference promoting the Feb. 3 World Boxing Organization bout at
the Trump Plaza Hotel and Casino between junior welterweights
Hector Camacho and Vinny Pazienza.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891011-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Pauley-Today 2ndLd-Writethru f0055 10-11 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pauley-Today, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0055,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jane Pauley Says She'll Likely Leave `Today' Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with no comment from network and
Pauley; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `It's a ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC ``Today'' show co-anchor Jane Pauley says
she probably will leave the program by the end of the year but will
stay with the network ``in some fashion or other,'' The Washington
Post reported today.
   Neither she nor the network would comment on the report.
   NBC News spokeswoman Peggy Hubble said a statement on Pauley's
future probably would be made later in the day. Ms. Pauley, who has
two years left on her NBC News contract, didn't return calls and
was reported by her office out taping an interview.
   ``I am definitely staying at NBC,'' the Post quoted Ms. Pauley
as saying in a telephone interview from New York.
   Ms. Pauley has been co-anchor of ``Today'' for 13 years, but her
future with the program has been the subject of speculation in the
weeks since Deborah Norville took over as newscaster on the program.
   ``Thirteen years ago today Jane Pauley began on `Today,'''
co-anchor Bryant Gumbel said at the opening of this morning's
broadcast. ``That's a long time. Is that a lifetime?''
   ``It's a long time. It's my whole adult life, virtually,'' Ms.
Pauley responded. ``Thank you.''
   At the end of the broadcast, the words ``Happy Anniversary''
flashed on the screen.
   Ms. Pauley told the newspaper there has been no hostility among
members of the ``Today'' cast, although she did say the place has
been more tense since Ms. Norville swapped duties with John Palmer,
who has been sent to ``NBC News at Sunrise.''
   ``When it was first revealed to me that John and Deborah were
going to switch, that was a real blow,'' Ms. Pauley was quoted as
saying. ``I like him very much, and I thought, `Why John? What did
he do to anybody?' But as soon as you say anything, it sounds like
a jealous older woman talking about a younger one.''
   Ms. Norville is 31; Ms. Pauley will be 39 at the end of this
month.
   Ms. Pauley told her interviewer that if she does leave
``Today,'' she would ``still like to come back to the show now and
then in the future, the way Barbara Walters does at `Good Morning
America.' It would be very unlike me to leave on bad terms.
   ``As it stands now, I am staying (with NBC) in some fashion or
other.''
   Ms. Pauley's agent has been negotiating with NBC since August,
when Ms. Norville was promoted. NBC executives, who thought she was
after more money, were startled when she submitted her resignation,
according to unidentified sources cited by the Post.
   ``Deborah and I are on great terms. It's not Deborah's fault she
is very talented and very beautiful and younger than I,'' Ms.
Pauley said. ``And my relationship with (Gumbel) is as good as it's
ever been.''
   Reports of bickering among the show's cast members have
circulated since March, when a memo written by Gumbel was leaked.
In the memo, he criticized his colleagues, especially weatherman
Willard Scott. Ms. Pauley was not mentioned.
   ``We remain very, very good friends,'' Ms. Pauley said,
referring to Gumbel.
</TEXT>
