<FIRST>r f PM-RamadaRestructuring     10-11 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ramada Restructuring,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ramada Restructuring on Hold, Company Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc.'s restructuring, including the sale
of its hotels to a Hong Kong company, has been placed on hold, the
company said today.
   Ramada cited ``unfavorable conditions in the high-yield credit
market'' as the reason for its decision not to proceed with an
offering of $400 million in debt securities, which is a
prerequisite for the restructuring.
   The Phoenix-based company announced earlier this year that it
would sell its worldwide hotel business to New World Hotel Holdings
Ltd. of Hong Kong and form a new company, Aztar Corp., to operate
its Nevada and New Jersey casinos.
   Arranging financing for Aztar is a condition of completing the
sale, Ramada said.
   The company originally announced that it would offer $170
million in first-mortgage notes and $230 million in bonds and, on
Oct. 3, said it was considering issuing warrants for 10 percent of
Aztar's common stock.
   ``Ramada management intends to develop a revised restructuring
proposal that will involve a modification to the consideration to
be received by Ramada shareholders,'' the company said in a
statement.
   Shareholders were to have received cash and stock in Aztar under
the original plan.
   Any new plan would require amendment of provisions in the
agreement with New World and an extension of the Nov. 30 deadline
for completing the sale, the company said.
   It also would require approval of shareholders and gaming
regulators in Nevada and New Jersey.
   Ramada said it ``can offer no assurance that a restructuring
will be completed and it cannot specifiy the timing of the next
steps.''
</TEXT>
