<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Banks     10-11 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Banks,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chase Posts $1.12 Billion Loss As Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Corp. reported Wednesday that it lost $1.12
billion in the third quarter, in line with projections made a month
ago when it decided to substantially boost its loan-loss reserves
to cover problem Third World debt.
   The loss for the three months ended Sept. 30 amounted to $12.45
a share, compared with a profit of $283 million, or $3.09 a share,
recorded the same period a year ago.
   Excluding the higher reserves, as well as other special
provisions taken in the third quarter, Chase said it would have
earned $151 million, or $1.45 a share. It said its 1988 third
quarter earnings, would have totaled $130 million, or $1.32 a
share, minus special gains from income tax benefits and its pension
plan.
   Chase said this year's third quarter included increases in net
interest income, consumer and investment banking fees and trading
account income. Income from foreign exchange trading declined from
the year-earlier quarter.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Chase's net loss totaled $840
million, or $10.01 per share, compared with net income of $784
million, or $8.62 per share a year earlier. Excluding the impact of
the special provisions, Chase would have netted $420 million, or
$4.04 a share.
   Chase, the nation's second-largest banking company after
Citicorp, with assets of around $106 billion, had said it expected
to lose $1.12 billion in the third quarter of this year when it
announced a major recapitalization plan on Sept. 20.
   The plan, which resulted in a total after-tax charge of $1.26
billion, included the addition of $1.15 billion to its loan-loss
reserves for Third World debt, an $85 million charge reflecting the
lower value of problem real estate assets in Chase's Arizona
banking subsidiary and a $25 million charge relating to securities
trading activities.
   Chase had also said it would issue $500 million in new common
stock.
   Two other major New York banks, J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. and
Manufacturers Hanover Corp., also sharply boosted their loan-loss
reserves last month. The moves reflected a growing realization
among bankers that the money lent to Third World countries in the
1970s to spur economic growth may never be fully repaid.
   Manufacturers Hanover added $950 million to its reserves in the
third quarter for a projected $775 million loss, while Morgan
raised reserves by $2 billion and said it expected a $1.8 billion
quarterly loss.
   Chase said its reserve for possible credit losses from Third
World countries totaled $2.9 billion the end of the third quarter,
or roughly 46 percent of Chase's total $6.2 billion of medium- and
long-term loans to Third World countries.
   The ratio was 24 percent at the end of the 1988 third quarter,
when reserves were $1.9 billion.
</TEXT>
