<DOCNO> AP891011-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1525EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     10-11 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0350</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices showed a broad loss today,
continuing the pullback that began in Tuesday's session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 6.08 on Tuesday,
dropped 20.78 points to 2,764.55 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 2 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 391 up,
1,078 down and 473 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders increasingly yielded to the temptation to
cash in their gains after the market's rise to record highs last
week and Monday.
   The tendency to lighten up was apparently heightened by a
dimming of hopes for any moves soon by the Federal Reserve to relax
its credit policy.
   Interest rates, which had been dropping in recent days on hopes
of some stimulus from the Fed, were mixed in today's credit-market
activity.
   In addition, the Bank of Japan raised its influential discount
rate from 3.25 percent to 3.75 percent.
   AMR dropped 3\ to 98[ in active trading on word that the company
was asking for legislation to help it ward off a takeover bid by
investor Donald Trump.
   Ramada Inc. fell 2] to 10~. The company said it wasn't
proceeding with a an offering of debt securities that had been
planned as part of a restructuring program.
   Gulf States Utilities, the most active Big Board issue, tumbled
2{ to 11}. A Louisiana judge rejected the company's attempt to
include $1.4 billion in costs associated with a nuclear power plant
in its electric rates.
   Losers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, down | at
44|; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down { at 42{; International
Paper, down ~ at 54~, and International Business Machines, down {
at 107}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.55 to 197.45. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 1.93 at 395.10.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 136.26 million shares with an
hour to go.
