<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-11 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained more ground Wednesday against
most major foreign currencies despite heavy selling by central
banks and a surprise hike in the Japanese discount rate.
   Gold prices rose after falling slightly overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $362 a troy ounce, a $1 increase from Tuesday.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold at
$361.50 an ounce, up 50 cents.
   Currency dealers said the dollar initially fell after the Bank
of Japan announced it would hike its discount rate _ the interest
rate charged to member banks _ to 3.75 percent from 3.25 percent.
   But the dollar soon shrugged off that unexpected news as well as
reports of widespread intervention by the Federal Reserve, the Bank
of Japan and several European central banks, they said.
   ``All rabbits have been pulled out of the hat and the dollar
still isn't going down,'' said a senior dealer at a U.S. investment
bank in London.
   Another European dealer said the central bank dollar-selling was
effective only in ``taking the sting out of what looked to be a
fairly vicious upward move.''
   J. Thomas Stanley, manager of corporate foreign exchange for
Chemical New York Capital Markets Group, said the dollar was being
supported by the belief that U.S. interest rates would hold steady.
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan hinted during a meeting in Moscow on
Tuesday that rates would stay firm in the near term regardless of
the currency's movements. He expressed concern that ``attempts to
maintain unrealistic exchange rates may lead to destabilizing
international capital flows ...''
   Those remarks helped push the dollar sharply higher in Tuesday
trading, since firmer interest rates tend to support a currency.
   Stanley predicted that ``without a rate cut by the Fed ... the
dollar is not going to come off.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.67 yen from Monday to close at 143.90
yen. Tokyo's markets were closed Tuesday for a national holiday.
The yen was quoted at 144.50 yen in London, and 144.50 yen in New
York, unchanged.
   The British pound continued to lose ground against the dollar.
It cost $1.5425 for one pound in London, cheaper than $1.5580 late
Tuesday. Sterling fetched $1.5460 in New York, down from $1.5520.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9155 West German marks, up from 1.9083; 6.4900
French francs, up from 6.4655; 1.6800 Swiss francs, up from 1.6670;
1.17475 Canadian dollars, down from 1.17625; and 1,402.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,394.875.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Tuesday's rates,
included: 1.9185 West German marks, up from 1.8965; 1.6785 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6545; 6.4925 French francs, up from 6.4300;
2.1630 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1290; 1.1750 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1735; and 1,403.25 Italian lire, up from 1,382.40.
   Gold fell in London to $361.25 an ounce from late Tuesday's
$362. In Zurich, gold closed at $361.50 an ounce, down from $362.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 0.72 cents to close at $362.36
an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.076 a troy ounce from $5.03
Tuesday. Silver fell in London to $5.05 an ounce from $5.06.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
