<FIRST>d f BC-CalFed     10-11 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CalFed,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parent of Big Thrift Sells Insurance Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CalFed Inc., parent of the nation's
fourth-largest thrift, said Wednesday it was getting out of the
property casualty business by selling its London-based Anglo
American Insurance Co. Ltd.
   Anglo American is being purchased by an affiliate of John Head &amp;
Partners LP, a New York-based merchant banking firm specializing in
insurance.
   Terms of the deal were not announced, but CalFed said the sale
price was about $100 million.
   The sale must be approved by the British Trade and Industry
Department.
   CalFed, which spent $80 million to set up Anglo American in
April 1987, said it expects the insurer to earn about $9 million in
1989 compared to $3.9 million in 1988.
   CalFed, whose principle subsidiary is the big California Federal
Bank savings and loan, announced in January that it had sold CalFed
Insurance Syndicate Inc., its other property-casualty insurance
subsidiary.
</TEXT>
