<DOCNO> AP891011-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-CBS     10-11 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-CBS,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fall 11 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. reported a 11 percent decline in
third-quarter earnings Wednesday, primarily because a severe drop
in income from joint ventures offset gains in television
advertising.
   The network said it earned $61.8 million or $2.40 a share in the
three months ended Sept. 30, compared with $69.8 million or $2.72 a
share in the year-earlier period. Third-quarter sales totaled
$593.5 million vs. $568 million, a 4 percent increase.
   CBS attributed most of the earnings drop to an 82.6 percent
decline in third-quarter income from CBS-Fox, a joint venture
between CBS and Twentieth Century Fox that markets and distributes
home videcassettes. CBS said it earned $1.2 million from the joint
venture in the period, vs. $6.9 million a year ago.
   President and Chief Executive Officer Laurence A. Tisch said
that despite the decline, the company's key television operations
were performing well, helped by gains in ad income, no unusual
disruptions to the fall season, and lower costs from the absence of
presidential campaign coverage this year.
   ``With a robust advertising market and better ratings over last
year's strike-disrupted program schedule, the Television Network is
expected to show imrpoved results for the balance of the year,''
Tisch said.
   For the first nine months of 1989, CBS said it earned $236.9
million or $9.21 a share, a 3 percent decline from the $243.3
million or $9.46 million a share earned in the year-earlier period.
Sales totaled $2.1 billion vs. $2.0 billion, a 5 percent increase.
   If discontinued operations from 1988 are included in the
figures, earnings for the first nine months of 1989 would have
fallen 79 percent from a year earlier, when company earnings were
inflated by $866.6 million from the sale of its records subsidiary
to Sony Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
