<DOCNO> AP891011-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 1715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TWA Bjt   10-11 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TWA, Bjt,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rumors, Questions Swirl Around Icahn's Plans for TWA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When you have an airline for sale, who do you
call? Don't ask Carl Icahn.
   Icahn, the takeover specialist who completed his $1.2 billion
buyout of Trans World Airlines Inc. last year, has been rumored for
several months to be looking to unload the airline through a sale
or merger or another kind of management change.
   TWA employees have heard through the grapevine that Icahn has
talked with other major airlines, other takeover experts, even St.
Louis-based corporate giants Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc. and McDonnell
Douglas Corp.
   The brewer and the aircraft maker often are approached to help
bail out local companies and institutions. TWA could fit nicely
with McDonnell Douglas, the world's second-largest builder of
commercial jets after Boeing Co.
   Icahn also had expressed interest some months ago in strikebound
Eastern Airlines, hinting at a possible merger between Eastern and
TWA.
   The latest speculation comes against a background of takeover
fever sweeping the nation's airline industry. An investor group
recently acquired Northwest Airlines parent NWA Inc. for $3.65
billion, while a pilot-management coalition is trying to buy UAL
Corp., United Airlines' parent, for $6.75 billion. Just last week,
developer Donald Trump made a record $7 billion offer for AMR
Corp., which owns American Airlines _ the nation's largest and most
profitable.
   Mark Buckstein, TWA's general counsel at its corporate
headquarters in Mt. Kisco, N.Y., declined comment Wednesday on the
rumors concerning Icahn.
   ``No Mr. Right has come out of the woodwork,'' said Morten
Beyer, chairman of Avmark Inc., an aviation consulting firm based
in Arlington, Va. ``I would say there certainly hasn't been a
stampede to buy TWA.''
   But Beyer and other analysts said it's clear that something
needs to be done to help TWA, which began this decade as the
nation's second-largest airline and is now near the bottom of the
list of majors.
   Will TWA end up as part of an airline merger?
   Mark Daugherty, an airline analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in New York, said he doesn't think so.
   ``I don't think the government would allow it,'' Daugherty said.
``The USAir-Piedmont merger barely squeaked by and I don't see a
TWA merger with a major carrier making it.''
   If it's not another airline, then it's anybody's guess what will
happen.
   TWA workers are just hoping something happens soon. The waiting
is becoming unbearable, said Herb Johnson, president of the
Machinists union's Local 1650.
   ``It's a tremendous amount of stress on our people. The anxiety
is growing,'' said Johnson, who's based in Kansas City, Mo., where
TWA has a large maintenance facility.
   ``Our people are trying to plan vacations, or trying to figure
out whether to buy a new car, just like everyone else in America,''
Johnson said. ``But we can't do anything because we don't know if
we'll have a job when we wake up.''
   The rumors have been passed around the workplace for so long, he
said, that nobody knows what to expect.
   ``It's really become a joke,'' Johnson said.
   Analysts say several major problems have contributed to the
decline of TWA and are probably also keeping suitors from rushing
to buy the airline.
   Chief among the troubles are financial woes.
   Through the first half of the year, TWA reported losses of $87.5
million, while many of the nation's other major carriers have been
posting record profits.
   The company, which Icahn took private last October, also has to
repay $400 million in interest payments this year and has $1.7
billion in principal and interest payments coming due in later
years.
   The airline also has a fairly dissatisfied workforce.
   Johnson said TWA aircraft mechanics haven't received a raise in
five years, while ticket agents and reservation clerks are being
paid the same amount they were in 1980.
   The 16,000 TWA employees in the Machinists union have been
working under a contract that expired last October. The airline's
pilots, among the lowest paid among major carriers, are continuing
a lawsuit challenging the manner in which Icahn took the company
private.
   The pilots lost the suit in New York Supreme Court and have
appealed that decision, according to David Berkeley, a spokesman
for the TWA pilots.
   Another big concern is the age of TWA's fleet, the second-oldest
among major U.S. carriers. The company has ordered 40 new planes
from Europe's Airbus Industrie, but the first shipment of 20 of
those jets won't be ready until 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
