<FIRST>r f AM-Harley-Davidson     10-11 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Harley-Davidson,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glazer Group Seeks Clearance To Increase Harley-Davidson Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by businessman Malcolm I. Glazer
said Wednesday it had requested federal permission to increase its
stake in the motorcycle manufacturer Harley-Davidson Inc. to 15
percent.
   The investor group said in a statement issued at its Rochester,
N.Y. headquarters that it was still studying ``a full range of
options'' regarding its stake in Harley, the last remaining U.S.
maker of motorcycles.
   The group currently holds 6.24 percent of Harley's stock.
   There has been speculation that Glazer, who has made takeover
bids for other companies in the past, might launch a bid for Harley.
   Harley responded to Wednesday's announcement by reiterating its
intention to remain independent.
   ``The company is not for sale,'' spokeswoman Katherine Holaday
said from Harley's Milwaukee office.
   She said Harley has had no contact from Glazer or his group, and
she added, ``I think at this point any speculation about (a
possible takeover bid) would certainly be premature.''
   Harley stock was unchanged at $40.75 a share in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading Wednesday.
   Glazer's group announced on Oct. 2 it had accumulated 6.24
percent of Harley stock. Under federal law, an investor must apply
for clearance from the Federal Trade Commission to acquire a stake
of 15 percent or more in a company.
   Last year, Glazer bought 9.9 percent of Formica Corp.'s stock
and offered to buy the entire company. His overtures were rejected
and a management-led group subsequently took Formica private.
   Glazer is chairman of First Allied Corp., which he said has
interests in more than 30 companies in 12 states, including
television stations, real estate, health care and banking. He said
the company has assets of more than $200 million.
</TEXT>
