<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2029EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Baker Adv15   10-11 1153</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Baker, Adv 15,1194</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Union Leader in Boeing Strike Criticized as Too Cozy With Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his dapper suits, executive salary and swank
office equipped with a kitchen and shoe-polish machine, Tom Baker
seems an unlikely leader of the knock-down, drag-out machinists
strike against Boeing Co.
   Since becoming president of District Lodge 751, International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers in 1980, Baker has
been criticized by dissidents in the aerospace giant's largest
union for what they call his coziness with management.
   At age 52, a rural Arkansas native who went from seaman to
Boeing electronics technician before making organized labor his
career, he was far from itching to strike.
   Nonetheless, he recommended rejection of a three-year contract
matching or exceeding most major recent settlements nationally. A
strike was approved on an 85 percent vote Oct. 3.
   ``Sometimes it takes a strike to get what you want, but if there
is a long strike, some people can wind up suffering,'' Baker said.
``That's the part I don't like.''
   The offer included 4 percent raises the first year and 3 percent
in each of the next two years, productivity bonuses of 8 percent of
gross pay the first year and 3 percent the second year, less
mandatory overtime and more benefits.
   Union members, whose tasks range from riveting to delicate
instrument calibrations, were making $17,534 to $37,377 a year
before the strike.
   Doug Hammond, a federal mediator who assisted in pre-strike
contract negotiations, couldn't predict the outcome of the strike
vote by 40,000 union members. Baker was certain.
   ``He really has a feel for the people he represents,'' Hammond
said.
   Dissident Franklin E. Knowles, 51, a toolmaker and 24-year union
member from Everett, Wash., emphasized that despite his criticisms
of Baker, ``I never said he was stupid.''
   Baker's predecessor, Albert Wydick, led the last strike against
Boeing, a 45-day walkout in 1977. In 1980 Wydick withdrew from an
election battle with Baker in exchange for a better paying, less
stressful union job.
   ``I do not believe he had the basic abilities that Tom Baker has
... the savvy, the intelligence,'' Knowles said.
   Favoring natty three-piece suits, sporting an impeccably trimmed
mustache and carefully coiffed silver hair, soft-spoken and
cautious, Baker was the first to win three consecutive terms of
what is now the largest of IAM's 162 district lodges without a
ballot opponent.
   ``I think he really typifies the local leadership'' of the
Machinists nationwide, said Machinists president George Kourpias.
   ``He's a good administrator,'' Kourpias said. ``He's also a good
leader. He has brought some stability to that district lodge.''
   Critics say Baker has artfully ensured that only his supporters
were elected to the District Council. Only council members, chosen
from the district's seven locals, may run for president.
   Tom Finnegan, a machine operator and 35-year Boeing employee in
Auburn, Wash., who lost his District Council seat to a Baker
supporter, said the president would have lost had he faced ballot
opposition.
   Even with the strike, Finnegan said, ``a lot of people figure
he's just too cozy with the company.''
   Anti-Baker leaflets circulated through Boeing plants last year
titled ``Truth Not Trivia'' zeroed in on a 17.5 percent increase in
base salary for Baker in 1987, lavish travel spending and the $9.4
million spent on ``Baker's Taj Mahal,'' a brick-and-glass edifice
featuring a soaring glass atrium that opened in July a few blocks
from Boeing headquarters.
   The president's suite includes a fully equipped kitchen, a
conference table and easel, a row of model Boeings on a shelf, an
electric rotary shoe buffer, couch, easy chairs and coffee table.
   Baker, who received $75,343 in salary and per diem and $27,546
for expenses last year for a total compensation of $102,889,
dismissed critics as petty carpers ``who don't stand for
something.''
   The building replaced a 40-year-old cramped and outmoded union
hall, and an image of ``permanence and strength'' was essential, he
asserted.
   Rarely does Baker raise his voice, even at times like a visit to
the picket line outside Boeing headquarters the day the strike
began.
   Wearing a blue union sweatshirt over jeans and white athletic
shoes, he waved his picket sign high, grinning.
   As head of the 43,300 Boeing machinists in the Seattle area _
nearly four-fifths of the 57,800 workers represented by the union
nationwide _ Baker has visited the picket lines daily.
   He has a Boeing family. Two sons, ages 30 and 28, are on strike,
as is his 25-year-old daughter and two of their spouses. The
younger son's wife, a salaried employee at Boeing, remains on the
job.
   In even tones bearing unmistakeable traces of the Ozark
Mountains, Baker described a rural childhood of hardship.
   He was born in Harrison, Ark., but the family moved to the
Bakersfield, Calif., area when he was young. His father worked on
irrigation systems and picked cotton. Baker later joined his father
in the fields, cramming in schoolwork between seasons.
   In about the fifth or sixth grade, he contracted rheumatic fever
and the family returned to Arkansas because his parents thought it
would improve his health. He later completed high school there and
joined the Navy.
   ``When they said, `We'll give you a free airplane ticket,' I
said, `I'm yours,'' he recalled.
   After four years at sea, where he began working with
electronics, he found work at Boeing, mostly dealing with ballistic
missile circuitry and control systems.
   ``The union was not something I had given any thought to, but I
happened to hit a shop that was well-organized ... with good,
strong exposure to union people,'' he said.
   In about 1959 he became a shop steward and eventually went on to
become a local president and a business representative.
   In his first campaign for district president, he joined a
groundswell of feeling that incumbent Wydick was weak.
   Three years later Baker clashed with Justin Ostro, an IAM vice
president who coordinates aerospace industry negotiations, over a
contract offer that _ for the first time _ sacrificed wage
increases in favor of bonuses.
   Ostro urged members to reject the contract. Baker said vote yes.
The members followed Baker.
   In 1986, despite a determined union effort to return to
increases in basic wage rates, a narrowly approved contract
provided only another round of bonuses.
   This year, citing an extensive survey showing 62 percent of
Boeing workers wanted wage gains, Baker made the issue a contract
demand.
   Kourpias dismissed Baker's past clashes with the international
leadership, or Grand Lodge and asserted hehad worked closely with
him ``from the day he was elected.''
   Kourpias also said Baker would be a strong candidate for a
higher position within the parent union, but Baker said he's not
interested.
   ``I think this job is really a better job than the vice
president's job in the (parent) union. Here I can make things
happen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
