<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-11 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Belly Market Surges As Supplies Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Frozen pork belly futures prices climbed sharply Wednesday on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, boosted by stronger cash markets,
shrinking supplies and bullish technical signals.
   On other commodity markets, livestock, energy and precious
metals were mostly higher while grain futures were mixed.
   Frozen pork bellies settled 1.10 cents to 1.22 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in February at 47.72 cents a pound. The
rally erased most of the losses piled up in the three previous
sessions.
   Pork belly prices have been recovering slowly since early
September after sliding to 18-year lows during the summer as
supplies piled up in warehouses, a function of declining
consumption of bacon, which is made from pork bellies.
   The government's decision to include pork bellies in food aid to
Poland helped get the market moving again last month, as did a drop
in retail bacon prices to levels that some consumers apparently
found irresistible.
   On Sept. 22, the Agriculture Department reported a record
45.4-million-pound drop in frozen pork belly stocks from Aug. 1 to
Sept. 1, to 50 million pounds. More recent statistics indicate the
stockpile continues to shrink.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange on Wednesday reported a
2.4-million-pound decline last week in bellies stored in warehouses
outside of Chicago.
   ``As much as anything, the bellies are getting energy from
fairly good out-movement,'' said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with
AgriVisor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Meanwhile, the dry, sunny weather of the past month has kept
many pork producers focused on harvesting corn and soybeans instead
of marketing hogs, temporarily reducing hog supplies and forcing
meatpackers to pay more for the animals and charge more for pork
products.
   This kink in the pork pipeline is a seasonal phenomenon but
``it's kind of extraordinary this year,'' Durchholz said, because
the harvesting weather has been unusually good.
   Another analyst, Dale Benson of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago, said the rally was also linked to technical buy signals,
especially the February contract's dip below 47 cents a pound,
which triggered large-scale buying.
   On the livestock markets, live cattle futures settled .10 cent
to .35 cent higher with October at 73.20 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .20 cent to .60 cent higher with October at 83.15 cents
a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to .40 cent higher with
October at 47.62 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices settled mostly higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in a session dominated by technical factors.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents lower to 8
cents higher with November at $20.25 a barrel; heating oil was .11
cent to .22 cent higher with November at 59.81 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .26 cent lower to .67 cent higher with
November at 55.73 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures were slightly higher while silver made substantial
gains on New York's Commodity Exchange. Analysts said silver was
due for a correction after sinking 23 cents an ounce in the last
four sessions.
   Gold finished 90 cents to $1 higher with October at $362 a troy
ounce; silver was 4.3 cents to 5 cents higher with December at
$5.143 a troy ounce.
   Most soybean and corn futures advanced slightly on the Chicago
Board of Trade as traders fine-tuned their positions ahead of
Thursday's Agriculture Department crop report.
   Most wheat futures posted modest losses, reflecting a lack of
new export demand.
   The USDA crop report, scheduled for release after Thursday's
close, is expected to indicate slightly larger corn and soybean
harvests than the USDA's September estimates of 1.89 billion
bushels of soybeans and 7.32 billion bushels of corn.
   Wheat futures settled 2} cents lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.04\ a bushel; corn futures
were \ cent to 1} cents higher with December at $2.35 a bushel;
oats were { cent lower to } cent higher with December at $1.40{ a
bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 3 cents higher with November at
$5.52\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
