<FIRST>u f AM-May-Caldor     10-11 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-May-Caldor,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>May Selling Caldor Chain To Investor Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. said Wednesday it has
sold its 118 Caldor discount stores to an investor group that
includes senior management and is spinning off its Venture discount
chain in order to concentrate on its higher-return and
faster-growing businesses.
   May, one of the nation's leading department store companies,
said Wednesday it had agreed to sell Caldor for $500 million cash
and $52 million in other considerations to CAL Holdings Inc.
   CAL Holdings is a new company formed by Odyssey Partners, L.P.;
Caldor management led by Don R. Clarke, chairman and chief
executive officer, Marc I. Balmuth, president, and others; and
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Capital Corp.
   CAL Holdings will assume $52 million in Caldor debt and
capitalized lease operations, May spokesman Jim Abrams said.
   Caldor is located primarily in the Northeast.
   May, which has been trying to sell its two discount operations
for several months, also announced a plan to spin off its Venture
division of 75 discount stores in eight states in the Midwest.
   Plans, which are subject to a favorable ruling by the Internal
Revenue Service, call for Venture to borrow money, which it then
would pay to May as compensation for separating itself from May.
   May would distribute stock in Venture to its shareholders,
Abrams said.
   ``We have done what we said we were going to do in late June,''
Abrams said. He said he could not place a dollar value on the
Venture spinoff.
   Analysts, however, estimate that the Venture move will raise
$300 million, which they expect May to use for further acquisitions
in the retail field.
   Linda Kristiansen of Dean Witter said she had expected the
Caldor and Venture moves to provide money for future expansion.
   ``I'm a little disappointed in the proceeds, which should total
$850 million,'' Kristiansen said. ``I expected it to come to about
$1.2 billion, but it doesn't change anything. Clearly, they'll be
in a position to make the ... acquisitions.''
   May said it does not currently have a specific use for the money
from the transactions, but it is considering adding more department
stores or specialty stores, repurchasing shares of its stock, or
using the money for other corporate purposes.
   Besides Caldor and Venture, May owns 14 department store chains
in 29 states and the District of Columbia and 2,663 Payless shoe
stores in the Northeast.
</TEXT>
