<FIRST>u f AM-P&amp;G-Artzt     10-11 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-P&amp;G-Artzt,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>P&amp;G's Chairman-to-be Discusses Goals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who will become Procter &amp; Gamble Co.'s
chairman on Jan. 2 said Wednesday he expects the company to win a
bigger share of international business and hopes employees increase
their stake in the company.
   ``We now think of ourselves as a world company. That's an
important cultural change for P&amp;G,'' said Edwin L. Artzt, who also
will assume the post of chief executive of the Cincinnati-based
company. ``We've discovered in the past 10 years that the product
strategies employed here really can work in other places around the
world.''
   P&amp;G says its employees, including retirees, own 24 percent of
the company's stock, much of it through profit-sharing programs.
Artzt said employee ownership, along with P&amp;G's financial health
and anti-takeover measures it has taken, can help guard against
takeover attempts.
   Artzt said P&amp;G would like to see its employees' holdings grow.
But, regarding concerns about takeovers, he said, ``I think the
best thing a company can do is satisfy its shareholders, and we're
trying to do that.''
   Artzt, 59, who joined Procter &amp; Gamble in 1953 and has spent the
past five years directing P&amp;G's international operations, said the
company hopes to do half its business in overseas markets at some
point during the 1990s. He told a news conference Wednesday he
thinks that goal could grow further.
   About 39 percent of P&amp;G's sales in the last fiscal year were
based outside the United States.
   P&amp;G announced to its shareholders' meeting Tuesday that Artzt
will take over Jan. 2 for John G. Smale, who will step down as
chairman and chief executive _ but continue as an employee and
director _ to spend more time with his family. Smale, 62, has been
with P&amp;G since 1952.
   Artzt said Smale first approached him with the idea early this
summer.
   ``I was pleasantly surprised,'' Artzt said. ``It was never my
expectation that John would step aside at this point, even though
some of our executives have done that.
   ``From my standpoint, it's quite a wonderful thing that he would
step aside and give me a chance to lead this company,'' Artzt said.
   John E. Pepper, 51, will continue as P&amp;G's president, but will
relinquish most of his responsibility for domestic operations in
return for succeeding Artzt as supervisor of international
operations. Artzt praised Pepper as a highly capable manager.
   ``I feel very good about having him in what I regard as the
second most important job in the company,'' Artzt said. He
suggested that Pepper could have a future shot at the chairman's
job.
   ``It's my time to step up to bat,'' Artzt said. ``John's in a
different generation than I am. He'll be around after my days are
over.''
   Artzt said he has no plans now to step aside early, as Smale is
doing.
   Artzt also said he expects to make no dramatic changes in the
company's direction.
   ``Our leader is stepping aside, but we intend to continue the
program that seems to be doing so well,'' Artzt said.
   Procter &amp; Gamble, a personal-care and home products company,
earned a company record $1.6 billion on record worldwide sales of
$21.4 billion in the fiscal year ended June 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
