<HEAD>Bank of New England Explores Selling Leasing Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New England Corp., citing unfavorable tax
laws and a desire to concentrate its business closer to home,
announced Wednesday it would discuss selling part of its leasing
business to the Bank of Tokyo.
   The bank said it had entered a preliminary agreement to
negotiate for a short period of time with the Bank of Tokyo.
   The Bank of New England said in a statement that no final
agreement has been reached, and any further comments would be
inappropriate.
   The company said it is contemplating the sale because federal
tax law changes have made the leasing business less attractive, and
because the bank's leasing business is concentrated outside New
England.
   The bank said it had adopted an earlier strategy to concentrate
resources in the New England region.
