<SECOND>BC-Beverly Enterprises,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Nursing Home Operator Continues Sale of Properties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beverly Enterprises Inc. announced
Wednesday that it has reached an agreement in principle to sell 18
of its nursing homes in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area for $32
million.
   The deal is the latest in a series begun early last year when
Beverly, the nation's largest owner of nursing homes, said it would
restructure by selling unprofitable businesses. The company has
been struggling with a nearly $1 billion load of debt.
   The Minnesota nursing homes, with a total of 1,998 beds, will be
sold to a group of investors who have retained Health Dimensions
Inc. of Cambridge, Minn., as managers. Beverly did not identify the
investors. The sale is expected to be completed later this year.
   Included in the $32 million is $14 million that Nationwide
Health Properties Inc. will receive for the sale of four homes that
are leased to Beverly.
   Once all its sales are completed, Beverly said its beds will
total 68,445, compared to 115,357 when the restructuring began.
   Beverly, the nation's largest owner of nursing homes, has a
workforce of more than 100,000 at facilities in 38 states and the
District of Columbia.
