<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-CPC     10-11 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-CPC,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Quarter Profit Increases 14 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD CLIFFS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CPC International Inc. reported
Wednesday that its earnings increased 14 percent in the third
quarter, due in part to growth in the company's consumer food and
corn refining businesses.
   Earnings rose to $87.2 million, or $1.13 a share, for the three
months ended Sept. 30 compared with $76.7 million, or 98 cents per
share, a year earlier.
   Worldwide sales increased 5.8 percent in the quarter to $1.29
billion from $1.22 billion in the period last year.
   ``We are very gratified by the earnings improvement achieved in
the third quarter especially in view of the fact that CPC's
European operations overcame the adverse effects of lower dollar
values of their currencies,'' chairman and chief executive officer
James. R. Eiszner said in a statement.
   For the first nine months of 1989, CPC's net income increased 15
percent to $238 million, or $3.05 per share, from $206.7 million,
or $2.62 a share, during the same nine-month period in 1988.
   Nine-month worldwide sales rose to $3.8 billion from $3.5
billion a year earlier.
   CPC's worldwide consumer foods business accounts for about 80
percent of the company's total sales. It is one of the largest
international food companies in the United States.
</TEXT>
