<SECOND>BC-Earns-Motorola,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola Reports Higher Third-Quarter Sales And Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. on Wednesday reported
higher sales and earnings for the third quarter compared to a year
ago.
   Earnings for the three months ending Sept. 30 totaled $89
million, or 69 cents a share, compared with $87 million, or 67
cents a share, a year earlier. Sales totaled $2.41 billion, up 20
percent from $2.01 billion in the same period of 1988.
   Nine-month earnings totaled $366 million, or $2.82 a share, up
from $321 million, or $2.48 a share, in the 1988 period. Sales for
the first nine months rose to $6.97 billion from $6.06 billion last
year.
   The 1989 figures reflect a pre-tax provision of about $43
million to cover anticipated costs of a voluntary severance program
announced earlier this month and a decrease in the estimated 1989
full-year tax rate, Motorola said in a statement.
   ``We are encouraged by the continuing strong demand for our
communications products, where we have had more than 40 years of
uninterrupted sales growth,'' said Chairman Robert W. Galvin.
   The company, based in this Chicago suburb, also reported an
increase in worldwide demand for its two-way radios, pagers and
radio data systems.
   New products introduced during the past three months included a
Wrist Watch Pager, which combines a numeric display pager with a
digital watch.
