<FIRST>r f AM-Toyota 1stLd-Writethru f0281 10-11 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toyota, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0281,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Plans to Increase North American Plant Capacity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Half of ...,' to CLARIFY that Toyota already
makes cars at the Fremont plant. Picks up 7th graf, `The plants' ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp.'s U.S. manufacturing capacity
must increase by two-thirds to meet American sales expectations, a
company official said Wednesday.
   The boost in capacity would come at time that other automakers
are struggling with too much factory capability.
   Ford Motor Co. is cutting back on overtime at its plants and
General Motors Corp. has announced that it will close its Lakewood
assembly plant in Atlanta this coming March.
   Chrysler Corp. has not ruled out plant closings.
   Bob McCurry, executive vice president for sales of Toyota Motor
Sales, USA Inc., said he expected the company would sell 1.5
million cars and trucks a year in the United States by the
mid-1990s.
   Half of that sales volume would come from North American plants.
Toyota makes cars at its plants in Georgetown, Ky., and Cambridge,
Ontario, and at a plant in Fremont, Calif., that it shares with GM.
Toyota plans to add light truck production to the Fremont plant by
next year.
   The plants' current capacity for Toyota is about 450,000
vehicles a year, meaning that capacity for another 300,000 vehicles
is needed.
   McCurry, speaking at Toyota's media introduction of its 1990
model cars and trucks, said production at existing plants could be
expanded to handle the extra 300,000, mostly through the Georgetown
and Fremont plants.
   ``It's possible,'' said analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc. of New York City. ``They are
going to do two things _ they are targeting the Midwest and the
fleet market. They can make a big move into that area.''
   A year ago, McCurry said the company was embarking on a program
to expand its dealer network in the Midwest, an area of the country
resistant to Japanese cars and trucks. On Wednesday, he said the
program was working.
   McCurry said there are about 1,125 Toyota dealers nationwide
now, and the company will have add 55 in the Midwest by year's end.
Another 55 are expected to be added in the region next year.
   McCurry said the company had established dealerships in most
Midwest metropolitan areas and was heading out of the cities to
find new dealers.
   Like other auto company executives, McCurry predicted a slower
sales year in 1990 than in 1989, with somewhere between 14 million
and 14.5 million cars and trucks being sold _ 500,000 to 1 million
fewer vehicles than estimates for the 1989 calendar year.
   He also said that 1990 Toyota prices would be 2.1 percent on
average more than 1989 prices. The increase, McCurry said, was due
entirely to federally mandated passive restraint systems _ driver's
side air bags or automatic seat belts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
