<FIRST>r f BC-MCorp-MVestment     10-11 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-MCorp-MVestment,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Holding Company Plans To Sell Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp, a troubled bank holding company, said
Wednesday it will sell its trust and investments subsidiary to an
Ohio-based banking company.
   MCorp said it agreed to sell MVestment Corp. to Cleveland-based
Ameritrust Corp. for a negotiated price of $120 million, including
$105 million in cash and a $15 million note.
   The board of directors of MCorp, which has been in Chapter 11
reorganization proceedings since March, approved the agreement and
will submit it for bankruptcy court approval. The sale also is
subject to regulatory approval.
   ``The decision to sell MVestment was based on our duty to
maximize the value of MCorp for the benefit of its creditors,
shareholders and other constituencies,'' Gene H. Bishop, MCorp's
chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
   ``We also believe that MVestment under Ameritrust will be in
excellent position to build further on its successful record.''
   Ameritrust owns regional banks in Ohio and Indiana and, through
its banking offices, operates trust departments across the country.
   Dallas-based MVestment, with 725 employees in 10 Texas cities,
reported pre-tax operating income of $13.7 million on $46 million
in revenues for the first nine months of this year.
   MVestment, which holds $17.1 billion in trust and custody
assets, consists of four operating companies: MTrust, MPetroleum,
MRealty and MSecurities.
   MCorp operates five MBanks in Brownsville, Corpus Christi, El
Paso, New Braunfels and Waco.
</TEXT>
