<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Zenith-Computers     10-11 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Zenith-Computers,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Introduces More Powerful Laptop Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Data Systems, the soon-to-be-sold
computer division of Zenith Electronics Corp., unveiled four new
personal computers Wednesday, including the industry's first
battery-powered laptop model based on the powerful Intel 80386SX
microprocessor.
   Zenith, the world's largest seller of battery-powered laptop
computers, said the new 12.1-pound SupersPort SX laptop _ which
weighs 16.8 pounds with its battery _ could operate for more than
three hours on the battery before it needs recharging.
   The model will be available with a 3.5-inch floppy disc drive
and either a 40 megabyte or 100 megabyte hard-disc drive at a
suggested retail price of about $6,800 and $7,400, respectively.
   Spokesman Matt Mirapaul said Japan's Toshiba and NEC also make
laptop-size computers based on the 386SX microprocessor but neither
runs on a battery.
   Glenview-based Zenith also introduced a desktop workstation
based on the 386SX microprocesser, a faster version of its
TurbosPort 386 laptop with an improved display and a faster version
of its SupersPort 286 laptop with improved display.
   Zenith announced Oct. 2 it had agreed to sell its computer
operations to France's Groupe Bull for up to $635 million.
   The sale will leave Zenith with its consumer electronics
business. Zenith is the last major U.S.-based television
manufacturer.
</TEXT>
